ency2.svg|23px|]]  [[Ibrahim Agha]]<br />\n[[File:AlgierRegency2.svg|23px|]]  [[Most\u00e9fa Boumezrag]]<br />\n[[Image:Drapeau_Ahmed_Bey_de_Constantine.svg|20px]] [[Ahmed Bey]]<br />\n[[Image:Drapeau_Ahmed_Bey_de_Constantine.svg|20px]] [[Ali ben A\u00efssa]]<br />\n[[Image:Flag of the Emirate of Mascara.svg|20px]] [[Emir Abdelkader al-Jazairi]]<br />\n[[Lalla Fatma N'Soumer]]<br />\n[[Image:Beni Abbas Kingdom2.svg|20px]]  [[Cheikh Mokrani]]<br />\n[[Image:Beni Abbas Kingdom2.svg|20px]] \n[[Boumezrag Mokrani]]<br />\n[[Image:Sultanat de touggourt.jpg|20px]] [[Soliman IV]]<br />\n[[Image:Flag of Kel Ahaggar.svg|20px]]  [[Mohammed ag Bessa]]<br />\n\n[[Cheikh Bouamama]]<br/>\n\n[[Cherif Boubaghla]]  '''Support :'''\n[[File:Flag of Morocco 1666 1915.svg|22px]] [[Abd al-Rahman of Morocco]]\n| strength1         = Invasion force:\n* 34,000 troops, 83 guns \n* 100 warships\n* 11 [[ships-of-the-line]]\n* 572 [[Cargo ship|merchantmen]]{{sfnp|Tucker|2009|p=1154}}<br/><br/>Ultimately:\n* 160,000 troops{{sfnp|Tucker|2009|p=1167}}\n| strength2         = Unknown\n| casualties1       = 150,000\u2013200,000 military losses <ref>Taking Power: On the Origins of Third World Revolutions, John Foran p94 [https://books.google.com/books?id=szJtXBrr2poC&pg=PA94]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=4nXl7h8i5scC&pg=PA43 The Making of Contemporary Algeria, 1830-1987 - Mahfoud Bennoune, p42]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=3Os5oDJGQYUC&pg=PA88 Law, Territory, and the Legal Geography of French Rule in Algeria, p87]</ref><ref>An Economic History of the Middle East and North Africa - Charles Issawi, p211 [https://books.google.com/books?id=lZ5TAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA211]</ref><ref>The Precarious Balance: State and Society in Africa- Donald S. Rothchild, Naomi H. Chazan - Westview Press, 1988 - 357 pages, p42 [https://books.google.com/books?id=10mNAAAAMAAJ&q=conquest+algeria+150,000+casualties&dq=conquest+algeria+150,000+casualties&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCMQ6AEwAWoVChMI2P_6xtywxwIVQ70UCh3QvgRI]</ref> <ref name=\"RothchildChazan1988\">{{cite book|last1=Rothchild|first1=Donald S.|last2=Chazan|first2=Naomi H.|title=The Precarious Balance: State and Society in Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=10mNAAAAMAAJ|year=1988|publisher=Westview Press|isbn=978-0-86531-738-3|page=42|ref= harv}}</ref>{{refn|group=notes|\"It has been calculated that between 1831 and 1851, 92,329 died in hospital, and only 3,336 in battle. The causes included diseases such as malaria and lack of medical care.\"<ref name=\"Greenhalgh2014\">{{cite book|last=Greenhalgh|first=Michael|title=The Military and Colonial Destruction of the Roman Landscape of North Africa, 1830-1900|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5pCfAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA366|year=2014|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-27163-0|page=366|ref= harv}}</ref>}}\n\nMore than 480,000 total death (civilians and soldiers in the 1830-1870 period)<ref>\"Urbain states in 1862 that the previous 32 years had killed, at a conservative estimate, over 480,000 people, not just soldiers.\" The Military and Colonial Destruction of the Roman Landscape of North Africa ... - Michael Greenhalgh, p. 366 [https://books.google.com/books?id=5pCfAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA366]</ref>\n| casualties2       = Unknown <ref>Kamel Kateb, Europ\u00e9ens, \"indig\u00e8nes\" et juifs en Alg\u00e9rie (1830-1962) : repr\u00e9sentations et r\u00e9alit\u00e9s des populations, INED, 2001, 386 p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=yEvQZ7bdybgC&pg=PA11]</ref><ref>Diana K. DAVIS, Les mythes environnementaux de la colonisation fran\u00e7aise au Maghreb, Paris, Editions Champ Vallon, 2007</ref><ref>[http://rh19.revues.org/4051 Bertrand Taithe, The 1866-1868 Famine in Algeria]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=01ERwhw78fwC&pg=PT61 Pour en finir avec la repentance coloniale, Daniel Lefeuvre]</ref>\n| campaignbox       = {{Campaignbox French conquest of Algeria}}\n{{Franco-Moroccan conflicts}}, and\n}}\n\nThe '''French conquest of Algeria''' took place between 1830 and 1857. In 1827, an argument between [[Hussein Dey]], the ruler of the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] [[Regency of Algiers]], and the French [[consul (representative)|consul]] escalated into a [[naval blockade]], following which [[July Monarchy|France]] invaded and quickly seized [[Algiers]] in 1830, and rapidly took control of other coastal communities. Amid internal political strife in France, decisions were repeatedly taken to retain control over the territory, and additional military forces were brought in over the following years to quell resistance in the interior of the country.\n\nAlgerian resistance forces were divided between forces under [[Ahmed Bey ben Mohamed Ch\u00e9rif]] at [[Constantine, Algeria|Constantine]], primarily in the east, and nationalist forces in [[Kabylie]] and the west. Treaties with the nationalists under [[Abd al-Qadir al-Jaza'iri|`Abd al-Q\u0101dir]] enabled the French to first focus on the elimination of the remaining Ottoman threat, achieved with the 1837 capture of Constantine. Abd Al-Q\u0101dir continued to give stiff resistance in the west. Finally driven into [[Morocco]] in 1842, by large-scale and heavy-handed French military action, he continued to wage a [[Guerrilla warfare|guerrilla war]] until the [[Moroccan government]], under French diplomatic pressure following its defeat in the [[First Franco-Moroccan War]], drove him out of Morocco. He surrendered to French forces in 1847.\n\n== Background information ==\n\nThe territory now known as [[Algeria]] was only partially under the [[Ottoman Empire]]'s control in 1830. The [[dey]] ruled the entire [[Regency of Algiers]], but only exercised direct control in and around [[Algiers]], with [[Bey]]liks established in a few outlying areas, including [[Oran]] and [[Constantine, Algeria|Constantine]]. The remainder of the territory (including much of the interior), while nominally Ottoman, was effectively under the control of local Arab leaders. The dey acted largely independently of the Ottoman Emperor, although he was supported by (or controlled by, depending on historical perspective) Turkish [[Janissary]] troops stationed in Algiers. The territory was bordered to the west by the [[Sultanate of Morocco]] and to the east by the Ottoman [[History of Ottoman-era Tunisia|Regency of Tunis]]. The western border, the {{ILL|Tafna|fr}} River, was particularly porous since there were shared tribal connections that crossed it.\n\nThe Regency of Algiers was one of the main bases of the [[Barbary pirate]]s and [[Barbary Slave Trade]]rs who attacked Christian ships and coastal settlements in the [[Mediterranean]] and North [[Atlantic (ocean)|Atlantic]]. Like the rest of the [[Barbary Coast]], the Regency of Algiers lived from the trade of slaves or goods captured from [[Europe]], [[United States|America]] and [[sub-Saharan Africa]]. The European powers bombarded Algiers on different occasions in retaliation and the United States provoked the [[Barbary Wars]] in order to put an end to Algerian privateering against Christian shipping.<ref>{{Cite news | first=Robert | last=Carver| title=Not so easy alliances: ''Two Faiths, One Banner: When Muslims Marched with Christians Across Europe\u2019s Battlegrounds'' |type= Book review | url=http://www.thetablet.co.uk/review/442| work= Tablet | location= | page= 24 | date=25 April 2009 |url-status= dead |archive-date= 29 June 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110629033728/http://www.thetablet.co.uk/review/442}}</ref>\n\nThe conquest of Algeria began in the last days of the [[Bourbon Restoration]] by [[Charles X of France]]. It aimed to put a definite end to Barbary privateering and increase the king's popularity among the French people, particularly in Paris, where many veterans of the [[Napoleonic Wars]] lived. Algerian slave trade and piracy immediately ceased after the French conquered Algiers.<ref>{{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Barbary Pirates}}</ref>\n\n=== Fan Affair ===\n<!-- This section is referenced in the Algeria article. Don't change the title without updating links. -->\nIn 1795\u201396, the French Republic contracted to purchase wheat for the French army from two Jewish merchants in Algiers, and Charles X was apparently uninterested in paying the Republic's debt. The merchants, who had debts to [[Hussein Dey]], the Ottoman ruler of Algiers, claimed inability to pay those debts until France paid its debts to them. The dey unsuccessfully negotiated with [[Pierre Deval (diplomat)|Pierre Deval]], the French consul, to rectify this situation, and suspected Deval of collaborating with the merchants against him, especially since the French government made no provision to pay the merchants in 1820.  Deval's nephew Alexandre, the consul in [[B\u00f4ne]], further angered the dey by fortifying French storehouses in B\u00f4ne and [[El Kala|La Calle]] despite prior agreements.{{sfnp|Abun-Nasr|1987|p=249}}\n\n[[File:Le coup d eventail 1827.jpg|thumb|left|The \"Fan Affair\", which escalated into the invasion.]]\nAfter a contentious meeting on 29 April 1827 in which Deval refused to provide satisfactory answers, the dey struck Deval with his [[fly-whisk]] (then called a [[Hand fan|fan]]). Charles X used this slight against his diplomatic representative to first demand an apology from the dey, and then to initiate a blockade against the port of Algiers. The blockade lasted for three years, and was primarily to the detriment of French merchants who were unable to do business with Algiers, while Barbary pirates were still able to evade the blockade.  When France in 1829 sent an ambassador to the dey with a proposal for negotiations, he responded with cannon fire directed toward one of the blockading ships. The French then decided that more forceful action was required.{{sfnp|Abun-Nasr|1987|p=250}}\n\nFollowing the failure of the ambassador's visit, Charles appointed as President [[Jules, Prince de Polignac]], a hardline conservative. This outraged the liberal French opposition, which then had a majority in the [[Chamber of Deputies of France|Chamber of Deputies]]. Polignac opened negotiations with [[Muhammad Ali of Egypt]] to essentially divide up North Africa. Ali, although nominally a vassal of the Ottomans, eventually rejected this idea. As popular opinion continued to rise against Polignac and the King, they decided that a foreign policy victory such as the capture of Algiers would turn opinion in their favour again.{{sfnp|Ruedy|2005|p=47}}\n\n==Invasion of Algiers==\n{{main|Invasion of Algiers in 1830}}\n[[Image:D\u00e9barquement en Alg\u00e9rie 09665.jpg|thumb|At Sidi-Ferruch by [[Pierre-Julien Gilbert]].]]\n[[File:Bombardementd alger-1830.jpg|thumb|The attack of [[Admiral Duperr\u00e9]] during the taking of Algiers in 1830.]]\n[[File:Ottoman cannon end of 16th century length 385cm cal 178mm weight 2910 stone projectile founded 8 October 1581 Alger seized 1830.jpg|thumb|Ornate [[Ottoman weapons|Ottoman cannon]], length: 385cm, cal:178mm, weight: 2910, stone projectile, founded 8 October 1581 in Algiers, seized by France at Algiers in 1830. [[Mus\u00e9e de l'Arm\u00e9e]], Paris.]]\n\n[[Admiral Duperr\u00e9]] took command in [[Toulon]] of an armada of 600 ships and then headed for Algiers. Following a plan for the invasion of Algeria originally developed under [[Napoleon]] in 1808, [[General de Bourmont]] then landed 34,000 soldiers {{convert|27|km|mi}} west of Algiers, at [[Sidi Ferruch]], on 14 June 1830. To face the French, the dey sent 7,000 [[Janissary|janissaries]], 19,000 troops from the beys of Constantine and Oran, and about 17,000 [[Kabyles]].{{sfnp|Ruedy|2005|p=48}} The French established a strong beachhead and pushed toward Algiers, thanks in part to superior artillery and better organization. On 19 June the French defeated the dey's army at the battle of [[Staou\u00e9li]], and entered Algiers on 5 July after a three-week campaign.{{sfnp|Ruedy|2005|p=49}} The dey accepted capitulation in exchange for his freedom and the offer to retain possession of his personal wealth. Five days later, he went into exile in [[Naples]] with his family. The Turkish Janissaries also quit the territory, leaving for Turkey.<ref name=R50>{{harvp|Ruedy|2005|p=50}}</ref> The dey's departure ended 313 years of Ottoman rule of the territory.\n\nWhile the French command had nominally agreed to preserve the liberties, properties, and religious freedoms of the inhabitants, French troops immediately began plundering the city, arresting and killing people for arbitrary reasons, seizing property, and desecrating religious sites. By mid-August, the last remnants of Turkish authority were summarily deported without opportunity to liquidate significant assets.<ref name=R50/> One estimate indicates that more than fifty million francs in assets were diverted into private hands during the plunder.{{sfnp|Ruedy|2005|p=52}} This activity had a profound effect on future relations between the French occupiers and the natives.  A French commission in 1833 wrote that \"we have sent to their deaths on simple suspicion and without trial people whose guilt was always doubtful ... we massacred people carrying safe conducts ... we have outdone in barbarity the barbarians\".<ref name=R50/>  One important side effect of the expulsion of the Turks was that it created a power vacuum in significant parts of the territory, from which resistance to French occupation immediately began to arise.{{sfnp|Wagner|1854|p=235}}\nThe methods used to establish French hegemony reached [[Genocide|genocidal proportions]] and war, famine and disease led to the death of between 500,000 and 1 million of an estimated 3 million Algerians.<ref>{{cite book |first= Dominik J. |last= Schaller |editor1-first= Donald |editor1-last= Bloxham |editor2-first= A. Dirk |editor2-last= Moses |chapter-url= https://books.google.com/books?id=bEcTDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA356 |title= The Oxford Handbook of Genocide Studies |publisher= Oxford University Press |date= 2010 |page= 356 |chapter= Genocide and Mass Violence in the 'Heart of Darkness': Africa in the Colonial Period |isbn= 978-0-19-923211-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Jalata|first=Asafa|title=Phases of Terrorism in the Age of Globalization: From Christopher Columbus to Osama bin Laden|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SCjxCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA92|date=2016|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan US|isbn=978-1-137-55234-1|pages=92\u20133|ref= harv}}</ref><ref name=\"Kiernan2007\">{{cite book|last=Kiernan|first=Ben|authorlink=Ben Kiernan|title=Blood and Soil: A World History of Genocide and Extermination from Sparta to Darfur|url=https://archive.org/details/bloodan_kie_2007_00_0326|url-access=registration|year=2007|publisher=[[Yale University Press]]|isbn=0-300-10098-1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/bloodan_kie_2007_00_0326/page/364 364]\u2013ff}}</ref>\n\nHardly had the news of the capture of Algiers reached Paris than Charles X was deposed during the [[Three Glorious Days]] of July 1830, and his cousin [[Louis-Philippe of France|Louis-Philippe]], the \"citizen king\", was named to preside over a [[July Monarchy|constitutional monarchy]]. The new government, composed of [[French liberalism|liberal opponents]] of the Algiers expedition, was reluctant to pursue the conquest begun by the old regime.  However, the victory was enormously popular, and the new government of Louis-Philippe only withdrew a portion of the invasion force.  General Bourmont, who had sent troops to occupy B\u00f4ne and Oran, withdrew them from those places with the idea of returning to France to restore Charles to the throne.  When it was clear that his troops were not supportive of this effort, he resigned and went into exile in Spain.  Louis-Philippe replaced him with [[Bertrand Clauzel]] in September 1830.\n\nThe bey of Titteri, who had participated in the battle at Staou\u00e9li, attempted to coordinate resistance against the French with the beys of Oran and Constantine, but they were unable to agree on leadership.  Clauzel in November led a French column of 8,000 to [[M\u00e9d\u00e9a]], Titteri's capital, losing 200 men in skirmishes.  After leaving 500 men at [[Blida]] he occupied M\u00e9d\u00e9a without resistance, as the bey had retreated.  After installing a supportive bey and a garrison, he returned toward Algiers.  On arrival at Blida, he learned that the garrison there had been attacked by the Kabyles, and in resisting them, had killed some women and children, causing the town's population to rise against them.  Clauzel decided to withdraw that garrison as the force returned to Algiers.{{sfnp|Wagner|1854|pp=237-9}}\n\n==Colonization begins==\n[[File:Alg\u00e9rie fr.jpg|thumb|1877 map of the three French departments of Alger, Oran and Constantine]]\n[[File:French Algeria evolution 1830-1962 map-fr.svg|thumb|Chronological map of the French conquest.]]\nClauzel introduced a formal civil administration in Algiers, and began recruiting [[zouave]]s, or native auxiliaries to the French forces, with the goal of establishing a proper colonial presence.  He and others formed a company to acquire agricultural land and to subsidize its settlement by European farmers, triggering a [[land run|land rush]]. Clauzel recognized the farming potential of the [[Mitidja Plain]] and envisioned the production there of [[cotton]] on a large scale. During his second term as governor general (1835&ndash;36), he used his office to make private investments in land and encouraged army officers and bureaucrats in his administration to do the same. This development created a vested interest among government officials in greater French involvement in Algeria. Commercial interests with influence in the government also began to recognize the prospects for profitable land speculation in expanding the French zone of occupation. Over a ten-year period they created large agricultural tracts, built factories and businesses, and bought cheap local labor.\n\nClauzel also attempted to extend French influence into Oran and Constantine by negotiating with the bey of Tunis to supply \"local\" rulers that would operate under French administration.  The bey refused, seeing the obvious conflicts inherent in the idea.  The French foreign ministry objected to negotiations Clauzel conducted with Morocco over the establishment of a Moroccan bey in Oran, and in early 1831 replaced him with [[Pierre Berthe\u00e9ne, Baron Berthez\u00e8ne|Baron Berthez\u00e8ne]].\n\nBerthez\u00e8ne was a weak administrator opposed to colonisation.{{sfnp|Wagner|1854|p= 240}}  His worst military failure came when he was called to support the bey at M\u00e9d\u00e9a, whose support for the French and corruption had turned the population there against him. Berthez\u00e8ne led troops to M\u00e9d\u00e9a in June 1831 to extract the bey and the French garrison.  On their way back to Algiers they were continually harassed by Kabyle resistance, and driven into a panicked retreat that Berthez\u00e8ne failed to control.  French casualties during this retreat were significant (nearly 300), and the victory fanned the flames of resistance, leading to attacks on colonial settlements.{{sfnp|Wagner|1854|pp= 241-3}} The growing colonial financial interests began insisting on a stronger hand, which Louis-Philippe provided in [[Anne Jean Marie Ren\u00e9 Savary|Duke Rovigo]] at the end of 1831.\n\nRovigo regained control of [[B\u00f4ne]] and Bougie (present-day [[B\u00e9ja\u00efa]]), cities that Clauzel had taken and then lost due to resistance by the [[Kabyle people]]. He continued policies of colonisation of the land and expropriation of properties.  His suppression of resistance in Algiers was brutal, with the military presence extended into its neighborhoods.  He was recalled in 1833 due to the overtly violent nature of the repression, and replaced by [[Th\u00e9ophile Voirol, Baron Voirol|Baron Voirol]].  Voirol successfully established French occupation in Oran, and another French general, [[Louis Alexis Desmichels]], was given an independent command that gained control over [[Arzew]] and [[Mostaganem]].\n\nOn 22 June 1834, France formally annexed the occupied areas of Algeria, which had an estimated Muslim population of about two million, as a military [[colony]].  The colony was run by a military governor who had both civilian and military authority, including the power of executive decree. His authority was nominally over an area of \"limited occupation\" near the coast, but the realities of French colonial expansion beyond those areas ensured continued resistance from the local population.  The policy of limited occupation was formally abandoned in 1840 for one of complete control.\n\nVoirol was replaced in 1834 by [[Jean-Baptiste Drouet, Comte d'Erlon]], who became the first governor of the colony, and who was given the task of dealing with the rising threat of [[Abd al-Qadir al-Jaza'iri|`Abd al-Q\u0101dir]] and continuing French failures to subdue [[Ahmed Bey]], Constantine's ruler.\n\n==Rise of Abdul Kader==\n{{unreferenced section|date=June 2013}}\nThe superior of a religious brotherhood, [[Muhyi ad Din]], who had spent time in Ottoman jails for opposing the bey's rule, launched attacks against the French and their [[makhzen]] allies at Oran in 1832. In the same year, tribal elders in the territories near [[Mascara, Algeria|Mascara]] chose Muhyi ad Din's son, twenty-five-year-old `Abd al-Q\u0101dir, to take his place leading the [[jihad]]. Abd al-Q\u0101dir, who was recognized as [[Amir al-Muminin]] (commander of the faithful), quickly gained the support of tribes in the western territories.  In 1834 he concluded a [[Treaty of Desmichels|treaty with General Desmichels]], who was then military commander of the province of Oran.  In the treaty, which was reluctantly accepted by the French administration, France recognized Abd al-Q\u0101dir as the sovereign of territories in Oran province not under French control, and authorized Abd al-Q\u0101dir to send consuls to French-held cities.  The treaty did not require Abd al-Q\u0101dir to recognize French rule, something glossed over in its French text.  Abd al-Q\u0101dir used the peace provided by this treaty to widen his influence with tribes throughout western and central Algeria.\n\nWhile d'Erlon was apparently unaware of the danger posed by Abd al-Q\u0101dir's activities, General [[Camille Alphonse Tr\u00e9zel]], then in command at Oran, did see it, and attempted to separate some of the tribes from Abd al-Q\u0101dir.  When he succeeded in convincing two tribes near Oran to acknowledge French supremacy, Abd al-Q\u0101dir dispatched troops to move those tribes to the interior, away from French influence.  Tr\u00e9zel countered by marching a column of troops out from Oran to protect the territory of those tribes on 16 June 1835.  After exchanging threats, Abd al-Q\u0101dir withdrew his consul from Oran and ejected the French consul from Mascara, a ''de facto'' declaration of war.  The two forces clashed in a bloody but inconclusive engagement near the [[Sig River]].  However, when the French, who were short on provisions, began withdrawing toward Arzew, Abd al-Q\u0101dir led 20,000 men against the beleaguered column, and in the [[Battle of Macta]] routed the force, killing 500 men.  The debacle led to the recall of Comte d'Erlon.\n\nGeneral Clausel was appointed a second time to replace d'Erlon.  He led an attack against [[Mascara, Algeria|Mascara]] in December of that year, which Abd al-Q\u0101dir, with advance warning, had evacuated.  In January 1836 Clausel occupied [[Tlemcen]], and established a garrison there before return to Algiers to plan an attack against [[Constantine, Algeria|Constantine]].  Abd al-Q\u0101dir continued to harry the French at Tlemcen, so additional troops under [[Thomas Robert Bugeaud]], a veteran of the [[Napoleonic Wars]] who was experienced in irregular warfare, were sent from Oran to secure control up to the [[Tafna]] River and to resupply the garrison.  Abd al-Q\u0101dir retreated before Bugeaud, but decided to make a stand on the banks of the [[Sikkak]] River.  On July 6, 1836, Bugeaud decisively defeated al-Q\u0101dir in the [[Battle of Sikkak]], losing less than fifty men to more than 1,000 casualties suffered by Abd al-Q\u0101dir.  The battle was one of the few formal battles al-Q\u0101dir engaged in; after this defeat he restricted his actions as much as possible to guerrilla-style attacks.\n\n==Constantine==\n[[File:Expeditionconstantine.jpg|thumb|[[Battle of Constantine]] in November 1836]]\nAhmed Bey had continuously resisted any attempts by the French or others to subjugate Constantine, and continued to play a role in resistance against French rule, in part because he hoped to eventually become the next dey.  Clausel and Ahmed had tangled diplomatically over Ahmed's refusal to recognize French authority over B\u00f4ne, which he considered to still be Ottoman territory, and Clausel decided to move against him.  In November 1836 Clausel led 8,700 men into the Constantine beylik, but was repulsed in the [[Battle of Constantine]]; the failure led to Clausel's recall.  He was replaced by [[Charles Marie Denys, comte de Damr\u00e9mont|the Comte de Damr\u00e9mont]], who led an expedition that successfully [[Capture of Constantine|captured Constantine]] the following year, although he was killed during the siege and replaced by [[Sylvain Charles Val\u00e9e|Sylvain Charles, comte Val\u00e9e]].\n\n==Abd Al-Q\u0101dir's resistance renewed==\n{{Main|Pacification of Algeria}}\n[[File:D\u00e9fense de Mazagran.jpg|thumb|[[Battle of Mazagran]] in 1840]]\n[[File:Bataille de sidi brahim 1845 26 septembre.jpg|thumb|[[Battle of Sidi Brahim]] in 1845]]\nIn May 1837, General [[Thomas Robert Bugeaud]], then in command of Oran, negotiated the [[Treaty of Tafna]] with Abd al-Q\u0101dir, in which he effectively recognized Abd al-Q\u0101dir's control over much of the interior of what is now Algeria. Abd Al-Q\u0101dir used the treaty to consolidate his power over tribes throughout the interior, establishing new cities far from French control. He worked to motivate the population under French control to resist by peaceful and military means.  Seeking to again face the French, he laid claim under the treaty to territory that included the main route between Algiers and Constantine.  When French troops contested this claim in late 1839 by marching through a mountain defile known as the Iron Gates, Abd al-Q\u0101dir claimed a breach of the treaty, and renewed calls for jihad.  Throughout 1840 he waged guerrilla war against the French in the provinces of Algiers and Oran.  Val\u00e9e's failures to end the war led to his replacement in December 1840 by General Bugeaud.\n\nBugeaud instituted a strategy of [[scorched earth]], combined with fast-moving cavalry columns not unlike those used by Abd al-Q\u0101dir to progressively take territory from Abd al-Q\u0101dir.  The troops' tactics were heavy-handed, and the population suffered significantly. Abd Al-Q\u0101dir was eventually forced to establish a mobile headquarters that was known as a ''smala'' or ''zmelah''.  In 1843 French forces successfully [[Battle of the Smala|raided this camp]] while he was away from it, capturing more than 5,000 fighters and Abd al-Q\u0101dir's warchest.\n\nAbd Al-Q\u0101dir was forced to retreat into Morocco, from which he had been receiving some support, especially from tribes in the border areas.  When French diplomatic efforts to convince Morocco to expel Abd al-Q\u0101dir failed, the French resorted to military means with the [[First Franco-Moroccan War]] in 1844 to compel the sultan to change his policy.\n\nEventually hemmed between French and Moroccan troops on the border in December 1847, Abd al-Q\u0101dir chose to surrender to the French, under terms that he be allowed to enter exile in the Middle East.  The French violated these terms, holding him in France until 1852, when he was allowed to go to [[Damascus]].\n\nThe Ottomans lodged a formal protest over the invasion of Algeria, but they never conceded the loss of the province. A map of \"Ottoman Africa\" from 1905 still shows the empire as possessing a border with Morocco to the west of the \"region\" (''hitta'', a term for a territory with vague borders) of Algeria.<ref name=\"Hanio\u011flu2010\">{{cite book|last=Hanio\u011flu|first=M. \u015e\u00fckr\u00fc|title=A Brief History of the Late Ottoman Empire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nK5ZDKf3JgkC|year=2010|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]|isbn=1-4008-2968-2|pages=9\u201310, 69|ref= harv}}</ref>\n\n{{wide image|Prise de la smalah d Abd-El-Kader a Taguin 16 mai 1843 Horace Vernet.jpg|800px|''[[Battle of the Smala|Capture of the Smala of Abd El-Kader]], 16 May 1843'' by [[Horace Vernet]]}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|title=A history of the Maghrib in the Islamic period|first=Jamil|last=Abun-Nasr|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year=1987|isbn=978-0-521-33767-0|ref= harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Greenhalgh|first=Michael|title=The Military and Colonial Destruction of the Roman Landscape of North Africa, 1830-1900|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5pCfAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA366|year=2014|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-27163-0|ref= harv}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BOopmtvrsOAC&lpg=PA33&dq=Berthezene%20Rovigo&pg=PA34#v=onepage&q=Berthezene%20Rovigo&f=false|title=France Overseas: a Study of Modern Imperialism |first=Herbert Ingram |last=Priestley|publisher=Routledge|year=1966|isbn=978-0-7146-1024-5 |ref= harv}}\n*{{cite book|title=Modern Algeria: The Origins and Development of a Nation|first=John Douglas|last=Ruedy|year=2005|edition=2nd|publisher=[[Indiana University Press]]|location=Bloomington, Indiana|isbn=978-0-253-21782-0|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Tucker|first=Spencer C.|title=A Global Chronology of Conflict: From the Ancient World to the Modern Middle East: From the Ancient World to the Modern Middle East|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h5_tSnygvbIC|date= 2009|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-85109-672-5 |ref= harv}}\n*{{cite book|title=The Tricolor on the Atlas: or, Algeria and the French conquest|first=Moritz|last=Wagner|translator=Pulszky, Francis |publisher=T. Nelson and Sons|year=1854|location=London|url=https://archive.org/details/tricoloronatlaso00wagnrich|ref= harv}}\n\n{{Former French colonies}}\n{{French colonial campaigns}}\n\n[[Category:French Algeria]]\n[[Category:19th-century conflicts]]\n[[Category:Wars involving France]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Morocco]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:1830s in Algeria]]\n[[Category:1840s in Algeria]]\n[[Category:France\u2013Morocco relations]]\n[[Category:1830s conflicts]]\n[[Category:1840s conflicts]]\n", "name_user": "Whatever748", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed the date in the texts", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_conquest_of_Algeria"}
{"title_page": "Indian Ocean raid (1944)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict = Second Indian Ocean raid\n|partof = [[Pacific War]]\n|image = [[File:Aoba class cruiser;h97733.jpg|300px|alt=Black and white drawing of a World War II-era warship|U.S. Navy recognition drawing for Japanese Aoba-class heavy cruisers]]\n|caption =U.S. Navy recognition drawing for Japanese ''Aoba''-class heavy cruisers\n|date = 1\u201316 March 1944\n|place = [[Indian Ocean]]\n|coordinates =\n|map_type =\n|latitude =\n|longitude =\n|map_size =\n|map_caption =\n|territory =\n|result = inconclusive\n|status =\n|combatant1 = {{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|combatant2 = {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|commander1 = {{flagicon|Empire of Japan|naval}} Rear Admiral [[Naomasa Sakonju]]\n|commander2 =\n|strength1 =3 [[heavy cruiser]]s\n|strength2 =\n|casualties1 = none\n|casualties2 =1 steamer sunk,<br />3 killed,<br />unknown wounded\n|notes =\n* Either 72 or 89 British survivors were executed by Japanese forces after being taken prisoner.\n|campaignbox={{Axis naval attacks on Australia}}\n{{Campaignbox Indian Ocean Theatre}}\n}}\n\nIn March 1944, a force of three [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] (IJN) [[heavy cruiser]]s raided [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] shipping in the [[Indian Ocean]]. The cruisers departed Japanese-held territory on 1&nbsp;March with the support of other IJN vessels and aircraft. On 9&nbsp;March, they encountered and sank the British [[Steamboat|steamer]] ''Behar'', with the heavy cruiser {{Ship|Japanese cruiser|Tone|1937|2}} picking up over 100 survivors. Fearing detection, the Japanese force subsequently returned to the [[Netherlands East Indies]] (NEI), arriving on 16&nbsp;March. Two days later, most of ''Behar''{{'}}s crew and passengers were murdered on board ''Tone''. Following the war the commander of the raid, Rear Admiral [[Naomasa Sakonju]], was executed for this [[war crime]] and ''Tone''{{'}}s captain Haruo Mayuzumi ([[:ja:\u9edb\u6cbb\u592b]]) was sentenced to seven years imprisonment.\n\n==Background==\nIn February 1944, the Japanese [[Combined Fleet]] withdrew from its base at [[Chuuk State|Truk]] in the Central [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]] to [[Palau]] and [[Singapore]]. The appearance of a powerful Japanese naval force at Singapore concerned the Allies, as it was feared that these ships could potentially conduct raids in the Indian Ocean and against [[Western Australia]].<ref>Odgers (1968), pp. 134\u2013135</ref> In response, the Allies strengthened their naval and air forces in the area by transferring two British [[light cruiser]]s from the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]] and [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]] as well as several [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] warships from the [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]]. The number of air units in [[Ceylon]] and the [[Bay of Bengal]] region was also increased.<ref>Gill (1968), p. 387</ref> Admiral [[James Somerville]], the commander of the British [[Eastern Fleet]], feared that the Japanese would repeat their devastating [[Indian Ocean raid]] of early 1942, and on 25&nbsp;February requested permission to withdraw his fleet from its base at [[Trincomalee]] so that it was not at risk from the larger Japanese force. The [[Admiralty]] rejected this request, and directed that the fleet should remain at Trincomalee unless it was threatened by a superior Japanese force as its withdrawal would affect morale and harm Britain's prestige in the region. It was agreed, however, that the Eastern Fleet should not engage superior Japanese forces and could withdraw if Somerville judged this necessary.<ref name=\"Gill_388\">Gill (1968), p. 388</ref>\n\nIn late February, Vice-Admiral [[Shiro Takasu]]\u2014the Commander in Chief, [[Southwest Area Fleet]]\u2014ordered the heavy cruisers {{Ship|Japanese cruiser|Aoba||2}}, {{Ship|Japanese cruiser |Chikuma|1938|2}}, and {{Ship|Japanese cruiser|Tone|1937|2}} to raid Allied shipping on the main route between [[Aden]] and [[Fremantle, Western Australia|Fremantle]]. This force was commanded by Rear Admiral Naomasa Sakonju on board ''Aoba''. In his instructions to Sakonju, Vice Admiral Takasu directed that if the force captured Allied merchant seamen all prisoners, other than radio operators and other personnel who might possess useful information, were to be killed.<ref name=\"Gill_388\"/> Sakonju did not question this order. The Japanese cruisers embarked specialised boarding parties for this operation as it was hoped that they could capture merchant ships to alleviate Japan's shipping shortage.<ref>Royal Navy Historical Section (1957), pp. 183\u2013184</ref>\n\n==Raid==\nThe three Japanese heavy cruisers departed from the Combined Fleet's anchorage in the [[Lingga Islands]] on 27&nbsp;February.<ref name=\"Aoba_TROM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/aoba_t.htm|title=HIJMS Aoba: Tabular Record of Movement|last=Hackett|first=Bob|author2=Kingsepp, Sander|year=2007|publisher=Combinedfleet.com|accessdate=28 June 2009}}</ref> The light cruisers {{Ship|Japanese cruiser|Kinu||2}} and {{ship|Japanese cruiser|\u014ci||2}} and three destroyers escorted the force through the [[Sunda Strait]] on 1&nbsp;March. The raiders were supported by 10 medium bombers and three or four [[seaplane]]s based in [[Sumatra]] and west [[Java]] which conducted patrols in the direction of Ceylon. Three or four submarines from the 8th&nbsp;Flotilla also monitored Allied shipping movements near [[Ceylon]], the [[Maldive Islands]] and [[Chagos Archipelago]].<ref name= \"Gill_388\"/> The Allies did not detect the Japanese force's departure, but [[Western Australian emergency of March 1944|reinforced their forces in Western Australia]] after an American submarine encountered ''Kinu'' and ''\u014ci'' operating near the [[Lombok Strait]] on 6&nbsp;March. The presence of these ships was taken to indicate that a hostile force had possibly been dispatched into the Indian Ocean.<ref name=\"Gill_390\">Gill (1968), p. 390</ref> On 8&nbsp;March, Somerville directed all Allied ships travelling between 80 and 100\u00b0 east to divert to the south or west.<ref name=\"RN_184\"/>\n\nAfter leaving the Sunda Strait, the Japanese heavy cruisers sailed south-west for the main route between Aden and Fremantle. The ships were spread {{convert|50|km|nmi mi|lk=on|abbr=on}} by day and {{convert|20|km|nmi mi|abbr=on}} by night and maintained [[radio silence]].<ref name=\"RN_184\">Royal Navy Historical Section (1957), p. 184</ref> On the morning of 9&nbsp;March, they encountered the {{convert|6100|LT|t|abbr=on}} British steamer ''Behar'' at {{coord|20|32|S|87|10|E}}, about midway between Fremantle and [[Colombo]].<ref name=\"Gill_388\"/> The ship was travelling from Fremantle to [[Bombay]] as part of a voyage between [[Newcastle, New South Wales]] and the United Kingdom carrying a cargo of [[zinc]].<ref name=\"Weaver_12\">Weaver (2000), p. 12</ref>\n\nUpon sighting the Japanese ships, ''Behar''{{'}}s master, Captain Maurice Symons, ordered that his radio operator transmit the \"RRR\" code in order to notify other ships and Allied bases that the merchant ship was being attacked by surface raiders. ''Tone''{{'}}s signals room picked up this message, and the cruiser opened fire on ''Behar''.<ref>Lamont-Brown (2002), pp. 110\u2013111</ref> The Japanese cruiser did not attempt to capture the steamer, as it was judged too risky to sail her back to Japanese territory.<ref name= \"RN_184\"/> ''Tone''{{'}}s gunners scored hits on ''Behar''{{'}}s prow and stern which killed three of her crew. Five minutes after the sighting, ''Behar''{{'}}s crew and passengers abandoned ship. The steamer sank shortly afterwards and either 104 or 108 survivors were rescued by ''Tone''.<ref>Gill (1968), pp. 388\u2013389</ref><ref name=\"Lamont_Brown_111\">Lamont-Brown (2002), p. 111</ref>{{ref|def|(I)}}\n\nThe ''Behar'' survivors were maltreated by members of ''Tone''{{'}}s crew. Japanese sailors forced the survivors to hand over all their personal belongings of any value, and then used ropes to tie the survivors in painful positions which caused them to have difficulty breathing. The merchant ship's chief officer was beaten after he complained that treating civilians in such a way violated the [[Geneva Conventions|Geneva Convention]]. However, the female survivors later had their ropes removed.<ref name=Lamont_Brown_111 /> When the survivors were taken below decks to be imprisoned they were badly beaten by Japanese sailors.<ref>Lamont-Brown (2002), pp. 111\u2013112</ref>\n\nFollowing the attack, Sakonju judged that it was too dangerous to continue the raid as ''Behar''{{'}}s distress message may have alerted the Allies to his force's presence. Accordingly, the Japanese turned back for the NEI that day.<ref name=\"Gill_389\">Gill (1968), p. 389</ref> The heavy cruisers were again escorted through the Sunda Strait by ''Kinu'', ''\u014ci'' and five destroyers, and arrived back at the NEI on 15&nbsp;March.<ref name= \"Gill_388\"/><ref name=\"Aoba_TROM\"/> During this time, the ''Behar'' survivors were held in a small and extremely hot store room on board ''Tone'', and were given little access to food and water, sanitary facilities and exercise.<ref name=\"Lamont_Brown_112\">Lamont-Brown (2002), p. 112</ref>\n\nDespite Sakonju's fears, the Allies were not immediately aware of the attack on ''Behar''. Her distress signal had been picked up by only a single Allied merchant ship, which did not report it until she arrived at Fremantle on 17&nbsp;March. In the meantime, Somerville had decided on 16&nbsp;March that surface raiders no longer posed a threat to shipping in the Indian Ocean and allowed Allied vessels to resume their normal routing.<ref name=\"RN_184\"/>\n\n==Massacre==\n[[File:Naomasa Sakonju.jpg|thumb|upright|Rear Admiral Naomasa Sakonju]]\nShortly after the ''Behar'' survivors were rescued, Sakonju sent a radio message to ''Tone''{{'}}s commanding officer, Captain Haruo Mayuzumi, reprimanding him for taking non-essential personnel prisoner and not capturing the merchant ship. In this message Sakonju ordered that the survivors be killed. Mayuzumi was unwilling to do so, however, as he felt that this would violate his Christian religious beliefs. His executive officer, Commander Junsuke Mii, also opposed killing the prisoners. Mayuzumi radioed a request to Sakonju that the prisoners be put ashore, but this was rejected. The captain then visited ''Aoba'' to argue his case, but Sakonju remained unmoved and told Mayuzumi to \"obey my orders\". Despite his misgivings, Mayuzumi decided to kill the prisoners.<ref name=Lamont_Brown_112 />\n\nOn 15&nbsp;March the three heavy cruisers anchored at [[Tanjung Priok]] near Java. Following this, either 15 or 36 survivors were transferred to ''Aoba''.<ref name=Gill_389 /><ref name=Lamont_Brown_112 />{{ref|def|(II)}} The party sent to ''Aoba'' included Symonds, the ''Behar''{{'}}s chief officer and several of the senior officers as well as both of the ship's female passengers.<ref name=Lamont_Brown_112 /> All of this group were later landed at Tanjung Priok.<ref name=\"Lamont_Brown_114\">Lamont-Brown (2002), p. 114</ref>\n\nThe three cruisers sailed from Tanjung Priok bound for Singapore on 18&nbsp;March.<ref name=\"Aoba_TROM\"/> That night, all the prisoners on board ''Tone'' were beheaded by several of the cruiser's officers.<ref name=\"Gill_389\"/><ref name=\"Lamont-Brown_112-114\">Lamont-Brown (2002), pp. 112\u2013114</ref> Mayuzumi watched the killings from the ship's bridge but Mii refused to take part.<ref name=Lamont-Brown_112-114 />\n\n==Aftermath==\n\n''Aoba'', ''Chikuma'' and ''Tone'' arrived at Singapore on 25&nbsp;March.<ref name=\"Aoba_TROM\"/> The Indian Ocean raid was the last operation conducted by Axis surface raiders during World War II.<ref name=\"Gill_390\"/> As a result, ''Behar'' was the final Allied merchant ship to be sunk by surface raiders during the war.<ref>Roskill (1960), p. 351</ref>\nThe raid is notable chiefly for the ''Behar'' massacre; it achieved little militarily. The raid failed to disrupt Allied traffic in the region as the diversions ordered by Somerville on 8 March were rescinded by the 16th. The only tangible result was the sinking of one ship,  the ''Behar''; by contrast Axis submarines [[Indian Ocean in World War II#1944|sank three ships]] in the Indian Ocean during the same period. The raid was also less successful than comparable raids by surface ships in the region, such as that of the [[German cruiser Admiral Scheer|''Admiral Scheer'']] in 1941. The Japanese made no attempt to capitalize on their numerical superiority in the region and by the end of the month it had vanished; reinforcements to the Eastern Fleet enabled Somerville to start  a series of carrier raids, commencing with the [[Operation Cockpit|attack on Sabang]] on 19 April 1944.<ref>Roskill (1960), p. 354-6</ref>\n\nThe party of ''Behar'' survivors who had been landed at Tanjung Priok were initially interned in [[prisoner of war]] camps in Java; the male prisoners were sent to a camp near [[Jakarta|Batavia]] and the women were held in a female camp nearby. After all the members of the group had been interrogated, the survivors were separated and sent to other camps in Java or to work as slave labourers in Japan. All the survivors were freed after the end of the war in August 1945.<ref name=Lamont_Brown_114 />\n\nFollowing the war, the Allies prosecuted the officers responsible for the murders on board ''Tone''. Vice Admiral Takasu had died from disease in September 1944, but Sakonju was tried by the British in 1947 at [[Hong Kong]] and sentenced to death.<ref>Fuller (1992), p. 284</ref> Mayuzumi was also convicted for his role in the killings and sentenced to seven years imprisonment.<ref name=\"Gill_390\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Japanese raiders in the Indian Ocean]]\n\n==Notes==\n* {{note|def|(I)}} The number of ''Behar'' survivors rescued after the ship's sinking differ between sources. Lamont-Brown (2002), p.&nbsp;111 states that 108 of the 111 people on board the ship were rescued while Gill (1968), p.&nbsp;389 states that there were 104 survivors, all of whom were rescued.\n* {{note|def|(II)}} Gill (1968), p.&nbsp;389 states that 15 ''Behar'' survivors were landed at Tanjung Priok while Lamont-Brown (2002), p.&nbsp;112 puts the figure at 36.\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Fuller|first=Richard|title=Shokan. Hirohito's Samurai|publisher=Arms and Armour Press|location=London|year=1992|isbn=1-85409-151-4|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/shokanhirohitoss00full}}\n* {{cite book |last=Gill|first=G. Hermon |authorlink=G. Hermon Gill|title=Royal Australian Navy 1942\u20131945|url= http://www.awm.gov.au/histories/second_world_war/volume.asp?levelID=67911|series=[[Australia in the War of 1939\u20131945|Australia in the War of 1939\u20131945. Series 2&nbsp;\u2013 Navy]]|year=1968|publisher= Australian War Memorial|location=Canberra|OCLC=65475}}\n* {{cite book|last=Lamont-Brown|first=Raymond|title=Ships From Hell : Japanese War Crimes on the High Seas|year=2002|publisher=Sutton|location=Stroud, Gloucestershire|isbn=0-7509-2719-4}}\n* {{cite book|last=Odgers |first=George |authorlink=George Odgers |title=Air War Against Japan 1943\u20131945 |url=http://www.awm.gov.au/histories/second_world_war/volume.asp?levelID=67913 |series=Australia in the War of 1939\u20131945. Series 3&nbsp;\u2013 Air |year=1968 |edition=reprint |publisher=Australian War Memorial |location=Canberra |OCLC=569568982 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014171352/http://www.awm.gov.au/histories/second_world_war/volume.asp?levelID=67913 |archivedate=14 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}\n* {{cite book |last=Roskill |first=S. W. |volume=III |title=The War at Sea 1939\u20131945: The Offensive Part I 1st June 1943 \u2013 31st May 1944 |publisher=HMSO |location=London |year=1960 |series=History of the Second World War. United Kingdom Military Series |oclc=570500225}}\n* {{cite book|last=Royal Navy Historical Section|title=War with Japan Volume IV. The South\u2013East Asian Operations and Central Pacific Advance|publisher=Royal Navy|location=London|year=1957|OCLC=651943668}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Weaver|first=Paul|year=2000|title=Behar massacre&nbsp;\u2014 a review of a little-known wartime atrocity|journal=Quarterly Newsletter&nbsp;\u2014 The Australian Association for Maritime History|issue=80|publisher=The Australian Association for Maritime History|location=Perth|issn=1440-5164|url=http://www.aamh.asn.au/news/0080.pdf|access-date=28 June 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091013072342/http://www.aamh.asn.au/news/0080.pdf|archive-date=13 October 2009|url-status=dead}}\n{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1944]]\n[[Category:Indian Ocean operations of World War II]]\n[[Category:Naval battles of World War II involving Japan]]\n[[Category:Japanese war crimes]]\n[[Category:Naval battles and operations of World War II involving the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:March 1944 events]]\n[[Category:Military raids]]\n[[Category:Japan\u2013United Kingdom military relations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict = Second Indian Ocean raid\n|partof = [[Pacific War]]\n|image = [[File:Aoba class cruiser;h97733.jpg|300px|alt=Black and white drawing of a World War II-era warship|U.S. Navy recognition drawing for Japanese Aoba-class heavy cruisers]]\n|caption =U.S. Navy recognition drawing for Japanese ''Aoba''-class heavy cruisers\n|date = 1\u201316 March 1944\n|place = [[Indian Ocean]]\n|coordinates =\n|map_type =\n|latitude =\n|longitude =\n|map_size =\n|map_caption =\n|territory =\n|result = inconclusive\n|status =\n|combatant1 = {{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|combatant2 = {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|commander1 = {{flagicon|Empire of Japan|naval}} Rear Admiral [[Naomasa Sakonju]]\n|commander2 =\n|strength1 =3 [[heavy cruiser]]s\n|strength2 =\n|casualties1 = none\n|casualties2 =1 steamer sunk,<br />3 killed,<br />unknown wounded\n|notes =\n* Either 72 or 89 British survivors were executed by Japanese forces after being taken prisoner.\n}}\n{{Axis naval attacks on Australia}}\n{{Campaignbox Indian Ocean Theatre}}\n\nIn March 1944, a force of three [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] (IJN) [[heavy cruiser]]s raided [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] shipping in the [[Indian Ocean]]. The cruisers departed Japanese-held territory on 1&nbsp;March with the support of other IJN vessels and aircraft. On 9&nbsp;March, they encountered and sank the British [[Steamboat|steamer]] ''Behar'', with the heavy cruiser {{Ship|Japanese cruiser|Tone|1937|2}} picking up over 100 survivors. Fearing detection, the Japanese force subsequently returned to the [[Netherlands East Indies]] (NEI), arriving on 16&nbsp;March. Two days later, most of ''Behar''{{'}}s crew and passengers were murdered on board ''Tone''. Following the war the commander of the raid, Rear Admiral [[Naomasa Sakonju]], was executed for this [[war crime]] and ''Tone''{{'}}s captain Haruo Mayuzumi ([[:ja:\u9edb\u6cbb\u592b]]) was sentenced to seven years imprisonment.\n\n==Background==\nIn February 1944, the Japanese [[Combined Fleet]] withdrew from its base at [[Chuuk State|Truk]] in the Central [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]] to [[Palau]] and [[Singapore]]. The appearance of a powerful Japanese naval force at Singapore concerned the Allies, as it was feared that these ships could potentially conduct raids in the Indian Ocean and against [[Western Australia]].<ref>Odgers (1968), pp. 134\u2013135</ref> In response, the Allies strengthened their naval and air forces in the area by transferring two British [[light cruiser]]s from the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]] and [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]] as well as several [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] warships from the [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]]. The number of air units in [[Ceylon]] and the [[Bay of Bengal]] region was also increased.<ref>Gill (1968), p. 387</ref> Admiral [[James Somerville]], the commander of the British [[Eastern Fleet]], feared that the Japanese would repeat their devastating [[Indian Ocean raid]] of early 1942, and on 25&nbsp;February requested permission to withdraw his fleet from its base at [[Trincomalee]] so that it was not at risk from the larger Japanese force. The [[Admiralty]] rejected this request, and directed that the fleet should remain at Trincomalee unless it was threatened by a superior Japanese force as its withdrawal would affect morale and harm Britain's prestige in the region. It was agreed, however, that the Eastern Fleet should not engage superior Japanese forces and could withdraw if Somerville judged this necessary.<ref name=\"Gill_388\">Gill (1968), p. 388</ref>\n\nIn late February, Vice-Admiral [[Shiro Takasu]]\u2014the Commander in Chief, [[Southwest Area Fleet]]\u2014ordered the heavy cruisers {{Ship|Japanese cruiser|Aoba||2}}, {{Ship|Japanese cruiser |Chikuma|1938|2}}, and {{Ship|Japanese cruiser|Tone|1937|2}} to raid Allied shipping on the main route between [[Aden]] and [[Fremantle, Western Australia|Fremantle]]. This force was commanded by Rear Admiral Naomasa Sakonju on board ''Aoba''. In his instructions to Sakonju, Vice Admiral Takasu directed that if the force captured Allied merchant seamen all prisoners, other than radio operators and other personnel who might possess useful information, were to be killed.<ref name=\"Gill_388\"/> Sakonju did not question this order. The Japanese cruisers embarked specialised boarding parties for this operation as it was hoped that they could capture merchant ships to alleviate Japan's shipping shortage.<ref>Royal Navy Historical Section (1957), pp. 183\u2013184</ref>\n\n==Raid==\nThe three Japanese heavy cruisers departed from the Combined Fleet's anchorage in the [[Lingga Islands]] on 27&nbsp;February.<ref name=\"Aoba_TROM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/aoba_t.htm|title=HIJMS Aoba: Tabular Record of Movement|last=Hackett|first=Bob|author2=Kingsepp, Sander|year=2007|publisher=Combinedfleet.com|accessdate=28 June 2009}}</ref> The light cruisers {{Ship|Japanese cruiser|Kinu||2}} and {{ship|Japanese cruiser|\u014ci||2}} and three destroyers escorted the force through the [[Sunda Strait]] on 1&nbsp;March. The raiders were supported by 10 medium bombers and three or four [[seaplane]]s based in [[Sumatra]] and west [[Java]] which conducted patrols in the direction of Ceylon. Three or four submarines from the 8th&nbsp;Flotilla also monitored Allied shipping movements near [[Ceylon]], the [[Maldive Islands]] and [[Chagos Archipelago]].<ref name= \"Gill_388\"/> The Allies did not detect the Japanese force's departure, but [[Western Australian emergency of March 1944|reinforced their forces in Western Australia]] after an American submarine encountered ''Kinu'' and ''\u014ci'' operating near the [[Lombok Strait]] on 6&nbsp;March. The presence of these ships was taken to indicate that a hostile force had possibly been dispatched into the Indian Ocean.<ref name=\"Gill_390\">Gill (1968), p. 390</ref> On 8&nbsp;March, Somerville directed all Allied ships travelling between 80 and 100\u00b0 east to divert to the south or west.<ref name=\"RN_184\"/>\n\nAfter leaving the Sunda Strait, the Japanese heavy cruisers sailed south-west for the main route between Aden and Fremantle. The ships were spread {{convert|50|km|nmi mi|lk=on|abbr=on}} by day and {{convert|20|km|nmi mi|abbr=on}} by night and maintained [[radio silence]].<ref name=\"RN_184\">Royal Navy Historical Section (1957), p. 184</ref> On the morning of 9&nbsp;March, they encountered the {{convert|6100|LT|t|abbr=on}} British steamer ''Behar'' at {{coord|20|32|S|87|10|E}}, about midway between Fremantle and [[Colombo]].<ref name=\"Gill_388\"/> The ship was travelling from Fremantle to [[Bombay]] as part of a voyage between [[Newcastle, New South Wales]] and the United Kingdom carrying a cargo of [[zinc]].<ref name=\"Weaver_12\">Weaver (2000), p. 12</ref>\n\nUpon sighting the Japanese ships, ''Behar''{{'}}s master, Captain Maurice Symons, ordered that his radio operator transmit the \"RRR\" code in order to notify other ships and Allied bases that the merchant ship was being attacked by surface raiders. ''Tone''{{'}}s signals room picked up this message, and the cruiser opened fire on ''Behar''.<ref>Lamont-Brown (2002), pp. 110\u2013111</ref> The Japanese cruiser did not attempt to capture the steamer, as it was judged too risky to sail her back to Japanese territory.<ref name= \"RN_184\"/> ''Tone''{{'}}s gunners scored hits on ''Behar''{{'}}s prow and stern which killed three of her crew. Five minutes after the sighting, ''Behar''{{'}}s crew and passengers abandoned ship. The steamer sank shortly afterwards and either 104 or 108 survivors were rescued by ''Tone''.<ref>Gill (1968), pp. 388\u2013389</ref><ref name=\"Lamont_Brown_111\">Lamont-Brown (2002), p. 111</ref>{{ref|def|(I)}}\n\nThe ''Behar'' survivors were maltreated by members of ''Tone''{{'}}s crew. Japanese sailors forced the survivors to hand over all their personal belongings of any value, and then used ropes to tie the survivors in painful positions which caused them to have difficulty breathing. The merchant ship's chief officer was beaten after he complained that treating civilians in such a way violated the [[Geneva Conventions|Geneva Convention]]. However, the female survivors later had their ropes removed.<ref name=Lamont_Brown_111 /> When the survivors were taken below decks to be imprisoned they were badly beaten by Japanese sailors.<ref>Lamont-Brown (2002), pp. 111\u2013112</ref>\n\nFollowing the attack, Sakonju judged that it was too dangerous to continue the raid as ''Behar''{{'}}s distress message may have alerted the Allies to his force's presence. Accordingly, the Japanese turned back for the NEI that day.<ref name=\"Gill_389\">Gill (1968), p. 389</ref> The heavy cruisers were again escorted through the Sunda Strait by ''Kinu'', ''\u014ci'' and five destroyers, and arrived back at the NEI on 15&nbsp;March.<ref name= \"Gill_388\"/><ref name=\"Aoba_TROM\"/> During this time, the ''Behar'' survivors were held in a small and extremely hot store room on board ''Tone'', and were given little access to food and water, sanitary facilities and exercise.<ref name=\"Lamont_Brown_112\">Lamont-Brown (2002), p. 112</ref>\n\nDespite Sakonju's fears, the Allies were not immediately aware of the attack on ''Behar''. Her distress signal had been picked up by only a single Allied merchant ship, which did not report it until she arrived at Fremantle on 17&nbsp;March. In the meantime, Somerville had decided on 16&nbsp;March that surface raiders no longer posed a threat to shipping in the Indian Ocean and allowed Allied vessels to resume their normal routing.<ref name=\"RN_184\"/>\n\n==Massacre==\n[[File:Naomasa Sakonju.jpg|thumb|upright|Rear Admiral Naomasa Sakonju]]\nShortly after the ''Behar'' survivors were rescued, Sakonju sent a radio message to ''Tone''{{'}}s commanding officer, Captain Haruo Mayuzumi, reprimanding him for taking non-essential personnel prisoner and not capturing the merchant ship. In this message Sakonju ordered that the survivors be killed. Mayuzumi was unwilling to do so, however, as he felt that this would violate his Christian religious beliefs. His executive officer, Commander Junsuke Mii, also opposed killing the prisoners. Mayuzumi radioed a request to Sakonju that the prisoners be put ashore, but this was rejected. The captain then visited ''Aoba'' to argue his case, but Sakonju remained unmoved and told Mayuzumi to \"obey my orders\". Despite his misgivings, Mayuzumi decided to kill the prisoners.<ref name=Lamont_Brown_112 />\n\nOn 15&nbsp;March the three heavy cruisers anchored at [[Tanjung Priok]] near Java. Following this, either 15 or 36 survivors were transferred to ''Aoba''.<ref name=Gill_389 /><ref name=Lamont_Brown_112 />{{ref|def|(II)}} The party sent to ''Aoba'' included Symonds, the ''Behar''{{'}}s chief officer and several of the senior officers as well as both of the ship's female passengers.<ref name=Lamont_Brown_112 /> All of this group were later landed at Tanjung Priok.<ref name=\"Lamont_Brown_114\">Lamont-Brown (2002), p. 114</ref>\n\nThe three cruisers sailed from Tanjung Priok bound for Singapore on 18&nbsp;March.<ref name=\"Aoba_TROM\"/> That night, all the prisoners on board ''Tone'' were beheaded by several of the cruiser's officers.<ref name=\"Gill_389\"/><ref name=\"Lamont-Brown_112-114\">Lamont-Brown (2002), pp. 112\u2013114</ref> Mayuzumi watched the killings from the ship's bridge but Mii refused to take part.<ref name=Lamont-Brown_112-114 />\n\n==Aftermath==\n\n''Aoba'', ''Chikuma'' and ''Tone'' arrived at Singapore on 25&nbsp;March.<ref name=\"Aoba_TROM\"/> The Indian Ocean raid was the last operation conducted by Axis surface raiders during World War II.<ref name=\"Gill_390\"/> As a result, ''Behar'' was the final Allied merchant ship to be sunk by surface raiders during the war.<ref>Roskill (1960), p. 351</ref>\nThe raid is notable chiefly for the ''Behar'' massacre; it achieved little militarily. The raid failed to disrupt Allied traffic in the region as the diversions ordered by Somerville on 8 March were rescinded by the 16th. The only tangible result was the sinking of one ship,  the ''Behar''; by contrast Axis submarines [[Indian Ocean in World War II#1944|sank three ships]] in the Indian Ocean during the same period. The raid was also less successful than comparable raids by surface ships in the region, such as that of the [[German cruiser Admiral Scheer|''Admiral Scheer'']] in 1941. The Japanese made no attempt to capitalize on their numerical superiority in the region and by the end of the month it had vanished; reinforcements to the Eastern Fleet enabled Somerville to start  a series of carrier raids, commencing with the [[Operation Cockpit|attack on Sabang]] on 19 April 1944.<ref>Roskill (1960), p. 354-6</ref>\n\nThe party of ''Behar'' survivors who had been landed at Tanjung Priok were initially interned in [[prisoner of war]] camps in Java; the male prisoners were sent to a camp near [[Jakarta|Batavia]] and the women were held in a female camp nearby. After all the members of the group had been interrogated, the survivors were separated and sent to other camps in Java or to work as slave labourers in Japan. All the survivors were freed after the end of the war in August 1945.<ref name=Lamont_Brown_114 />\n\nFollowing the war, the Allies prosecuted the officers responsible for the murders on board ''Tone''. Vice Admiral Takasu had died from disease in September 1944, but Sakonju was tried by the British in 1947 at [[Hong Kong]] and sentenced to death.<ref>Fuller (1992), p. 284</ref> Mayuzumi was also convicted for his role in the killings and sentenced to seven years imprisonment.<ref name=\"Gill_390\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Japanese raiders in the Indian Ocean]]\n\n==Notes==\n* {{note|def|(I)}} The number of ''Behar'' survivors rescued after the ship's sinking differ between sources. Lamont-Brown (2002), p.&nbsp;111 states that 108 of the 111 people on board the ship were rescued while Gill (1968), p.&nbsp;389 states that there were 104 survivors, all of whom were rescued.\n* {{note|def|(II)}} Gill (1968), p.&nbsp;389 states that 15 ''Behar'' survivors were landed at Tanjung Priok while Lamont-Brown (2002), p.&nbsp;112 puts the figure at 36.\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Fuller|first=Richard|title=Shokan. Hirohito's Samurai|publisher=Arms and Armour Press|location=London|year=1992|isbn=1-85409-151-4|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/shokanhirohitoss00full}}\n* {{cite book |last=Gill|first=G. Hermon |authorlink=G. Hermon Gill|title=Royal Australian Navy 1942\u20131945|url= http://www.awm.gov.au/histories/second_world_war/volume.asp?levelID=67911|series=[[Australia in the War of 1939\u20131945|Australia in the War of 1939\u20131945. Series 2&nbsp;\u2013 Navy]]|year=1968|publisher= Australian War Memorial|location=Canberra|OCLC=65475}}\n* {{cite book|last=Lamont-Brown|first=Raymond|title=Ships From Hell : Japanese War Crimes on the High Seas|year=2002|publisher=Sutton|location=Stroud, Gloucestershire|isbn=0-7509-2719-4}}\n* {{cite book|last=Odgers |first=George |authorlink=George Odgers |title=Air War Against Japan 1943\u20131945 |url=http://www.awm.gov.au/histories/second_world_war/volume.asp?levelID=67913 |series=Australia in the War of 1939\u20131945. Series 3&nbsp;\u2013 Air |year=1968 |edition=reprint |publisher=Australian War Memorial |location=Canberra |OCLC=569568982 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014171352/http://www.awm.gov.au/histories/second_world_war/volume.asp?levelID=67913 |archivedate=14 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}\n* {{cite book |last=Roskill |first=S. W. |volume=III |title=The War at Sea 1939\u20131945: The Offensive Part I 1st June 1943 \u2013 31st May 1944 |publisher=HMSO |location=London |year=1960 |series=History of the Second World War. United Kingdom Military Series |oclc=570500225}}\n* {{cite book|last=Royal Navy Historical Section|title=War with Japan Volume IV. The South\u2013East Asian Operations and Central Pacific Advance|publisher=Royal Navy|location=London|year=1957|OCLC=651943668}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Weaver|first=Paul|year=2000|title=Behar massacre&nbsp;\u2014 a review of a little-known wartime atrocity|journal=Quarterly Newsletter&nbsp;\u2014 The Australian Association for Maritime History|issue=80|publisher=The Australian Association for Maritime History|location=Perth|issn=1440-5164|url=http://www.aamh.asn.au/news/0080.pdf|access-date=28 June 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091013072342/http://www.aamh.asn.au/news/0080.pdf|archive-date=13 October 2009|url-status=dead}}\n{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1944]]\n[[Category:Indian Ocean operations of World War II]]\n[[Category:Naval battles of World War II involving Japan]]\n[[Category:Japanese war crimes]]\n[[Category:Naval battles and operations of World War II involving the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:March 1944 events]]\n[[Category:Military raids]]\n[[Category:Japan\u2013United Kingdom military relations]]\n", "name_user": "Eastfarthingan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Infobox layout", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_Ocean_raid_(1944)"}
{"title_page": "Zion Williamson", "text_new": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American basketball player}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Zion Williamson\n| image = Zion Williamson (49488462157) (cropped).jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Williamson with the Pelicans in 2020\n| number = 1\n| team = New Orleans Pelicans\n| position = [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| league = [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|2000|7|6}}\n| birth_place = [[Salisbury, North Carolina]]\n| nationality = American\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 6\n| weight_lbs = 285\n| high_school = [[Spartanburg Day School|Spartanburg Day]]<br>([[Spartanburg, South Carolina]])\n| college = [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke]] (2018\u20132019)\n| draft_year = 2019\n| draft_round = 1\n| draft_pick = 1\n| draft_team = [[New Orleans Pelicans]]\n| career_start = 2019\n| years1 = {{nbay|2019|start}}\u2013present\n| team1 = [[New Orleans Pelicans]]\n| highlights =\n* Consensus [[List of U.S. men's college basketball national player of the year awards|National College Player of the Year]] (2019)\n* Consensus first-team [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] ([[2019 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|2019]])\n* [[USBWA National Freshman of the Year|Wayman Tisdale Award]] (2019)\n* [[Karl Malone Award]] (2019) \n* [[ACC Athlete of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Atlantic Coast Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year|ACC Player of the Year]] (2019) \n* [[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]] All-Freshman team (2019) \n* First-team All-[[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]] (2019)\n* [[Atlantic Coast Conference Men's Basketball Rookie of the Year|ACC Rookie of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[ACC Men's Basketball Tournament|ACC Tournament]] MVP ([[2019 ACC Men's Basketball Tournament|2019]])\n* [[McDonald's All-American]] ([[2018 McDonald's All-American Boys Game|2018]])\n* [[Jordan Brand Classic]] (2018)\n* [[Nike Hoop Summit]] (2018)\n* [[South Carolina Mr. Basketball]] (2018)\n| nba_profile = zion_williamson\n| bbr = willizi01\n}}\n'''Zion Lateef Williamson''' (born July 6, 2000) is an American professional [[basketball]] player for the [[New Orleans Pelicans]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). He plays the [[power forward (basketball)|power forward]] position.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/w/willizi01.html|title=Zion Williamson|publisher=[[Basketball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Following a dominant freshman-year stint with the [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke Blue Devils]], he was selected by the Pelicans first overall in the [[2019 NBA draft]].\n\nBorn in [[Salisbury, North Carolina]], Williamson attended [[Spartanburg Day School]], where he was a consensus five-star [[college recruiting|recruit]] and was ranked among the top five players in the 2018 class. He led his team to three straight state championships and earned [[South Carolina Mr. Basketball]] recognition in his senior season. Williamson also left high school as a [[McDonald's All-American Game|McDonald's All-American]], runner-up for [[Mr. Basketball USA]], and [[USA Today All-USA high school basketball team|''USA Today'' All-USA first team]] honoree. In high school, he drew national attention for his [[slam dunk]]s.\n\nIn his freshman and only season with Duke, Williamson was named [[Atlantic Coast Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year|ACC Player of the Year]], [[ACC Athlete of the Year]] and [[Atlantic Coast Conference Men's Basketball Rookie of the Year|ACC Rookie of the Year]]. He set the single-game school scoring record for freshmen in January 2019, claimed ACC Rookie of the Week accolades five times, earned [[Associated Press College Basketball Player of the Year|AP Player of the Year]], [[Sporting News Men's College Basketball Player of the Year|''Sporting News'' College Player of the Year]] recognition, and won the [[USBWA National Freshman of the Year|Wayman Tisdale Award]].\n\n==Early life==\nWilliamson was born in [[Salisbury, North Carolina]]. Besides basketball, Williamson played [[Association football|soccer]] and the [[quarterback]] position in [[American football|football]].<ref name=finest/> When he was five years old, he set sights on becoming a [[college basketball]] star. At age nine, Williamson began waking up every morning at 5&nbsp;a.m. to go train.<ref name=usatodayhss/> He competed in youth leagues with his mother Sharonda Sampson coaching and played for the Sumter Falcons on the [[Amateur Athletic Union]] (AAU) circuit, facing opponents four years older than him.<ref name=legend/> Williamson later began working with his stepfather, former college basketball player Lee Anderson, to improve his skills as a [[point guard]].<ref name=usatodayhss/> He joined the basketball team at Johnakin Middle School in [[Marion, South Carolina]], where he was again coached by his mother and averaged 20 points per game. In middle school, Williamson was a point guard and lost only three games in two years.<ref name=usatodayhss/> In 2013, he guided Johnakin to an 8\u20131 record and a conference title.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mcfadden |first1=Naeem |title=Middle school basketball teams capture conference championships |url=https://www.scnow.com/starandenterprise/sports/article_53d5d30e-7b7c-11e2-9c78-001a4bcf6878.html |website=[[The Morning News (American newspaper)|The Morning News]] |access-date=January 16, 2019 |date=February 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==High school career==\n===Freshman and sophomore seasons===\nWilliamson attended [[Spartanburg Day School]], a small [[K\u201312]] private school in [[Spartanburg, South Carolina]], where he played basketball for the Griffins.<ref name=finest/> Between eighth and ninth grade, he grew from {{height|ft=5|in=9}} to {{height|ft=6|in=3}}.<ref name=legend/> In the summer leading up to his first season, Williamson practiced in the school gym and developed the ability to dunk.<ref name=\"washpost\">{{cite web|last1=Babb|first1=Kent|title=Zion Williamson, 16, might be the best dunker on the Internet. And what else?|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/highschools/zion-williamson-16-might-be-the-best-dunker-on-the-internet-and-what-else/2017/04/07/84139f04-1b02-11e7-855e-4824bbb5d748_story.html|website=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=April 9, 2017|date=April 8, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408225619/https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/highschools/zion-williamson-16-might-be-the-best-dunker-on-the-internet-and-what-else/2017/04/07/84139f04-1b02-11e7-855e-4824bbb5d748_story.html|archive-date=April 8, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> At the time, he competed for the South Carolina Hornets AAU team as well, where he was teammates with [[Ja Morant]].<ref name=\"morant\">{{cite web |last1=Norlander |first1=Matt |title=The real story of Ja Morant and Zion Williamson playing on the same AAU team |url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/court-report-the-real-story-of-ja-morant-zion-williamson-playing-on-the-same-aau-team/ |publisher=[[CBS Sports]] |access-date=January 23, 2019 |date=January 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190124041742/https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/court-report-the-real-story-of-ja-morant-zion-williamson-playing-on-the-same-aau-team/ |archive-date=January 24, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> As a freshman, Williamson averaged 24.4 points, 9.4 rebounds, 2.8 assists, 3.3 steals and 3.0 blocks, earning All-State and All-Region honors.<ref name=\"freshman\">{{cite web|title=2015 Boys Basketball All-Area Team|url=http://www.goupstate.com/news/20150405/2015-boys-basketball-all-area-team|website=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]]|access-date=April 9, 2017|date=April 5, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170410051957/http://www.goupstate.com/news/20150405/2015-boys-basketball-all-area-team|archive-date=April 10, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He also led Spartanburg Day to a [[South Carolina Independent School Association]] (SCISA) state championship game appearance.<ref name=\"genz\">{{cite web |last1=Figman |first1=Adam |title=Generation Z |url=https://www.slamonline.com/college-hs/high-school/zion-williamson-spartanburg-slam-cover/ |website=[[Slam (magazine)|Slam]] |access-date=August 24, 2018 |date=June 6, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825002609/https://www.slamonline.com/college-hs/high-school/zion-williamson-spartanburg-slam-cover/ |archive-date=August 25, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2015, Williamson took part in the SCISA North-South All-Star Game in [[Sumter, South Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Eight area players ready for SCISA North-South All-Star games |url=https://www.scnow.com/sports/article_f60d1ea6-c482-11e4-bcf7-d302529639b2.html |website=[[The Morning News (American newspaper)|The Morning News]] |access-date=January 16, 2019 |date=March 6, 2015}}</ref> By his second year in high school, he stood {{height|ft=6|in=6}}.<ref name=genz/> In his sophomore season, Williamson averaged 28.3 points, 10.4 rebounds, 3.9 blocks, and 2.7 steals per game and was named SCISA Region I-2A Player of the Year.<ref name=\"melton\">{{cite web |last1=Melton |first1=Kevin |title=Zion Williamson picks up offer from South Carolina |url=https://www.goupstate.com/news/20160503/zion-williamson-picks-up-offer-from-south-carolina |website=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]] |access-date=January 16, 2019 |date=May 3, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117071441/https://www.goupstate.com/news/20160503/zion-williamson-picks-up-offer-from-south-carolina |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He led the Griffins to their first SCISA Region I-2A title in program history.<ref name=finest/> In June 2016, Williamson participated in the [[National Basketball Players Association]] (NBPA) Top 100 camp and was its leading scorer.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Meyer |first1=Jerry |title=Zion Williamson leading NBA Top 100 Camp in scoring |url=https://247sports.com/college/alabama/Bolt/Zion-Williamson-leading-NBA-Top-100-Camp-in-scoring-45854651/ |publisher=[[247Sports.com|247Sports]] |access-date=August 24, 2018 |date=June 17, 2016}}</ref> In August, he won the [[Under Armour]] Elite 24 showcase dunk contest in [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Resetar |first1=Max |title=Zion Williamson Wins the 2016 Elite 24 Dunk Contest |url=https://www.slamonline.com/slam-tv/zion-williamson-wins-2016-elite-24-dunk-contest/ |website=[[Slam (magazine)|Slam]] |access-date=January 16, 2019 |date=August 20, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117013422/https://www.slamonline.com/slam-tv/zion-williamson-wins-2016-elite-24-dunk-contest/ |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Junior season===\nAs a junior, Williamson averaged 36.8 points, 13 rebounds, 3 steals, and 2.5 blocks per game.<ref name=\"repeats\">{{cite web |last1=Melton |first1=Kevin |title=Slam Dunk: Zion Williamson repeats as Player of the Year |url=https://www.goupstate.com/sports/20170422/slam-dunk-zion-williamson-repeats-as-player-of-year |website=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]] |access-date=January 19, 2019 |date=April 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120095116/https://www.goupstate.com/sports/20170422/slam-dunk-zion-williamson-repeats-as-player-of-year |archive-date=January 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Entering the season, he was among 50 players selected to the [[Naismith Prep Player of the Year Award]] watch list.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bezjak |first1=Lou |title=Jalek Felton, Christian Brown on Naismith Boys High School Player of the Year watch list |url=https://www.thestate.com/sports/high-school/prep-basketball/article114898558.html |website=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]] |access-date=January 17, 2019 |date=November 15, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121033/https://www.thestate.com/sports/high-school/prep-basketball/article114898558.html |archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Starting in the 2016\u201317 season, Williamson was propelled into the national spotlight for his [[viral video|viral]] highlight videos.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jordan |first1=Jason |title=Zion Williamson's newfound fame has grown his social media following substantially |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2017/zion-williamsons-newfound-fame-has-grown-his-social-media-following-substantially |newspaper=[[USA Today|USA Today High School Sports]] |access-date=January 17, 2019 |date=January 24, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121119/https://usatodayhss.com/2017/zion-williamsons-newfound-fame-has-grown-his-social-media-following-substantially |archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He made his season debut on November 15, 2016, recording 42 points and 16 rebounds in a win over [[Cardinal Newman High School (Columbia, South Carolina)|Cardinal Newman High School]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Watson |first1=Randy |title=Zion Williamson Drops 42 & 13 in Season Debut |url=http://ballislife.com/zion-williamson-42-13-debut/ |publisher=[[Ballislife.com|Ballislife]] |access-date=January 17, 2019 |date=November 15, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121802/http://ballislife.com/zion-williamson-42-13-debut/ |archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In the same month, his highlights drew the praise of NBA player [[Stephen Curry]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Burns |first1=Ashley |title=Steph Curry Is Impressed By High School Hoops Prospect Zion Williamson And You Should Be, Too |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/steph-curry-impressed-high-school-171726818.html |work=[[Yahoo Sports]] |access-date=January 17, 2019 |date=November 18, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121554/https://sports.yahoo.com/news/steph-curry-impressed-high-school-171726818.html |archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On November 24, Williamson erupted for 50 points, including 10 dunks, along with 16 rebounds and 5 blocks versus [[Proviso East High School]] at the Tournament of Champions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Five-Star Junior Prospect Zion Williamson Drops 50 Points |url=https://www.slamonline.com/slam-tv/five-star-junior-prospect-zion-williamson-drops-50-points/ |website=[[Slam (magazine)|Slam]] |access-date=January 17, 2019 |date=November 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121344/https://www.slamonline.com/slam-tv/five-star-junior-prospect-zion-williamson-drops-50-points/ |archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Regan |first1=Brett |title=Zion Williamson's Monster 50-Point Performance Steals ToC Show |url=https://www.flohoops.com/articles/5058094-zion-williamsons-monster-50-point-performance-steals-toc-show |publisher=FloHoops |access-date=January 17, 2019 |date=November 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121056/https://www.flohoops.com/articles/5058094-zion-williamsons-monster-50-point-performance-steals-toc-show |archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In a 73\u201353 victory over Gray Collegiate Academy at the [[Chick-fil-A]] Classic on December 21, he posted a tournament-record 53 points and 16 rebounds, shooting 25-of-28 from the field.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Melton |first1=Kevin |title=Spartanburg Day's Zion Williamson has record night in tourney opener |url=https://www.goupstate.com/sports/20161221/spartanburg-days-zion-williamson-has-record-night-in-tourney-opener |website=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]] |access-date=January 17, 2019 |date=December 21, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119174222/https://www.goupstate.com/sports/20161221/spartanburg-days-zion-williamson-has-record-night-in-tourney-opener |archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On December 30, Williamson recorded 31 points and 14 rebounds to win [[most valuable player]] (MVP) at the Farm Bureau Insurance Classic.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Melton |first1=Kevin |title=Newton tops Spartanburg Day; Zion Williamson named MVP |url=https://www.goupstate.com/sports/20161230/newton-tops-spartanburg-day-zion-williamson-named-mvp |website=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]] |access-date=January 17, 2019 |date=December 30, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119174219/https://www.goupstate.com/sports/20161230/newton-tops-spartanburg-day-zion-williamson-named-mvp |archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On January 15, 2017, he received nationwide publicity after rapper [[Drake (musician)|Drake]] wore his jersey in an [[Instagram]] post.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jordan |first1=Jason |title=Zion Williamson's No. 1 fan Drake sports his high school jersey |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2017/zion-williamsons-no-1-fan-drake-sports-his-high-school-jersey |newspaper=[[USA Today|USA Today High School Sports]] |access-date=January 17, 2019 |date=January 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119174411/https://usatodayhss.com/2017/zion-williamsons-no-1-fan-drake-sports-his-high-school-jersey |archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWilliamson surpassed the 2,000-point barrier on January 20, when he tallied 48 points against [[Oakbrook Preparatory School]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wellman |first1=Webb |title=Zion Williamson 48 Points & Dunks On Everyone But The Coach |url=http://ballislife.com/zion-williamson-2000/ |publisher=[[Ballislife.com|Ballislife]] |access-date=January 17, 2019 |date=January 20, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121807/http://ballislife.com/zion-williamson-2000/ |archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On February 14, he led Spartanburg Day past Oakbrook Prep for their first SCISA Region I-2A title, chipping in a game-high 37 points in a 105\u201349 rout. Williamson broke the state record for most 30-point games in a season, with 27 by the end of the regular season.<ref name=\"staterecord\">{{cite web |last1=FitzPatrick |first1=Joel |title=Zion Williamson sets state record in rout |url=https://www.goupstate.com/sports/20170214/zion-williamson-sets-state-record-in-rout |website=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]] |access-date=January 17, 2018 |date=February 14, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602200148/http://www.goupstate.com/sports/20170214/zion-williamson-sets-state-record-in-rout |archive-date=June 2, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> He repeated as SCISA Region I-2A Player of the Year.<ref name=repeats/> High school sports website [[MaxPreps]] named him National Junior of the Year and to the High School All-American first team, while ''[[USA Today]]'' High School Sports gave him [[USA Today All-USA high school basketball team|All-USA first team]] recognition.<ref>{{cite web |title=2016\u201317 MaxPreps Boys Basketball Junior All-American Team |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/news/otwRLm_KeEGHwC460kRRPg/2016-17-maxpreps-boys-basketball-junior-all-american-team.htm |publisher=[[MaxPreps]] |access-date=January 19, 2019 |date=April 11, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120093549/http://www.maxpreps.com/news/otwRLm_KeEGHwC460kRRPg/2016-17-maxpreps-boys-basketball-junior-all-american-team.htm |archive-date=January 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2016\u201317 MaxPreps High School Boys Basketball All-American Team |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/news/90GdoEN1_UCBDFsChBO2nw/2016-17-maxpreps-high-school-boys-basketball-all-american-team.htm |publisher=[[MaxPreps]] |access-date=January 19, 2019 |date=April 6, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107154501/http://www.maxpreps.com/news/90GdoEN1_UCBDFsChBO2nw/2016-17-maxpreps-high-school-boys-basketball-all-american-team.htm |archive-date=January 7, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Halley |first1=Jim |title=ALL-USA Boys Basketball First Team: Zion Williamson, Spartanburg Day (S.C.) |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2017/all-usa-boys-basketball-first-team-zion-williamson-spartanburg-day-s-c |newspaper=[[USA Today|USA Today High School Sports]] |accessdate=January 19, 2019 |date=March 28, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120093523/https://usatodayhss.com/2017/all-usa-boys-basketball-first-team-zion-williamson-spartanburg-day-s-c |archive-date=January 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On April 22, 2017, Williamson recorded 26 points and 7 rebounds for his AAU team SC Supreme in a loss to highly touted recruit [[Romeo Langford]] and Twenty Two Vision at an [[Adidas]] Gauntlet tournament.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bossi |first1=Eric |title=No. 2 and No. 3 Zion Williamson and Romeo Langford duel at adidas Gauntlet |url=https://basketballrecruiting.rivals.com/news/no-2-and-no-3-zion-williamson-and-romeo-langford-duel-at-adidas-gauntlet |publisher=[[Rivals.com|Rivals]] |accessdate=January 19, 2019 |date=April 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120093516/https://basketballrecruiting.rivals.com/news/no-2-and-no-3-zion-williamson-and-romeo-langford-duel-at-adidas-gauntlet |archive-date=January 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In June, he appeared on the cover of basketball magazine ''[[Slam (magazine)|Slam]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Figman |first1=Adam |title=Zion Williamson Covers SLAM 210 |url=https://www.slamonline.com/college-hs/high-school/zion-williamson-covers-slam-210/ |website=[[Slam (magazine)|Slam]] |accessdate=January 19, 2019 |date=June 6, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120093436/https://www.slamonline.com/college-hs/high-school/zion-williamson-covers-slam-210/ |archive-date=January 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson, in a highly publicized AAU game on July 27, scored 28 points and led SC Supreme to a 104\u201392 win over 2019 class recruit [[LaMelo Ball]] and Big Ballers at the Adidas Uprising Summer Championships.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Medcalf |first1=Myron |title=AAU game featuring LaMelo Ball, Zion Williamson goes on despite large crowd |url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/20167079/with-massive-crowd-hand-lamelo-ball-zion-williamson-showdown-goes-on |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=January 19, 2019 |date=July 27, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120093459/http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/20167079/with-massive-crowd-hand-lamelo-ball-zion-williamson-showdown-goes-on |archive-date=January 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In August, he was named MVP of the 2017 Adidas Nations camp after averaging 22.5 points and 7.2 rebounds through 6 games.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tomes |first1=Evan |title=adidas Nations: Top High School / Internationals |url=https://www.nbadraft.net/adidas-nations-top-high-school-internationals |publisher=NBADraft.net |accessdate=January 19, 2019 |date=August 23, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120093437/https://www.nbadraft.net/adidas-nations-top-high-school-internationals |archive-date=January 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Senior season===\nIn his senior season, Williamson averaged 36.4 points, 11.4 rebounds and 3.5 assists per game.<ref name=\"allusa\">{{cite news |last1=Halley |first1=Jim |title=ALL-USA Boys Basketball First Team: Zion Williamson, Spartanburg Day |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2018/all-usa-boys-basketball-first-team-zion-williamson-spartanburg-day |newspaper=[[USA Today|USA Today High School Sports]] |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |date=April 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121064221/https://usatodayhss.com/2018/all-usa-boys-basketball-first-team-zion-williamson-spartanburg-day |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He debuted on November 15, 2017, erupting for 46 points and 15 rebounds in a 70\u201362 loss to [[Christ School (North Carolina)|Christ School]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ostrander |first1=Lynden |title=Zion Williamson scores 46 points in season opener |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/news/ql_UTPSyo0qOG_28w5l0hQ/zion-williamson-scores-46-points-in-season-opener.htm |publisher=[[MaxPreps]] |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |date=November 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121064250/http://www.maxpreps.com/news/ql_UTPSyo0qOG_28w5l0hQ/zion-williamson-scores-46-points-in-season-opener.htm |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In his home opener on November 21, he recorded 29 points and 11 rebounds, leading the Griffins to a 70\u201355 win over [[Hammond School (South Carolina)|Hammond School]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ramspacher |first1=Andrew |title=Zion Williamson keeps dunking and college programs keep waiting |url=https://www.thestate.com/sports/high-school/prep-basketball/article185965988.html |website=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]] |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |date=November 21, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121010916/https://www.thestate.com/sports/high-school/prep-basketball/article185965988.html |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In the game, Williamson bruised his left foot, which sidelined him for over a month.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Millians |first1=Rick |title=What's wrong with Zion Williamson and when will he return? |url=https://www.thestate.com/sports/high-school/prep-basketball/article189503624.html |website=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]] |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |date=December 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121064052/https://www.thestate.com/sports/high-school/prep-basketball/article189503624.html |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> While recovering, he commented, \"It's really been a time to grow mentally.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bezjak |first1=Lou |title=Zion Williamson's return to the court coming soon |url=https://www.thestate.com/sports/high-school/prep-basketball/article193382214.html |website=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]] |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |date=January 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121064055/https://www.thestate.com/sports/high-school/prep-basketball/article193382214.html |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson made his return from the injury on January 11, 2018, scoring 31 points in a 71\u201362 victory over [[Asheville Christian Academy]].<ref>{{cite web |title=High school basketball phenom Zion Williamson dominates in return to the court after injury |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/news/TEbDek4SU0uSEp22hFDsnQ/high-school-basketball-phenom-zion-williamson-dominates-in-return-to-the-court-after-injury.htm |publisher=[[MaxPreps]] |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |date=January 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121064231/http://www.maxpreps.com/news/TEbDek4SU0uSEp22hFDsnQ/high-school-basketball-phenom-zion-williamson-dominates-in-return-to-the-court-after-injury.htm |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On January 13, in a nationally televised game at the Hoophall Classic, he scored 36 points as his team lost to [[Chino Hills High School]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Johnson |first1=Chris |title=Viral Sensation Zion Williamson Picks Duke as Blue Devils Solidify Loaded 2018 Class |url=https://www.si.com/college-basketball/2018/01/20/zion-williamson-commits-duke-2018-recruiting |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |date=January 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121010849/https://www.si.com/college-basketball/2018/01/20/zion-williamson-commits-duke-2018-recruiting |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson tallied 30 points and 13 rebounds in his final home game on February 8, a 58\u201354 win over [[Greensboro Day School]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blackwell |first1=Jed |title=With a monster dunk, Zion Williamson closes out his final home game |url=https://www.goupstate.com/news/20180208/with-monster-dunk-zion-williamson-closes-out-his-final-home-game |website=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]] |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |date=February 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121065548/https://www.goupstate.com/news/20180208/with-monster-dunk-zion-williamson-closes-out-his-final-home-game |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On February 17, he posted 37 points, 10 rebounds, and 5 steals, while scoring his 3,000th career point, versus Spartanburg Christian Academy at the SCISA Region I-2A tournament.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Landreth |first1=Rob |title=Zion Williamson gets 3,000th career point to open SCISA tourney |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2018/video-zion-williamson-gets-3000th-career-point-to-open-scisa-tourney |newspaper=[[USA Today|USA Today High School Sports]] |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |date=February 17, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121064348/https://usatodayhss.com/2018/video-zion-williamson-gets-3000th-career-point-to-open-scisa-tourney |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> One week later, Williamson guided Spartanburg Day to its third consecutive SCISA Region I-2A championship after recording 38 points against [[Trinity Collegiate School]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Boardwine |first1=Andrew |title=Spartanburg Day, Zion Williamson, down Trinity-Byrnes in SCISA 2A title |url=https://www.scnow.com/sports/article_b6e410dc-1997-11e8-8774-db7fb564c145.html |website=[[The Morning News (American newspaper)|The Morning News]] |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |date=February 24, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180224230842/http://www.scnow.com/sports/article_b6e410dc-1997-11e8-8774-db7fb564c145.html |archive-date=February 24, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, Williamson played in the [[2018 McDonald's All-American Boys Game|2018 McDonald's All-American Game]], where he scored 8 points in 17 minutes before leaving with a thumb injury.<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Basketball Box Score \u2013 Game Totals \u2013 Final Statistics |url=https://www.mcdonaldsallamerican.com/content/dam/aag/AABOYS.pdf |publisher=[[McDonald's All-American Game]] |accessdate=January 21, 2019 |date=March 28, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003221127/https://www.mcdonaldsallamerican.com/content/dam/aag/AABOYS.pdf |archive-date=October 3, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Boone |first1=Kyle |title=Zion Williamson injury: Five-star Duke commit injures hand in McDonald's All-American Game |url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/zion-williamson-injury-five-star-duke-commit-injures-hand-in-mcdonalds-all-american-game/ |publisher=[[CBS Sports]] |accessdate=January 21, 2019 |date=March 29, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122094803/https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/zion-williamson-injury-five-star-duke-commit-injures-hand-in-mcdonalds-all-american-game/ |archive-date=January 22, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The injury also forced him to miss the [[Jordan Brand Classic]] and [[Nike Hoop Summit]] in the following month.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Zagoria |first1=Adam |title=Zion Williamson Sidelined For Jordan Brand Classic & Nike Hoop Summit |url=https://www.flohoops.com/articles/6170725-zion-williamson-sidelined-for-jordan-brand-classic-nike-hoop-summit |publisher=FloHoops |accessdate=January 22, 2019 |date=April 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190123071746/https://www.flohoops.com/articles/6170725-zion-williamson-sidelined-for-jordan-brand-classic-nike-hoop-summit |archive-date=January 23, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> For his 2017\u201318 high school season, Williamson was named to the ''USA Today'' All-USA first team and MaxPreps All-American second team.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Divens |first1=Jordan |title=2017\u201318 MaxPreps High School Boys Basketball All-American Team |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/news/vpYHC6-v2kiq_nCltCL9_Q/2017-18-maxpreps-high-school-boys-basketball-all-american-team-.htm |publisher=[[MaxPreps]] |accessdate=January 22, 2019 |date=April 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190123071708/http://www.maxpreps.com/news/vpYHC6-v2kiq_nCltCL9_Q/2017-18-maxpreps-high-school-boys-basketball-all-american-team-.htm |archive-date=January 23, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Halley |first1=Jim |title=ALL-USA Boys Basketball First Team: Zion Williamson, Spartanburg Day |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2018/all-usa-boys-basketball-first-team-zion-williamson-spartanburg-day |newspaper=[[USA Today|USA Today High School Sports]] |accessdate=January 22, 2019 |date=April 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121064221/https://usatodayhss.com/2018/all-usa-boys-basketball-first-team-zion-williamson-spartanburg-day |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He additionally earned [[South Carolina Mr. Basketball]] recognition and was runner-up for [[Mr. Basketball USA]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Flores |first1=Ronnie |title=All-Time Mr. Basketball USA Honorees |url=http://www.grassrootshoops.net/2018/04/all-time-mr-basketball-usa-honorees/ |publisher=Grassroots Hoops |accessdate=January 22, 2019 |date=April 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190123071737/http://www.grassrootshoops.net/2018/04/all-time-mr-basketball-usa-honorees/ |archive-date=January 23, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wertz Jr. |first1=Langston |title=UNC, Duke recruits named Mr. Basketball in North, South Carolina |url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/high-school/article207586694.html |website=[[The Charlotte Observer]] |accessdate=January 22, 2019 |date=March 31, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181109234950/https://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/high-school/article207586694.html |archive-date=November 9, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Recruiting===\n[[Wofford Terriers men's basketball|Wofford]] offered Williamson his first college basketball scholarship when he was a freshman in high school.<ref name=\"wofford\">{{cite web|last1=Fowler|first1=Scott|title=Basketball star Zion Williamson: 'Wide open' on recruiting, including ... Wofford?|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/college/article133115939.html|website=[[The Charlotte Observer]]|accessdate=January 14, 2018|date=February 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180115184538/http://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/college/article133115939.html|archive-date=January 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In the summer of 2015, Williamson emerged with the South Carolina Hornets AAU team as one of the top players in his class.<ref>{{cite web |title=Name to Know: 6'5\u2033 2018 Zion Williamson of Spartanburg Country Day (SC) |url=http://www.phenomhoopreport.com/name-to-know-65-2018-zion-williamson-of-spartanburg-country-day-sc/ |publisher=Phenom Hoop Report |accessdate=January 21, 2019 |date=September 15, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122094731/http://www.phenomhoopreport.com/name-to-know-65-2018-zion-williamson-of-spartanburg-country-day-sc/ |archive-date=January 22, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> By the end of his sophomore season, he received offers from 16 [[NCAA Division I]] programs, including [[Clemson Tigers men's basketball|Clemson]], [[Florida Gators men's basketball|Florida]], and [[South Carolina Gamecocks men's basketball|South Carolina]], but was not planning on making a decision until his senior year.<ref name=melton/> In the summer of 2016, Williamson was drawing the most attention from Clemson, Florida, [[North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball|North Carolina]], and South Carolina.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Meyer |first1=Jerry |title=Top247 No. 1 Zion Williamson lists four recruiting him hardest |url=https://247sports.com/Bolt/Clemson-Florida-North-Carolina-and-South-Carolina-recruiting-Zion-Williamson-the-hardest-46904188/ |publisher=[[247Sports.com|247Sports]] |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |date=August 22, 2016}}</ref> On August 30, 2016, he received a scholarship offer from [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rowe |first1=Adam |title=Duke offers 247Sports' #1 player in 2018, SF Zion Williamson |url=https://247sports.com/college/duke/Bolt/duke-basketball-recruiting-zion-williamson-offer-47069123/ |publisher=[[247Sports.com|247Sports]] |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |date=August 30, 2016}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> Williamson was also offered a [[American football|football]] scholarship by Eric Mateos, [[tight end]]s coach for [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]], but did not show interest.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Borzello |first1=Jeff |title=Ex-LSU asst.: Zion Williamson 'probably the best damn tight end to ever live' |url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/25280950/duke-sensation-zion-williamson-had-football-scholarship-offer-lsu |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=November 15, 2018 |date=November 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115201742/http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/25280950/duke-sensation-zion-williamson-had-football-scholarship-offer-lsu |archive-date=November 15, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Entering his junior season, he was a consensus five-star recruit and was ranked the number one player in the 2018 class by recruiting service [[247Sports.com|247Sports]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Zion Williamson takes over top spot in 247Sports' 2018 basketball player rankings |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2016/zion-williamson-takes-over-top-spot-in-247sports-2018-basketball-player-rankings |newspaper=[[USA Today|USA Today High School Sports]] |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |date=August 5, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125020306/https://usatodayhss.com/2016/zion-williamson-takes-over-top-spot-in-247sports-2018-basketball-player-rankings |archive-date=January 25, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2016, [[ESPN]] recruiting director Paul Biancardi touted Williamson as \"probably the best player in terms of production\" in his class.<ref name=usatodayhss/> By 2018, most recruiting experts predicted that he would play for Clemson.<ref>{{cite web |last1=O'Donnell |first1=Ricky |title=Clemson has become the surprise favorite for 5-star basketball recruit Zion Williamson |url=https://www.sbnation.com/college-basketball/2018/1/5/16856056/zion-williamson-recruiting-predictions-clemson-tigers-basketball-kentucky-duke-kansas |publisher=[[SB Nation]] |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |date=January 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190124203434/https://www.sbnation.com/college-basketball/2018/1/5/16856056/zion-williamson-recruiting-predictions-clemson-tigers-basketball-kentucky-duke-kansas |archive-date=January 24, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn a live ESPN telecast on January 20, 2018, Williamson committed to Duke.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Borzello |first1=Jeff |title=Zion Williamson pledge gives Duke top three players in ESPN 100 |url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/22163323/espn-100-recruit-zion-williamson-commits-duke-blue-devils |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |date=January 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122132616/http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/22163323/espn-100-recruit-zion-williamson-commits-duke-blue-devils |archive-date=January 22, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"brotherhood\">{{cite web |last1=Pope IV |first1=Jonas |title=Zion Williamson: 'I will be joining the brotherhood of Duke University' |url=https://www.newsobserver.com/sports/college/acc/unc/article195807054.html |website=[[The News & Observer]] |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |date=January 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125020914/https://www.newsobserver.com/sports/college/acc/unc/article195807054.html |archive-date=January 25, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He explained the decision, \"Duke stood out because the brotherhood represents a family. ([[Mike Krzyzewski]]) is just the most legendary coach that ever coached college basketball. I feel like going to [[Duke University]], I can learn a lot from him.\"<ref name=brotherhood/> Duke, who had landed [[RJ Barrett]] and [[Cam Reddish]] in addition to Williamson, became the first team to land the top three recruits in a class since modern recruiting rankings began.<ref name=\"top3\">{{cite web |last1=Roberts |first1=Ben |title=Duke has the top three basketball recruits in the country. Has that ever happened? |url=https://www.kentucky.com/sports/college/kentucky-sports/uk-basketball-men/article195908284.html |website=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]] |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |date=January 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824065807/https://www.kentucky.com/sports/college/kentucky-sports/uk-basketball-men/article195908284.html |archive-date=August 24, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> His stepfather Lee Anderson remarked that Clemson lost a \"mile-and-a-half lead\" in recruiting Williamson.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Connolly |first1=Matt |title=How could Clemson lose 'a mile-and-a-half lead' for Zion Williamson? |url=https://www.thestate.com/sports/college/acc/clemson-university/article196041029.html |website=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]] |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |date=January 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125073345/https://www.thestate.com/sports/college/acc/clemson-university/article196041029.html |archive-date=January 25, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Despite having three of the country's top recruits on their roster, Duke was unable to win the 2019 NCAA Tournament when they lost to Michigan State by one point in the East Regional Final.\n\n{{College athlete recruit start|collapse=no|year=2018}}\n{{College athlete recruit entry\n| recruit = Zion Williamson\n| position = [[Power forward (basketball)|PF]]\n| hometown = [[Spartanburg, South Carolina|Spartanburg, SC]]\n| highschool = [[Spartanburg Day School]] (SC)\n| feet = 6\n| inches = 6\n| weight = 272\n| 40 =\n| commitdate = January 20, 2018\n| scout stars = \n| rivals stars = 5\n| 247 stars = 5\n| espn stars = 5\n| espn grade = 96\n}}\n{{College athlete recruit end\n| 40 =\n| year = 2018\n| rivals ref title = Duke 2018 Basketball Commitments\n| scout ref title = \n| espn ref title = 2018 Duke Blue Devils Recruiting Class\n| 247 school =\n| rivals school = duke\n| scout s = \n| espn schoolid = 150\n| scout overall = \n| rivals overall = 5\n| 247 overall = 7\n| espn overall = 2\n| accessdate = January 14, 2018\n| bball = yes\n}}\n\n==College career==\n[[File:Zion Williamson Duke (cropped).jpg|thumb|235px|Williamson with Duke in December 2018]]\nWilliamson played in a preseason game for Duke on August 15, 2018, in an 86\u201367 win over Canadian university [[Ryerson Rams|Ryerson]], recording a [[double (basketball)|double-double]] of 29 points and 13 rebounds and shooting 3-of-4 from three-point range.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Boone |first1=Kyle |title=Duke's Zion Williamson, R.J. Barrett lead Blue Devils to exhibition rout of Ryerson |url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/dukes-zion-williamson-r-j-barrett-lead-blue-devils-to-exhibition-rout-of-ryerson/ |publisher=[[CBS Sports]] |accessdate=August 19, 2018 |date=August 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820005843/https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/dukes-zion-williamson-r-j-barrett-lead-blue-devils-to-exhibition-rout-of-ryerson/ |archive-date=August 20, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> He was named to the preseason watch lists for the [[Karl Malone Award]], [[Naismith College Player of the Year|Naismith Trophy]], and [[John R. Wooden Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.woodenaward.com/john_r_wooden_award_presented_by_wendy_s_announces_2018_19_preseason_top_50_watch_list|title=John R. Wooden Award Presented By Wendy's Announces 2018\u201319 Preseason Top 50 Watch List|website=[[John R. Wooden Award]]|date=November 6, 2018|accessdate=November 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108025819/http://www.woodenaward.com/john_r_wooden_award_presented_by_wendy_s_announces_2018_19_preseason_top_50_watch_list|archive-date=November 8, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://naismithtrophy.com/citizen-naismith-trophy-mens-watch-list-released/|title=Citizen Naismith Trophy Men's Watch List Released|website=[[Naismith College Player of the Year]]|publisher=Atlanta Tipoff Club|date=November 5, 2018|accessdate=November 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106053317/http://naismithtrophy.com/citizen-naismith-trophy-mens-watch-list-released/|archive-date=November 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncaa.com/news/basketball-men/article/2018-10-18/college-basketball-awards-20-power-forwards-named-karl|title=College basketball awards: 20 power forwards named to Karl Malone Award preseason watch list|website=ncaa.com|publisher=NCAA|date=October 18, 2018|accessdate=October 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181022232829/https://www.ncaa.com/news/basketball-men/article/2018-10-18/college-basketball-awards-20-power-forwards-named-karl|archive-date=October 22, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On November 6, in his first regular season game with Duke, Williamson scored 28 points on 11-of-13 shooting in 23 minutes in a 118\u201384 win over [[Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball|Kentucky]] at the [[Champions Classic]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Doyel |first1=Gregg |title=Meet Duke phenom Zion Williamson, the most unique college basketball player I've ever seen |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/2018/11/07/zion-williamson-duke-blue-devils/1917786002/ |website=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=November 8, 2018 |date=November 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107152619/https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/2018/11/07/zion-williamson-duke-blue-devils/1917786002/ |archive-date=November 7, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> In the game, he and teammate RJ Barrett each broke the Duke freshman debut scoring record set by [[Marvin Bagley III]].<ref>{{cite web |title=No. 4 Duke Topples No. 2 Kentucky 118\u201384 |url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211779280 |publisher=Duke Athletics |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |date=November 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117070213/http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211779280 |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In his following game, a 94\u201372 victory over [[Army Black Knights men's basketball|Army]], Williamson tallied 27 points, 16 rebounds, and 6 blocks.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rollins |first1=Khadrice |title=Zion Williamson's Almost-Perfect First Half Propels Duke to 22-Point Win Over Army |url=https://www.si.com/college-basketball/2018/11/11/duke-army-highlights-zion-williamson-rj-barrett-cam-reddish-video |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |date=November 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117070042/https://www.si.com/college-basketball/2018/11/11/duke-army-highlights-zion-williamson-rj-barrett-cam-reddish-video |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He became the second player in school history to record at least 25 points, 15 rebounds, and 5 blocks in a game.<ref name=\"pow1\">{{cite web |title=ACC Announces Weekly Basketball Honors |url=http://theacc.com/news/2018/11/12/mens-basketball-acc-announces-weekly-basketball-honors.aspx |publisher=[[Atlantic Coast Conference]] |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |date=November 12, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190211094634/http://theacc.com/news/2018/11/12/mens-basketball-acc-announces-weekly-basketball-honors.aspx |archive-date=February 11, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson was subsequently named both player and freshman of the week in the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] (ACC).<ref name=pow1/>\n\nOn January 5, 2019, he had another strong performance versus Clemson, with 25 points, 10 rebounds, and a 360-degree dunk in 22 minutes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Williamson Leads No. 1 Duke Past Clemson 87\u201368 |url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211785688 |publisher=Duke Athletics |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |date=January 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117070338/http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211785688 |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Two days later, Williamson earned ACC Freshman of the Week honors for a second time.<ref>{{cite web |title=Virginia's Guy, Duke's Williamson recognized |url=http://theacc.com/news/2019/1/7/mens-basketball-acc-announces-basketball-players-of-the-week.aspx |publisher=[[Atlantic Coast Conference]] |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |date=January 7, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190110072015/http://theacc.com/news/2019/1/7/mens-basketball-acc-announces-basketball-players-of-the-week.aspx |archive-date=January 10, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On January 8, he posted 30 points, 10 rebounds, 5 assists, and 4 steals in an 87\u201365 win over [[Wake Forest Demon Deacons men's basketball|Wake Forest]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hale |first1=David M. |title=Duke's Zion Williamson posts all-around gem in rout of Wake Forest |url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/25717739/duke-blue-devils-zion-williamson-does-all-vs-wake-forest |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |date=January 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190112135843/http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/25717739/duke-blue-devils-zion-williamson-does-all-vs-wake-forest |archive-date=January 12, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On January 12, against [[Florida State Seminoles men's basketball|Florida State]], he was poked in the left eye by an opposing player towards the second half and missed the remainder of the game.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wiseman |first1=Steve |title=Duke star Zion Williamson poked in left eye, suffers double vision |url=https://www.newsobserver.com/sports/article224439050.html |website=[[The News & Observer]] |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |date=January 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117070351/https://www.newsobserver.com/sports/article224439050.html |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson returned in Duke's next game, a 95\u201391 [[Overtime (sports)|overtime]] loss to [[Syracuse Orange men's basketball|Syracuse]], and erupted for 35 points, 10 rebounds, and 4 blocks.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Goldberg |first1=Rob |title=Tyus Battle's 32 Lead Syracuse to Shocking Upset Win over Zion Williamson, Duke |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2815699-tyus-battles-32-lead-syracuse-to-shocking-upset-win-over-zion-williamson-duke |website=[[Bleacher Report]] |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |date=January 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115082719/https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2815699-tyus-battles-32-lead-syracuse-to-shocking-upset-win-over-zion-williamson-duke |archive-date=January 15, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He eclipsed the Duke freshman record for single-game points previously held by Marvin Bagley III and [[J.J. Redick]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Duke University Men's Basketball Postgame Notes January 14, 2019 \u2013 vs. Syracuse |url=http://www.goduke.com/pdf9/5481322.pdf |publisher=Duke Athletics |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |date=January 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117122253/http://www.goduke.com/pdf9/5481322.pdf |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On January 21, Williamson collected his third ACC Freshman of the Week accolades.<ref>{{cite web |title=Williamson Grabs Third ACC Freshman of the Week Honor |url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_LANG=C&ATCLID=211787280&DB_OEM_ID=4200 |publisher=Duke Athletics |access-date=January 24, 2019 |date=January 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190123202618/http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_LANG=C&ATCLID=211787280&DB_OEM_ID=4200 |archive-date=January 23, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> One week later, he scored 26 points and grabbed 9 rebounds in an 81\u201363 victory over [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish men's basketball|Notre Dame]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/college/ct-spt-duke-notre-dame-zion-williamson-20190128-story.html|title=Zion Williamson leaves an impression on Notre Dame|last=|first=|date=|work=Chicago Tribune|access-date=January 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129164456/https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/college/ct-spt-duke-notre-dame-zion-williamson-20190128-story.html|archive-date=January 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> By recording nine 25-point games in the season, Williamson set a new Duke freshman record.<ref>{{cite web |title=Duke University Men's Basketball Postgame Notes January 28, 2019 \u2013 vs. Notre Dame |url=http://www.goduke.com/pdf9/5481935.pdf?_ga=2.29292281.459220722.1548735165-881145153.1546751298 |publisher=Duke Athletics |access-date=March 9, 2019 |date=January 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190206134255/http://www.goduke.com/pdf9/5481935.pdf?_ga=2.29292281.459220722.1548735165-881145153.1546751298 |archive-date=February 6, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On February 2, he led all scorers with 29 points and 5 steals in a 91\u201361 win over [[St. John's Red Storm men's basketball|St. John's]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Williamson's 29 leads No. 2 Duke to 91-61 rout of St. John's |url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401082685 |website=[[ESPN]] |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=March 9, 2019 |date=February 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190304145945/http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401082685 |archive-date=March 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> After two days, Williamson was named ACC Freshman of the Week on his fourth occasion, while earning National Player of the Week distinction from the Naismith Trophy.<ref>{{cite web |title=Williamson Named National Player, ACC Freshman of the Week |url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211789182 |publisher=Duke Athletics |access-date=March 9, 2019 |date=February 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404171520/http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211789182 |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He had his third 30-point game of the season on February 16, scoring 32 points in a 94\u201378 victory over [[NC State Wolfpack men's basketball|NC State]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Barrett has triple-double, No. 2 Duke beats NC State, 94-78 |url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401082688 |website=[[ESPN]] |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=March 9, 2019 |date=February 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190314061122/http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401082688 |archive-date=March 14, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The performance helped him claim his second ACC Player of the Week and fifth ACC Freshman of the Week accolades.<ref>{{cite web |title=Duke's Williamson sweeps ACC weekly honors |url=http://theacc.com/news/2019/2/18/mens-basketball-dukes-williamson-sweeps-acc-weekly-honors.aspx |publisher=[[Atlantic Coast Conference]] |access-date=March 9, 2019 |date=February 18, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222051029/http://www.theacc.com/news/2019/2/18/mens-basketball-dukes-williamson-sweeps-acc-weekly-honors.aspx |archive-date=February 22, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> \n{{multiple image\n<!-- Essential parameters -->\n| align = left\n| direction = horizontal\n| width = 170\n| image1 = ZION WILLIAMSON (cropped) 2.jpg\n| width1 = \n| alt1 = \n| caption1 =\n| image3 = ZION WILLIAMSON 2 (cropped).jpg\n| width3 =\n| alt3 = \n| caption3 =\n| header = Williamson out with knee injury in February 2019\n| header_align = <!-- left/right/center -->\n| header_background = \n| footer = Williamson sits on the bench during a game versus [[Virginia Tech Hokies men's basketball|Virginia Tech]] with an injury suffered from a broken shoe. He walks on the court during a media timeout.\n| footer_align = <!-- left/right/center -->\n| footer_background = \n| background color = \n}}\nIn a February 20 game versus [[North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball|North Carolina]], Williamson suffered a Grade 1 knee [[sprain]] 36 seconds into the contest after his foot ripped through his [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] shoe, causing him to slip.<ref>{{cite news |date=February 21, 2019 |title=Zion Williamson felled by faulty Nike as North Carolina blast top-ranked Duke |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/feb/21/zion-shoe-duke-north-carolina-nike |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=February 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190221233601/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/feb/21/zion-shoe-duke-north-carolina-nike |archive-date=February 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"2021 Gleeson\">{{cite news |last=Gleeson |first=Scott |date=February 21, 2019 |title=Duke star Zion Williamson considered 'day-to-day' with a knee sprain |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/acc/2019/02/21/zion-williamson-duke-day-to-day-knee-sprain-injury/2936664002/ |work=USA Today |accessdate=February 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222055501/https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/acc/2019/02/21/zion-williamson-duke-day-to-day-knee-sprain-injury/2936664002/ |archive-date=February 22, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He did not return to the game, which Duke lost, 88\u201372.<ref>{{cite web |title=With Zion injured, No. 8 UNC routs No. 1 Duke 88-72 |url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401082689 |website=[[ESPN]] |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=March 9, 2019 |date=February 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190304044636/http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401082689 |archive-date=March 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Nike saw the value of its [[stock market|stock]] drop by $1.1 billion the following day as a result of the incident.<ref>{{cite news |last=Drury |first=Colin |date=February 22, 2019 |title=Nike stock market value plunges by $1.1bn after basketball star Zion Williamson's shoe breaks |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/nike-share-price-zion-williamson-shoe-duke-blue-devils-north-california-stock-a8791476.html |work=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=February 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222113408/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/nike-share-price-zion-williamson-shoe-duke-blue-devils-north-california-stock-a8791476.html |archive-date=February 22, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Alexander |first=Chip |date=February 21, 2019 |title=Zion Williamson's shoe blowout, knee injury leads to blowback for Nike |url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/article226570779.html |work=Charlotte Observer |access-date=February 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404155021/https://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/article226570779.html |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The day after the injury, Duke announced that Williamson was \"day-to-day\".<ref name=\"2021 Gleeson\" /> The incident led to growing calls for Williamson to stop playing basketball at the college level because he had already established himself as the top [[2019 NBA draft]] prospect.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jenkins |first1=Sally |title=Zion Williamson injury makes clear: The NCAA has turned education into a risk |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/colleges/zion-williamson-injury-makes-clear-the-ncaa-has-turned-education-into-a-risk/2019/02/21/6f14fd56-35f3-11e9-af5b-b51b7ff322e9_story.html |website=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=March 11, 2019 |date=February 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190311144943/https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/colleges/zion-williamson-injury-makes-clear-the-ncaa-has-turned-education-into-a-risk/2019/02/21/6f14fd56-35f3-11e9-af5b-b51b7ff322e9_story.html |archive-date=March 11, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wertz Jr. |first1=Langston |title=NBA players urge Zion Williamson to shut it down after bizarre injury during UNC game |url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/latest-news/article226561629.html |website=[[The Charlotte Observer]] |access-date=March 11, 2019 |date=February 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190303064836/https://www.charlotteobserver.com/latest-news/article226561629.html |archive-date=March 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, the injury resulted in more criticism of the NCAA for not paying student-athletes.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sullivan |first1=Tim |title=Zion Williamson's injury underscores the inequities of college sports |url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/2019/02/21/zion-williamson-injury-underscores-inequities-ncaa-sports/2937819002/ |website=[[The Courier-Journal]] |access-date=March 11, 2019 |date=February 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Gregory |first1=Sean |title=Zion Williamson's Exploding Shoe Is a Reminder That College Basketball Needs Serious Fixing |url=http://time.com/5534615/zion-williamson-shoe-college-basketball/ |website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |access-date=March 11, 2019 |date=February 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190305050022/http://time.com/5534615/zion-williamson-shoe-college-basketball/ |archive-date=March 5, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Skinner |first1=Nancy |title=How to pay NCAA athletes like Zion Williamson without costing colleges a dime |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2019/02/26/how-pay-ncaa-athletes-without-costing-colleges-dime/ |website=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=March 11, 2019 |date=February 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190305155957/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2019/02/26/how-pay-ncaa-athletes-without-costing-colleges-dime/ |archive-date=March 5, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He was held out from his team's final six games in the regular season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Zion Williamson Caps Stunning Return, Leading Duke to A.C.C. Title |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/17/sports/college-basketball-tournaments-zion-williamson.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=April 3, 2019 |date=March 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404144058/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/17/sports/college-basketball-tournaments-zion-williamson.html |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> When the regular season concluded, Williamson earned [[Atlantic Coast Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year|Player of the Year]] and [[Atlantic Coast Conference Men's Basketball Rookie of the Year|Rookie of the Year]] honors in the ACC, joining former Duke players [[Jahlil Okafor]] and Marvin Bagley III as the only recipients of both awards. Williamson was also named [[ACC Athlete of the Year]], becoming the 10th Duke player to win the Award.<ref>{{Cite news|url= http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=22737&SPID=1845&DB_LANG=C&DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211806496|title=Williamson Voted ACC Male Athlete of the Year|last=|first=|date=|work=www.goduke.com|access-date=July 25, 2019}}</ref> He additionally made the ACC All-Defensive and All-Freshman teams.<ref>{{cite web |title=ACC 2019 Men's Basketball All-Conference Team, Postseason Awards |url=https://accsports.com/acc-news/acc-2019-mens-basketball-all-conference-team-postseason-awards/ |publisher=[[Atlantic Coast Conference]] |access-date=March 11, 2019 |date=March 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330211136/https://accsports.com/acc-news/acc-2019-mens-basketball-all-conference-team-postseason-awards/ |archive-date=March 30, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Sporting News]]'' named Williamson as its [[Sporting News Men's College Basketball Player of the Year|Player of the Year]] and Freshman of the Year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=DeCourcy |first1=Mike |title=Duke's Zion Williamson is Sporting News Player, Freshman of the Year |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/us/ncaa-basketball/news/dukes-zion-williamson-is-sporting-news-player-freshman-of-the-year/rnnni0dhtiwzcfrcty42nm6 |website=[[Sporting News]] |access-date=March 15, 2019 |date=March 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190314144805/http://www.sportingnews.com/us/ncaa-basketball/news/dukes-zion-williamson-is-sporting-news-player-freshman-of-the-year/rnnni0dhtiwzcfrcty42nm6 |archive-date=March 14, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He returned from injury on March 14, posting 29 points, 14 rebounds, and 5 steals in an 84\u201372 win over Syracuse in the quarterfinals of the [[2019 ACC Men's Basketball Tournament|ACC Tournament]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tracy |first1=Marc |title=Zion Williamson Returns in Style, Leading Duke to Victory Over Syracuse |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/14/sports/duke-zion-williamson-returns.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=March 15, 2019 |date=March 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190315174326/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/14/sports/duke-zion-williamson-returns.html |archive-date=March 15, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He shot 13-of-13 from the field, marking the best shooting performance in school and tournament history, while tying the best in ACC history.<ref>{{cite web |title=Duke University Men's Basketball Postgame Notes March 14, 2019 \u2013 vs. Syracuse (ACC Tournament Quarterfinals) |url=http://www.goduke.com/pdf9/5485015.pdf?_ga=2.249588290.514877976.1552629767-814154638.1552629766 |publisher=Duke Athletics |access-date=March 15, 2019 |date=March 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190322011420/http://www.goduke.com/pdf9/5485015.pdf?_ga=2.249588290.514877976.1552629767-814154638.1552629766 |archive-date=March 22, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson also became the first Duke player to record at least 25 points, 10 rebounds, and 5 steals in a game since [[Christian Laettner]] in 1992.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Parrish |first1=Gary |title=Duke remains No. 5 in Top 25 And 1 after Zion Williamson's incredible return |url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/college-basketball-rankings-duke-remains-no-5-in-top-25-and-1-after-zion-williamsons-incredible-return/ |publisher=[[CBS Sports]] |access-date=March 15, 2019 |date=March 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404171457/https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/college-basketball-rankings-duke-remains-no-5-in-top-25-and-1-after-zion-williamsons-incredible-return/ |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The next day, he scored 31 points including the game-winner to help Duke defeat North Carolina, 74\u201373, in the ACC Tournament semifinals.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jones |first1=Jonathan |title=Zion Williamson Puts on a Show in Classic Duke-UNC Rivalry Game |url=https://www.si.com/college-basketball/2019/03/16/zion-williamson-puts-show-duke-defeats-unc-acc-tourney |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=April 3, 2019 |date=March 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404144101/https://www.si.com/college-basketball/2019/03/16/zion-williamson-puts-show-duke-defeats-unc-acc-tourney |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> After posting 21 points in a 73\u201363 victory over Florida State in the championship game, Williamson was named ACC Tournament MVP, becoming the sixth freshman to win the honor.<ref>{{cite web |title=Duke Beats FSU for Program's 21st ACC Title |url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211795899 |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=April 3, 2019 |date=March 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404155053/http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211795899 |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFor the [[2019 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|2019 NCAA Tournament]], official broadcast partner [[CBS]] specifically devoted a camera\u2014called the \"Zion Cam\"\u2014to record Williamson throughout the tournament.<ref name=\"zioncam\">{{cite web |last1=Lauletta |first1=Tyler |title=CBS hired a special cameraman to work the 'Zion Cam' and record every move the Duke star makes in his NCAA tournament run |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/zion-williamson-cbs-cam-march-madness-2019-3 |website=[[Business Insider]] |accessdate=April 3, 2019 |date=March 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404144059/https://www.businessinsider.com/zion-williamson-cbs-cam-march-madness-2019-3 |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In his NCAA Tournament debut on March 22, he scored 25 points in an 85\u201362 win over 16th-seeded [[North Dakota State Bison men's basketball|North Dakota State]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Top-Seeded Duke Beats NDSU, 85-62, in NCAA Opener |url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211796767 |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=April 3, 2019 |date=March 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401030801/http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211796767 |archive-date=April 1, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On March 24, Williamson erupted for 32 points, 11 rebounds, and 4 assists in a 77\u201376 second round victory over [[UCF Knights men's basketball|UCF]]. He was the first player in school history to record at least 25 points, 10 rebounds, and 4 assists in an NCAA Tournament game.<ref>{{cite web |title=Duke University Men's Basketball Postgame Notes March 24, 2019 \u2013 vs. UCF |url=http://www.goduke.com/pdf9/5485603.pdf |publisher=Duke Athletics |accessdate=April 3, 2019 |date=March 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404144057/http://www.goduke.com/pdf9/5485603.pdf |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson led all scorers on March 31, with 24 points and 14 rebounds in a season-ending 68\u201367 loss to [[Michigan State Spartans men's basketball|Michigan State]] in the Elite 8.<ref>{{cite web |title=Duke Falls to Michigan State, 68-67 |url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211797994 |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=April 3, 2019 |date=March 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401145312/http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211797994 |archive-date=April 1, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Through 33 appearances in his freshman season, he averaged 22.6 points, 8.9 rebounds, 2.1 steals, and 1.8 blocks per game.<ref name=\"stats\">{{cite web |title=Zion Williamson Stats |url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/player/stats/_/id/4395628/zion-williamson |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=April 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401220400/http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/player/stats/_/id/4395628/zion-williamson |archive-date=April 1, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He shot 68% from the field, which led the ACC, ranked second in the NCAA Division I, and was the highest ever field goal percentage by a freshman.<ref>{{cite web |title=Zion Williamson Named NABC Player, Freshman of the Year |url=https://dukereport.com/duke-basketball/zion-williamson-named-nabc-player-freshman-of-the-year-dis/ |publisher=Duke Report |accessdate=April 3, 2019 |date=April 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404144059/https://dukereport.com/duke-basketball/zion-williamson-named-nabc-player-freshman-of-the-year-dis/ |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"nola\">{{cite web |last1=Duncan |first1=Jeff |title=Zion Williamson could transform basketball in New Orleans and the Pelicans must do everything they can to get him |url=https://www.nola.com/pelicans/2019/04/zion-williamson-could-transform-basketball-in-new-orleans-and-the-pelicans-must-try-to-get-him.html |website=[[The Times-Picayune]] |accessdate=April 3, 2019 |date=April 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404144059/https://www.nola.com/pelicans/2019/04/zion-williamson-could-transform-basketball-in-new-orleans-and-the-pelicans-must-try-to-get-him.html |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, Williamson joined [[Kevin Durant]] and [[Anthony Davis]] as the only freshmen to collect 500 points, 50 steals, and 50 blocks in a season.<ref name=nola/>\n\nOn April 15, 2019, Williamson declared his eligibility for the 2019 NBA draft.<ref>{{cite web |title=Zion declares for draft after 'best year' of life |url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/26532333/zion-declares-draft-best-year-life |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=May 17, 2019 |date=April 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424015808/http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/26532333/zion-declares-draft-best-year-life |archive-date=April 24, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> After the [[New Orleans Pelicans]] won the 2019 [[NBA draft lottery]], Williamson's stepfather Lee Anderson said they were excited about him potentially playing in New Orleans and dismissed rumors that he would return to Duke for a second year, saying, \"As far as returning to Duke, that's not something we've even considered.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shapiro |first1=Michael |title=Zion Williamson's Stepfather Says Former Duke Star Won't Return to College After Pelicans Won Lottery |url=https://www.si.com/nba/2019/05/16/zion-williamson-pelicans-nba-draft-lottery-duke-freshman |website=SI.com |accessdate=May 17, 2019 |date=May 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190516153242/https://www.si.com/nba/2019/05/16/zion-williamson-pelicans-nba-draft-lottery-duke-freshman |archive-date=May 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nOn June 20, 2019, the [[New Orleans Pelicans]] drafted Williamson with the first pick in the [[2019 NBA draft]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/27018830|title=Pelicans pick Zion to open draft, Morant goes 2nd|date=June 20, 2019|website=ESPN.com|access-date=June 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621074618/https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/27018830|archive-date=June 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/basketball/48716152|title=NBA draft: Zion Williamson is selected first by the New Orleans Pelicans|date=June 21, 2019|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=June 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621113729/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/basketball/48716152|archive-date=June 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On July 1, 2019, Williamson officially signed with the Pelicans.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pelicans sign Zion Williamson |url=https://www.nba.com/pelicans/pelicans-sign-zion-williamson |website=NBA.com |accessdate=July 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701203732/https://www.nba.com/pelicans/pelicans-sign-zion-williamson |archive-date=July 1, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson tore his [[Tear of meniscus|meniscus]] on October 13, 2019, during the preseason of his rookie campaign.<ref>{{cite web |title=Where is Zion Williamson? |url=https://www.sbnation.com/nba/2019/12/25/21036567/zion-williamson-injury-new-orleans-pelicans-why-isnt-he-playing |website=sbnation.com |accessdate=December 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191226035102/https://www.sbnation.com/nba/2019/12/25/21036567/zion-williamson-injury-new-orleans-pelicans-why-isnt-he-playing |archive-date=December 26, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson made his professional debut three months later on January 22, 2020 in a 121\u2013117 loss to the [[San Antonio Spurs]]. He played 18 minutes and finished with 22 points and 7 rebounds, scoring 17 consecutive points in 3:08 minutes during the fourth quarter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28542223/pelicans-zion-williamson-erupts-17-4th-sits-final-minutes-debut|title=Pelicans' Zion Williamson erupts for 17 in 4th, sits out final minutes of debut|website=espn.com|publisher=ESPN|first=Andrew|last=Lopez|date=January 22, 2020|accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref> He would later become the first teenager in NBA history to score 20+ points in 10 consecutive games.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Young |first1=Ryan |title=Zion Williamson becomes first teenager in NBA history with 10 straight 20-point games |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/new-orleans-pelicans-zion-williamson-first-teenager-nba-history-10-straight-20-point-games-034707525.html |website=sports.yahoo.com |accessdate=April 18, 2020 |date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> On March 1, Williamson scored a career-high 35 points, along with 7 rebounds, in a 122\u2013114 loss to the [[Los Angeles Lakers]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Botkin |first1=Brad |title=Zion Williamson goes toe to toe with LeBron James, extends teenage record with a career-high 35 points |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/zion-williamson-goes-toe-to-toe-with-lebron-james-extends-teenage-record-with-a-career-high-35-points/ |website=cbssports.com |accessdate=April 18, 2020 |date=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Player profile==\n[[File:Zion Williamson - Keenan Hairston (cropped).jpg|thumb|Williamson goes in for a slam dunk against [[Hartford Hawks men's basketball|Hartford]], December 2018]]\nWilliamson is listed at {{Height|ft=6|in=6}} tall and weighs {{convert|285|lbs|kg|0}}.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |title=Zion Williamson |url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211767525 |publisher=[[Duke Blue Devils]] |accessdate=August 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822020553/http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211767525 |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Boone |first1=Kyle |title=Why 5-star Zion Williamson would fit better at Clemson than Kentucky, Kansas, or Duke |url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/why-5-star-zion-williamson-would-fit-better-at-clemson-than-kentucky-kansas-or-duke/ |publisher=[[CBS Sports]] |accessdate=August 20, 2018 |date=January 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822014952/https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/why-5-star-zion-williamson-would-fit-better-at-clemson-than-kentucky-kansas-or-duke/ |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Despite his heavy weight for a basketball player, he is known for his speed and [[Vertical jump|leaping]] ability.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Phillips |first1=Scott |title=Zion Williamson breaks Duke vertical leap record |url=https://collegebasketball.nbcsports.com/2018/07/07/zion-williamson-breaks-duke-vertical-leap-record/ |publisher=[[NBC Sports]] |accessdate=August 21, 2018 |date=July 7, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"willitwork\">{{cite web |last1=O'Donnell |first1=Ricky |title=We've never seen anyone like Zion Williamson ... but will his game work in the NBA? |url=https://www.sbnation.com/2017/10/19/16454852/zion-williamson-recruit-highlights-nba |publisher=[[SB Nation]] |accessdate=August 21, 2018 |date=October 19, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822014950/https://www.sbnation.com/2017/10/19/16454852/zion-williamson-recruit-highlights-nba |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> NBA player [[Kevin Durant]] described him as a \"once-in-a-generation type athlete\" while an anonymous [[college basketball]] coach labeled him a \"freak of nature\".<ref name=\"johnson\">{{cite web |last1=Johnson |first1=Chris |title=Zion Williamson: Basketball's next dunking prodigy |url=https://www.si.com/longform/2017/zion-williamson-basketball-dunks-high-school/index.html |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=August 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707010252/https://www.si.com/longform/2017/zion-williamson-basketball-dunks-high-school/index.html |archive-date=July 7, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"durant\">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Cam |title=Kevin Durant on Zion Williamson: 'He's a once-in-a-generation type athlete' |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2017/kevin-durant-on-zion-williamson-hes-a-once-in-a-generation-type-athlete |newspaper=[[USA Today|USA Today High School Sports]] |accessdate=August 20, 2018 |date=November 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822014842/https://usatodayhss.com/2017/kevin-durant-on-zion-williamson-hes-a-once-in-a-generation-type-athlete |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson plays the [[power forward (basketball)|power forward]] position but is also capable of being a [[Small ball (basketball)|small-ball]] [[center (basketball)|center]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Westerholm |first1=Tony |title=Zion Williamson to Duke: Three takeaways as hyper-athletic forward joins Blue Devils mens basketball |url=https://www.masslive.com/hoophallclassic/index.ssf/2018/01/zion_williamson_to_duke_four_t.html |website=[[The Republican (Springfield, Massachusetts)|The Republican]] |accessdate=August 20, 2018 |date=January 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822045938/https://www.masslive.com/hoophallclassic/index.ssf/2018/01/zion_williamson_to_duke_four_t.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> However, he is best played as a forward due to his size. He has been described as not fitting a specific [[basketball positions|basketball position]].<ref name=\"gauntlet\">{{cite web|last1=Bossi|first1=Eric|title=Adidas Gauntlet: Feeding frenzy for five-star Langford|url=https://basketballrecruiting.rivals.com/news/adidas-gauntlet-feeding-frenzy-for-five-star-langford|website=[[Rivals.com]]|accessdate=January 14, 2018|date=April 18, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180115184704/https://basketballrecruiting.rivals.com/news/adidas-gauntlet-feeding-frenzy-for-five-star-langford|archive-date=January 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> His physical attributes have drawn comparisons to former NBA stars [[Charles Barkley]], [[Anthony Mason (basketball)|Anthony Mason]], and [[Larry Johnson (basketball, born 1969)|Larry Johnson]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Astramskas |first1=David |title=The Insane Growth Of The Man-Child That Is Zion Williamson |url=http://ballislife.com/zion-williamson-size/ |website=ballislife.com |accessdate=April 18, 2020 |date=August 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Bossi |first1=Eric |last2=Evans |first2=Corey |title=Rival Views: The best Zion Williamson comparison |url=https://basketballrecruiting.rivals.com/news/rival-views-the-best-zion-williamson-comparison |publisher=[[Rivals.com|Rivals]] |accessdate=August 20, 2018 |date=January 18, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822045958/https://basketballrecruiting.rivals.com/news/rival-views-the-best-zion-williamson-comparison |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, according to different analysts, he resembles NBA players [[LeBron James]] and [[Julius Randle]].<ref name=gauntlet/> Lee Sartor, Williamson's high school coach, reported that basketball coach [[Roy Williams (coach)|Roy Williams]] told Williamson \"that he was probably one of the best high school players he's seen since Michael Jordan\".<ref name=\"nextlebron\">{{cite web|last1=Fowler|first1=Scott|title=Is SC dunking phenom Zion Williamson basketball's next LeBron James?|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/spt-columns-blogs/scott-fowler/article133103369.html|website=[[The Charlotte Observer]]|accessdate=January 14, 2018|date=February 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108014943/http://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/spt-columns-blogs/scott-fowler/article133103369.html|archive-date=January 8, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson, who is [[handedness|left-handed]], is almost [[ambidextrous]], being adept using either hand.<ref name=gauntlet/>\n\nWhile in high school, Williamson drew national attention for his [[slam dunk]]s.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wiseman |first1=Steve |title=Duke's Zion Williamson talks dunks, his fame and learning from Coach K |url=https://www.myajc.com/sports/duke-zion-williamson-talks-dunks-his-fame-and-learning-from-coach/t2VPgpHpdUwLFWGFvXfglJ/ |website=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]] |accessdate=August 20, 2018 |date=August 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822014738/https://www.myajc.com/sports/duke-zion-williamson-talks-dunks-his-fame-and-learning-from-coach/t2VPgpHpdUwLFWGFvXfglJ/ |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Charlotte Observer]]'' remarked that he \"could be the best high-school dunker in history\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fowler |first1=Scott |title=Is Zion Williamson the best prep dunker ever? Watch this video from ONE GAME and drool |url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/spt-columns-blogs/scott-fowler/article132589769.html |website=[[The Charlotte Observer]] |accessdate=August 21, 2018 |date=February 14, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822015001/https://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/spt-columns-blogs/scott-fowler/article132589769.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> NBA point guard [[John Wall (basketball)|John Wall]] has likened Williamson's in-game dunking ability to that of [[Vince Carter]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nelson |first1=Ryne |title=John Wall: Zion Williamson Is Top 2\u20133 'Most Athletic Player I've Ever Seen' |url=https://www.slamonline.com/nba/john-wall-zion-williamson-top-2-3-most-athletic-player-ever-seen/ |website=[[Slam (magazine)|Slam]] |accessdate=August 20, 2018 |date=August 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824080552/http://www.slamonline.com/nba/john-wall-zion-williamson-top-2-3-most-athletic-player-ever-seen/ |archive-date=August 24, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson's outside shooting has been considered a point of concern, and he has unorthodox shot mechanics.<ref name=legend/><ref name=washpost/><ref name=\"stepien\">{{cite web |last1=Gribanov |first1=Mike |title=Draft Profile: Zion Williamson |url=https://www.thestepien.com/zion-williamson/ |publisher=The Stepien |accessdate=August 21, 2018 |date=November 11, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822014757/https://www.thestepien.com/zion-williamson/ |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Recruiting service [[247Sports.com|247Sports]] has praised his [[dribbling|ball handling]] and passing skills for his size, commenting that they are \"overshadowed by [his] athletic plays\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Flaherty |first1=Kevin |title=YouTube star Zion Williamson creates challenge for evaluators |url=https://247sports.com/Article/Duke-basketball-recruit-Zion-Williamson-could-have-unique-fits-in-college-and-NBA-game-117476807/ |publisher=[[247Sports.com|247Sports]] |accessdate=August 21, 2018 |date=April 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822014813/https://247sports.com/Article/Duke-basketball-recruit-Zion-Williamson-could-have-unique-fits-in-college-and-NBA-game-117476807/ |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson has the ability to defend multiple positions well due to his speed and length, although his defensive effort has been questioned.<ref name=\"westerholm\">{{cite web |last1=Westerholm |first1=Tom |title=Zion Williamson Scouting: How does the freakishly athletic HS forward project to the NBA? |url=https://www.masslive.com/hoophallclassic/index.ssf/2018/01/scouting_zion_williamson_how_d.html |website=[[The Republican (Springfield, Massachusetts)|The Republican]] |accessdate=August 21, 2018 |date=January 14, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822014747/https://www.masslive.com/hoophallclassic/index.ssf/2018/01/scouting_zion_williamson_how_d.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> His explosive play makes him a reliable [[block (basketball)|shot-blocker]] and gives him prowess as a [[rebound (basketball)|rebounder]].<ref name=\"realgm\">{{cite web |last1=Uehara |first1=Rafael |title=Prospect Report: Zion Williamson Of Duke |url=https://basketball.realgm.com/analysis/250890/Prospect-Report-Zion-Williamson-Of-Duke |publisher=[[RealGM]] |accessdate=August 21, 2018 |date=August 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180802113204/https://basketball.realgm.com/analysis/250890/Prospect-Report-Zion-Williamson-Of-Duke |archive-date=August 2, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===College===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2018\u201319 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2018\u201319]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2018\u201319 Duke Blue Devils men's basketball team|Duke]]\n| 33 || 33 || 30.0 || .680 || .338 || .640 || 8.9 || 2.1 || 2.1 || 1.8 || 22.6\n{{s-end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nWilliamson was born in [[Salisbury, North Carolina]] to Lateef Williamson and Sharonda Sampson.<ref name=\"growthspurt\">{{cite web|last1=Wertz, Jr.|first1=Langston|title=One of nation's top basketball recruits resides in Spartanburg, says Coach K offered scholarship|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/high-school/article112797658.html|website=[[The Charlotte Observer]]|accessdate=April 7, 2017|date=November 5, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170405170554/http://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/high-school/article112797658.html|archive-date=April 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Lateef was a football [[Lineman (gridiron football)|defensive lineman]] at [[Mayo High School for Math, Science, and Technology|Mayo High School]] in [[Darlington, South Carolina]] who was a 1993 High School All-American and had committed to [[NC State Wolfpack football|NC State]] before transferring to [[Livingstone College]].<ref name=legend/><ref name=growthspurt/> Sampson was a [[Sprint (running)|sprinter]] at Livingstone and became a middle school health and physical education teacher.<ref name=growthspurt/> She named Williamson after the [[Bible|biblical]] location [[Mount Zion]] near [[Jerusalem]], taking her grandmother's advice to name him \"something extra special\".<ref name=\"finest\">{{cite web|last1=Bezjak|first1=Lou|title=Williamson drawing attention as one of 2018's finest|url=http://www.thestate.com/sports/high-school/prep-basketball/article105425861.html|website=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]]|accessdate=April 7, 2017|date=October 1, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408083909/http://www.thestate.com/sports/high-school/prep-basketball/article105425861.html|archive-date=April 8, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> When Williamson reached two years of age, following the death of his maternal grandmother, his family moved to [[Florence, South Carolina]].<ref name=legend/><ref name=growthspurt/> By the time he was five years old, his parents divorced, and his mother married Lee Anderson, a former [[Clemson Tigers men's basketball|Clemson]] basketball player.<ref name=\"usatodayhss\">{{cite news|last1=Jordan|first1=Jason|title=Chick-fil-A Classic: Zion Williamson is taking the country by storm|url=http://usatodayhss.com/2016/chick-fil-a-classic-zion-williamson-is-taking-the-country-by-storm-duke-kentucky-north-carolina-drake|newspaper=[[USA Today|USA Today High School Sports]]|accessdate=April 7, 2017|date=December 23, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170409021041/http://usatodayhss.com/2016/chick-fil-a-classic-zion-williamson-is-taking-the-country-by-storm-duke-kentucky-north-carolina-drake|archive-date=April 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"legend\">{{cite web|last1=Fowler|first1=Scott|title=The legend of basketball phenom Zion Williamson|url=http://www.kentucky.com/sports/college/kentucky-sports/uk-recruiting/article133179434.html|website=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]|accessdate=April 7, 2017|date=February 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408082436/http://www.kentucky.com/sports/college/kentucky-sports/uk-recruiting/article133179434.html|archive-date=April 8, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn July 23, 2019, Williamson signed a five-year, $75 million shoe deal with [[Air Jordan|Jordan brand]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Zagoria |first1=Adam |title=Zion Williamson Signs Multiyear Deal With Jordan Brand |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/adamzagoria/2019/07/23/zion-williamson-signs-multi-year-deal-with-jordan-brand/#3136ef9317e2 |website=Forbes |accessdate=April 18, 2020 |date=July 23, 2019}}</ref> Williamson's deal is the second-largest rookie shoe deal in history, trailing only LeBron James's $90 million rookie deal signed in 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.si.com/nba/2019/07/24/zion-williamson-jordan-brand-shoe-deal-75-million-five-years|title=Report: Zion's shoe deal worth $75 million over five years|last=Abdeldaiem|first=Alaa|website=Sports Illustrated|access-date=December 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209201923/https://www.si.com/nba/2019/07/24/zion-williamson-jordan-brand-shoe-deal-75-million-five-years|archive-date=December 9, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nOn March 13, 2020, Williamson pledged to pay for the salaries of all the employees of the [[Smoothie King Center]] for 30 days during the [[suspension of the 2019-20 NBA season]] because of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic|the coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Giannis Antetokounmpo, Zion Williamson among stars aiding arena workers |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28898869/giannis-antetokounmpo-pledges-100k-help-fiserv-forum-staff |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{basketballstats|nba=zion_williamson|bbr=w/willizi01}}\n* [http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211767525 Duke Blue Devils bio]\n* [http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/26406892/the-education-zion-williamson The Education of Zion Williamson]\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{New Orleans Pelicans current roster}}\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{2019 NBA draft}}\n{{NBA NumberOne Draft Picks}}\n{{Naismith Player of the Year men}}\n{{Wooden Player of the Year men}}\n{{Oscar Robertson Trophy}}\n{{Associated Press College Basketball Player of the Year}}\n{{NABC Player of the Year}}\n{{Sporting News College Men's Basketball Player of the Year}}\n{{2019 NCAA Men's Basketball Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{Atlantic Coast Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year navbox}}\n{{ACC Athlete of the Year navbox}}\n{{USBWA National Freshman of the Year}}\n{{Karl Malone Award}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|Sports}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williamson, Zion}}\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American basketball players]]\n[[Category:All-American college men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Duke Blue Devils men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:McDonald's High School All-Americans]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Pelicans draft picks]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Pelicans players]]\n[[Category:People from Salisbury, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Power forwards (basketball)]]\n[[Category:Small forwards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Spartanburg, South Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American basketball player}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Zion Williamson\n| image = Zion Williamson (49488462157) (cropped).jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Williamson with the Pelicans in 2020\n| number = 1\n| team = New Orleans Pelicans\n| position = [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| league = [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|2000|7|6}}\n| birth_place = [[Salisbury, North Carolina]]\n| nationality = American\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 6\n| weight_lbs = 285\n| high_school = [[Spartanburg Day School|Spartanburg Day]]<br>([[Spartanburg, South Carolina]])\n| college = [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke]] (2018\u20132019)\n| draft_year = 2019\n| draft_round = 1\n| draft_pick = 1\n| draft_team = [[New Orleans Pelicans]]\n| career_start = 2019\n| years1 = {{nbay|2019|start}}\u2013present\n| team1 = [[New Orleans Pelicans]]\n| highlights =\n* Consensus [[List of U.S. men's college basketball national player of the year awards|National College Player of the Year]] (2019)\n* Consensus first-team [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] ([[2019 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|2019]])\n* [[USBWA National Freshman of the Year|Wayman Tisdale Award]] (2019)\n* [[Karl Malone Award]] (2019) \n* [[ACC Athlete of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Atlantic Coast Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year|ACC Player of the Year]] (2019) \n* [[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]] All-Freshman team (2019) \n* First-team All-[[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]] (2019)\n* [[Atlantic Coast Conference Men's Basketball Rookie of the Year|ACC Rookie of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[ACC Men's Basketball Tournament|ACC Tournament]] MVP ([[2019 ACC Men's Basketball Tournament|2019]])\n* [[McDonald's All-American]] ([[2018 McDonald's All-American Boys Game|2018]])\n* [[Jordan Brand Classic]] (2018)\n* [[Nike Hoop Summit]] (2018)\n* [[South Carolina Mr. Basketball]] (2018)\n| nba_profile = zion_williamson\n| bbr = willizi01\n}}\n'''Zion Lateef Williamson''' (born July 6, 2000) is an American professional [[basketball]] player for the [[New Orleans Pelicans]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). He plays the [[power forward (basketball)|power forward]] position.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/w/willizi01.html|title=Zion Williamson|publisher=[[Basketball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Following a dominant freshman-year stint with the [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke Blue Devils]], he was selected by the Pelicans first overall in the [[2019 NBA draft]].\n\nBorn in [[Salisbury, North Carolina]], Williamson attended [[Spartanburg Day School]], where he was a consensus five-star [[college recruiting|recruit]] and was ranked among the top five players in the 2018 class. He led his team to three straight state championships and earned [[South Carolina Mr. Basketball]] recognition in his senior season. Williamson also left high school as a [[McDonald's All-American Game|McDonald's All-American]], runner-up for [[Mr. Basketball USA]], and [[USA Today All-USA high school basketball team|''USA Today'' All-USA first team]] honoree. In high school, he drew national attention for his [[slam dunk]]s.\n\nIn his freshman and only season with Duke, Williamson was named [[Atlantic Coast Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year|ACC Player of the Year]], [[ACC Athlete of the Year]] and [[Atlantic Coast Conference Men's Basketball Rookie of the Year|ACC Rookie of the Year]]. He set the single-game school scoring record for freshmen in January 2019, claimed ACC Rookie of the Week accolades five times, earned [[Associated Press College Basketball Player of the Year|AP Player of the Year]], [[Sporting News Men's College Basketball Player of the Year|''Sporting News'' College Player of the Year]] recognition, and won the [[USBWA National Freshman of the Year|Wayman Tisdale Award]].\n\n==Early life==\nWilliamson was born in [[Salisbury, North Carolina]]. Besides basketball, Williamson played [[Association football|soccer]] and the [[quarterback]] position in [[American football|football]].<ref name=finest/> When he was five years old, he set sights on becoming a [[college basketball]] star. At age nine, Williamson began waking up every morning at 5&nbsp;a.m. to go train.<ref name=usatodayhss/> He competed in youth leagues with his mother Sharonda Sampson coaching and played for the Sumter Falcons on the [[Amateur Athletic Union]] (AAU) circuit, facing opponents four years older than him.<ref name=legend/> Williamson later began working with his stepfather, former college basketball player Lee Anderson, to improve his skills as a [[point guard]].<ref name=usatodayhss/> He joined the basketball team at Johnakin Middle School in [[Marion, South Carolina]], where he was again coached by his mother and averaged 20 points per game. In middle school, Williamson was a point guard and lost only three games in two years.<ref name=usatodayhss/> In 2013, he guided Johnakin to an 8\u20131 record and a conference title.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mcfadden |first1=Naeem |title=Middle school basketball teams capture conference championships |url=https://www.scnow.com/starandenterprise/sports/article_53d5d30e-7b7c-11e2-9c78-001a4bcf6878.html |website=[[The Morning News (American newspaper)|The Morning News]] |access-date=January 16, 2019 |date=February 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==High school career==\n===Freshman and sophomore seasons===\nWilliamson attended [[Spartanburg Day School]], a small [[K\u201312]] private school in [[Spartanburg, South Carolina]], where he played basketball for the Griffins.<ref name=finest/> Between eighth and ninth grade, he grew from {{height|ft=5|in=9}} to {{height|ft=6|in=3}}.<ref name=legend/> In the summer leading up to his first season, Williamson practiced in the school gym and developed the ability to dunk.<ref name=\"washpost\">{{cite web|last1=Babb|first1=Kent|title=Zion Williamson, 16, might be the best dunker on the Internet. And what else?|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/highschools/zion-williamson-16-might-be-the-best-dunker-on-the-internet-and-what-else/2017/04/07/84139f04-1b02-11e7-855e-4824bbb5d748_story.html|website=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=April 9, 2017|date=April 8, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408225619/https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/highschools/zion-williamson-16-might-be-the-best-dunker-on-the-internet-and-what-else/2017/04/07/84139f04-1b02-11e7-855e-4824bbb5d748_story.html|archive-date=April 8, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> At the time, he competed for the South Carolina Hornets AAU team as well, where he was teammates with [[Ja Morant]].<ref name=\"morant\">{{cite web |last1=Norlander |first1=Matt |title=The real story of Ja Morant and Zion Williamson playing on the same AAU team |url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/court-report-the-real-story-of-ja-morant-zion-williamson-playing-on-the-same-aau-team/ |publisher=[[CBS Sports]] |access-date=January 23, 2019 |date=January 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190124041742/https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/court-report-the-real-story-of-ja-morant-zion-williamson-playing-on-the-same-aau-team/ |archive-date=January 24, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> As a freshman, Williamson averaged 24.4 points, 9.4 rebounds, 2.8 assists, 3.3 steals and 3.0 blocks, earning All-State and All-Region honors.<ref name=\"freshman\">{{cite web|title=2015 Boys Basketball All-Area Team|url=http://www.goupstate.com/news/20150405/2015-boys-basketball-all-area-team|website=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]]|access-date=April 9, 2017|date=April 5, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170410051957/http://www.goupstate.com/news/20150405/2015-boys-basketball-all-area-team|archive-date=April 10, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He also led Spartanburg Day to a [[South Carolina Independent School Association]] (SCISA) state championship game appearance.<ref name=\"genz\">{{cite web |last1=Figman |first1=Adam |title=Generation Z |url=https://www.slamonline.com/college-hs/high-school/zion-williamson-spartanburg-slam-cover/ |website=[[Slam (magazine)|Slam]] |access-date=August 24, 2018 |date=June 6, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825002609/https://www.slamonline.com/college-hs/high-school/zion-williamson-spartanburg-slam-cover/ |archive-date=August 25, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2015, Williamson took part in the SCISA North-South All-Star Game in [[Sumter, South Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Eight area players ready for SCISA North-South All-Star games |url=https://www.scnow.com/sports/article_f60d1ea6-c482-11e4-bcf7-d302529639b2.html |website=[[The Morning News (American newspaper)|The Morning News]] |access-date=January 16, 2019 |date=March 6, 2015}}</ref> By his second year in high school, he stood {{height|ft=6|in=6}}.<ref name=genz/> In his sophomore season, Williamson averaged 28.3 points, 10.4 rebounds, 3.9 blocks, and 2.7 steals per game and was named SCISA Region I-2A Player of the Year.<ref name=\"melton\">{{cite web |last1=Melton |first1=Kevin |title=Zion Williamson picks up offer from South Carolina |url=https://www.goupstate.com/news/20160503/zion-williamson-picks-up-offer-from-south-carolina |website=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]] |access-date=January 16, 2019 |date=May 3, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117071441/https://www.goupstate.com/news/20160503/zion-williamson-picks-up-offer-from-south-carolina |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He led the Griffins to their first SCISA Region I-2A title in program history.<ref name=finest/> In June 2016, Williamson participated in the [[National Basketball Players Association]] (NBPA) Top 100 camp and was its leading scorer.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Meyer |first1=Jerry |title=Zion Williamson leading NBA Top 100 Camp in scoring |url=https://247sports.com/college/alabama/Bolt/Zion-Williamson-leading-NBA-Top-100-Camp-in-scoring-45854651/ |publisher=[[247Sports.com|247Sports]] |access-date=August 24, 2018 |date=June 17, 2016}}</ref> In August, he won the [[Under Armour]] Elite 24 showcase dunk contest in [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Resetar |first1=Max |title=Zion Williamson Wins the 2016 Elite 24 Dunk Contest |url=https://www.slamonline.com/slam-tv/zion-williamson-wins-2016-elite-24-dunk-contest/ |website=[[Slam (magazine)|Slam]] |access-date=January 16, 2019 |date=August 20, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117013422/https://www.slamonline.com/slam-tv/zion-williamson-wins-2016-elite-24-dunk-contest/ |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Junior season===\nAs a junior, Williamson averaged 36.8 points, 13 rebounds, 3 steals, and 2.5 blocks per game.<ref name=\"repeats\">{{cite web |last1=Melton |first1=Kevin |title=Slam Dunk: Zion Williamson repeats as Player of the Year |url=https://www.goupstate.com/sports/20170422/slam-dunk-zion-williamson-repeats-as-player-of-year |website=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]] |access-date=January 19, 2019 |date=April 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120095116/https://www.goupstate.com/sports/20170422/slam-dunk-zion-williamson-repeats-as-player-of-year |archive-date=January 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Entering the season, he was among 50 players selected to the [[Naismith Prep Player of the Year Award]] watch list.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bezjak |first1=Lou |title=Jalek Felton, Christian Brown on Naismith Boys High School Player of the Year watch list |url=https://www.thestate.com/sports/high-school/prep-basketball/article114898558.html |website=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]] |access-date=January 17, 2019 |date=November 15, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121033/https://www.thestate.com/sports/high-school/prep-basketball/article114898558.html |archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Starting in the 2016\u201317 season, Williamson was propelled into the national spotlight for his [[viral video|viral]] highlight videos.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jordan |first1=Jason |title=Zion Williamson's newfound fame has grown his social media following substantially |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2017/zion-williamsons-newfound-fame-has-grown-his-social-media-following-substantially |newspaper=[[USA Today|USA Today High School Sports]] |access-date=January 17, 2019 |date=January 24, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121119/https://usatodayhss.com/2017/zion-williamsons-newfound-fame-has-grown-his-social-media-following-substantially |archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He made his season debut on November 15, 2016, recording 42 points and 16 rebounds in a win over [[Cardinal Newman High School (Columbia, South Carolina)|Cardinal Newman High School]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Watson |first1=Randy |title=Zion Williamson Drops 42 & 13 in Season Debut |url=http://ballislife.com/zion-williamson-42-13-debut/ |publisher=[[Ballislife.com|Ballislife]] |access-date=January 17, 2019 |date=November 15, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121802/http://ballislife.com/zion-williamson-42-13-debut/ |archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In the same month, his highlights drew the praise of NBA player [[Stephen Curry]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Burns |first1=Ashley |title=Steph Curry Is Impressed By High School Hoops Prospect Zion Williamson And You Should Be, Too |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/steph-curry-impressed-high-school-171726818.html |work=[[Yahoo Sports]] |access-date=January 17, 2019 |date=November 18, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121554/https://sports.yahoo.com/news/steph-curry-impressed-high-school-171726818.html |archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On November 24, Williamson erupted for 50 points, including 10 dunks, along with 16 rebounds and 5 blocks versus [[Proviso East High School]] at the Tournament of Champions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Five-Star Junior Prospect Zion Williamson Drops 50 Points |url=https://www.slamonline.com/slam-tv/five-star-junior-prospect-zion-williamson-drops-50-points/ |website=[[Slam (magazine)|Slam]] |access-date=January 17, 2019 |date=November 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121344/https://www.slamonline.com/slam-tv/five-star-junior-prospect-zion-williamson-drops-50-points/ |archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Regan |first1=Brett |title=Zion Williamson's Monster 50-Point Performance Steals ToC Show |url=https://www.flohoops.com/articles/5058094-zion-williamsons-monster-50-point-performance-steals-toc-show |publisher=FloHoops |access-date=January 17, 2019 |date=November 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121056/https://www.flohoops.com/articles/5058094-zion-williamsons-monster-50-point-performance-steals-toc-show |archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In a 73\u201353 victory over Gray Collegiate Academy at the [[Chick-fil-A]] Classic on December 21, he posted a tournament-record 53 points and 16 rebounds, shooting 25-of-28 from the field.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Melton |first1=Kevin |title=Spartanburg Day's Zion Williamson has record night in tourney opener |url=https://www.goupstate.com/sports/20161221/spartanburg-days-zion-williamson-has-record-night-in-tourney-opener |website=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]] |access-date=January 17, 2019 |date=December 21, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119174222/https://www.goupstate.com/sports/20161221/spartanburg-days-zion-williamson-has-record-night-in-tourney-opener |archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On December 30, Williamson recorded 31 points and 14 rebounds to win [[most valuable player]] (MVP) at the Farm Bureau Insurance Classic.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Melton |first1=Kevin |title=Newton tops Spartanburg Day; Zion Williamson named MVP |url=https://www.goupstate.com/sports/20161230/newton-tops-spartanburg-day-zion-williamson-named-mvp |website=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]] |access-date=January 17, 2019 |date=December 30, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119174219/https://www.goupstate.com/sports/20161230/newton-tops-spartanburg-day-zion-williamson-named-mvp |archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On January 15, 2017, he received nationwide publicity after rapper [[Drake (musician)|Drake]] wore his jersey in an [[Instagram]] post.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jordan |first1=Jason |title=Zion Williamson's No. 1 fan Drake sports his high school jersey |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2017/zion-williamsons-no-1-fan-drake-sports-his-high-school-jersey |newspaper=[[USA Today|USA Today High School Sports]] |access-date=January 17, 2019 |date=January 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119174411/https://usatodayhss.com/2017/zion-williamsons-no-1-fan-drake-sports-his-high-school-jersey |archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWilliamson surpassed the 2,000-point barrier on January 20, when he tallied 48 points against [[Oakbrook Preparatory School]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wellman |first1=Webb |title=Zion Williamson 48 Points & Dunks On Everyone But The Coach |url=http://ballislife.com/zion-williamson-2000/ |publisher=[[Ballislife.com|Ballislife]] |access-date=January 17, 2019 |date=January 20, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121807/http://ballislife.com/zion-williamson-2000/ |archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On February 14, he led Spartanburg Day past Oakbrook Prep for their first SCISA Region I-2A title, chipping in a game-high 37 points in a 105\u201349 rout. Williamson broke the state record for most 30-point games in a season, with 27 by the end of the regular season.<ref name=\"staterecord\">{{cite web |last1=FitzPatrick |first1=Joel |title=Zion Williamson sets state record in rout |url=https://www.goupstate.com/sports/20170214/zion-williamson-sets-state-record-in-rout |website=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]] |access-date=January 17, 2018 |date=February 14, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602200148/http://www.goupstate.com/sports/20170214/zion-williamson-sets-state-record-in-rout |archive-date=June 2, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> He repeated as SCISA Region I-2A Player of the Year.<ref name=repeats/> High school sports website [[MaxPreps]] named him National Junior of the Year and to the High School All-American first team, while ''[[USA Today]]'' High School Sports gave him [[USA Today All-USA high school basketball team|All-USA first team]] recognition.<ref>{{cite web |title=2016\u201317 MaxPreps Boys Basketball Junior All-American Team |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/news/otwRLm_KeEGHwC460kRRPg/2016-17-maxpreps-boys-basketball-junior-all-american-team.htm |publisher=[[MaxPreps]] |access-date=January 19, 2019 |date=April 11, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120093549/http://www.maxpreps.com/news/otwRLm_KeEGHwC460kRRPg/2016-17-maxpreps-boys-basketball-junior-all-american-team.htm |archive-date=January 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2016\u201317 MaxPreps High School Boys Basketball All-American Team |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/news/90GdoEN1_UCBDFsChBO2nw/2016-17-maxpreps-high-school-boys-basketball-all-american-team.htm |publisher=[[MaxPreps]] |access-date=January 19, 2019 |date=April 6, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107154501/http://www.maxpreps.com/news/90GdoEN1_UCBDFsChBO2nw/2016-17-maxpreps-high-school-boys-basketball-all-american-team.htm |archive-date=January 7, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Halley |first1=Jim |title=ALL-USA Boys Basketball First Team: Zion Williamson, Spartanburg Day (S.C.) |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2017/all-usa-boys-basketball-first-team-zion-williamson-spartanburg-day-s-c |newspaper=[[USA Today|USA Today High School Sports]] |accessdate=January 19, 2019 |date=March 28, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120093523/https://usatodayhss.com/2017/all-usa-boys-basketball-first-team-zion-williamson-spartanburg-day-s-c |archive-date=January 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On April 22, 2017, Williamson recorded 26 points and 7 rebounds for his AAU team SC Supreme in a loss to highly touted recruit [[Romeo Langford]] and Twenty Two Vision at an [[Adidas]] Gauntlet tournament.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bossi |first1=Eric |title=No. 2 and No. 3 Zion Williamson and Romeo Langford duel at adidas Gauntlet |url=https://basketballrecruiting.rivals.com/news/no-2-and-no-3-zion-williamson-and-romeo-langford-duel-at-adidas-gauntlet |publisher=[[Rivals.com|Rivals]] |accessdate=January 19, 2019 |date=April 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120093516/https://basketballrecruiting.rivals.com/news/no-2-and-no-3-zion-williamson-and-romeo-langford-duel-at-adidas-gauntlet |archive-date=January 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In June, he appeared on the cover of basketball magazine ''[[Slam (magazine)|Slam]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Figman |first1=Adam |title=Zion Williamson Covers SLAM 210 |url=https://www.slamonline.com/college-hs/high-school/zion-williamson-covers-slam-210/ |website=[[Slam (magazine)|Slam]] |accessdate=January 19, 2019 |date=June 6, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120093436/https://www.slamonline.com/college-hs/high-school/zion-williamson-covers-slam-210/ |archive-date=January 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson, in a highly publicized AAU game on July 27, scored 28 points and led SC Supreme to a 104\u201392 win over 2019 class recruit [[LaMelo Ball]] and Big Ballers at the Adidas Uprising Summer Championships.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Medcalf |first1=Myron |title=AAU game featuring LaMelo Ball, Zion Williamson goes on despite large crowd |url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/20167079/with-massive-crowd-hand-lamelo-ball-zion-williamson-showdown-goes-on |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=January 19, 2019 |date=July 27, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120093459/http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/20167079/with-massive-crowd-hand-lamelo-ball-zion-williamson-showdown-goes-on |archive-date=January 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In August, he was named MVP of the 2017 Adidas Nations camp after averaging 22.5 points and 7.2 rebounds through 6 games.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tomes |first1=Evan |title=adidas Nations: Top High School / Internationals |url=https://www.nbadraft.net/adidas-nations-top-high-school-internationals |publisher=NBADraft.net |accessdate=January 19, 2019 |date=August 23, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120093437/https://www.nbadraft.net/adidas-nations-top-high-school-internationals |archive-date=January 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Senior season===\nIn his senior season, Williamson averaged 36.4 points, 11.4 rebounds and 3.5 assists per game.<ref name=\"allusa\">{{cite news |last1=Halley |first1=Jim |title=ALL-USA Boys Basketball First Team: Zion Williamson, Spartanburg Day |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2018/all-usa-boys-basketball-first-team-zion-williamson-spartanburg-day |newspaper=[[USA Today|USA Today High School Sports]] |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |date=April 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121064221/https://usatodayhss.com/2018/all-usa-boys-basketball-first-team-zion-williamson-spartanburg-day |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He debuted on November 15, 2017, erupting for 46 points and 15 rebounds in a 70\u201362 loss to [[Christ School (North Carolina)|Christ School]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ostrander |first1=Lynden |title=Zion Williamson scores 46 points in season opener |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/news/ql_UTPSyo0qOG_28w5l0hQ/zion-williamson-scores-46-points-in-season-opener.htm |publisher=[[MaxPreps]] |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |date=November 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121064250/http://www.maxpreps.com/news/ql_UTPSyo0qOG_28w5l0hQ/zion-williamson-scores-46-points-in-season-opener.htm |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In his home opener on November 21, he recorded 29 points and 11 rebounds, leading the Griffins to a 70\u201355 win over [[Hammond School (South Carolina)|Hammond School]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ramspacher |first1=Andrew |title=Zion Williamson keeps dunking and college programs keep waiting |url=https://www.thestate.com/sports/high-school/prep-basketball/article185965988.html |website=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]] |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |date=November 21, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121010916/https://www.thestate.com/sports/high-school/prep-basketball/article185965988.html |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In the game, Williamson bruised his left foot, which sidelined him for over a month.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Millians |first1=Rick |title=What's wrong with Zion Williamson and when will he return? |url=https://www.thestate.com/sports/high-school/prep-basketball/article189503624.html |website=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]] |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |date=December 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121064052/https://www.thestate.com/sports/high-school/prep-basketball/article189503624.html |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> While recovering, he commented, \"It's really been a time to grow mentally.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bezjak |first1=Lou |title=Zion Williamson's return to the court coming soon |url=https://www.thestate.com/sports/high-school/prep-basketball/article193382214.html |website=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]] |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |date=January 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121064055/https://www.thestate.com/sports/high-school/prep-basketball/article193382214.html |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson made his return from the injury on January 11, 2018, scoring 31 points in a 71\u201362 victory over [[Asheville Christian Academy]].<ref>{{cite web |title=High school basketball phenom Zion Williamson dominates in return to the court after injury |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/news/TEbDek4SU0uSEp22hFDsnQ/high-school-basketball-phenom-zion-williamson-dominates-in-return-to-the-court-after-injury.htm |publisher=[[MaxPreps]] |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |date=January 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121064231/http://www.maxpreps.com/news/TEbDek4SU0uSEp22hFDsnQ/high-school-basketball-phenom-zion-williamson-dominates-in-return-to-the-court-after-injury.htm |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On January 13, in a nationally televised game at the Hoophall Classic, he scored 36 points as his team lost to [[Chino Hills High School]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Johnson |first1=Chris |title=Viral Sensation Zion Williamson Picks Duke as Blue Devils Solidify Loaded 2018 Class |url=https://www.si.com/college-basketball/2018/01/20/zion-williamson-commits-duke-2018-recruiting |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |date=January 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121010849/https://www.si.com/college-basketball/2018/01/20/zion-williamson-commits-duke-2018-recruiting |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson tallied 30 points and 13 rebounds in his final home game on February 8, a 58\u201354 win over [[Greensboro Day School]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blackwell |first1=Jed |title=With a monster dunk, Zion Williamson closes out his final home game |url=https://www.goupstate.com/news/20180208/with-monster-dunk-zion-williamson-closes-out-his-final-home-game |website=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]] |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |date=February 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121065548/https://www.goupstate.com/news/20180208/with-monster-dunk-zion-williamson-closes-out-his-final-home-game |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On February 17, he posted 37 points, 10 rebounds, and 5 steals, while scoring his 3,000th career point, versus Spartanburg Christian Academy at the SCISA Region I-2A tournament.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Landreth |first1=Rob |title=Zion Williamson gets 3,000th career point to open SCISA tourney |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2018/video-zion-williamson-gets-3000th-career-point-to-open-scisa-tourney |newspaper=[[USA Today|USA Today High School Sports]] |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |date=February 17, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121064348/https://usatodayhss.com/2018/video-zion-williamson-gets-3000th-career-point-to-open-scisa-tourney |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> One week later, Williamson guided Spartanburg Day to its third consecutive SCISA Region I-2A championship after recording 38 points against [[Trinity Collegiate School]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Boardwine |first1=Andrew |title=Spartanburg Day, Zion Williamson, down Trinity-Byrnes in SCISA 2A title |url=https://www.scnow.com/sports/article_b6e410dc-1997-11e8-8774-db7fb564c145.html |website=[[The Morning News (American newspaper)|The Morning News]] |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |date=February 24, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180224230842/http://www.scnow.com/sports/article_b6e410dc-1997-11e8-8774-db7fb564c145.html |archive-date=February 24, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, Williamson played in the [[2018 McDonald's All-American Boys Game|2018 McDonald's All-American Game]], where he scored 8 points in 17 minutes before leaving with a thumb injury.<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Basketball Box Score \u2013 Game Totals \u2013 Final Statistics |url=https://www.mcdonaldsallamerican.com/content/dam/aag/AABOYS.pdf |publisher=[[McDonald's All-American Game]] |accessdate=January 21, 2019 |date=March 28, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003221127/https://www.mcdonaldsallamerican.com/content/dam/aag/AABOYS.pdf |archive-date=October 3, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Boone |first1=Kyle |title=Zion Williamson injury: Five-star Duke commit injures hand in McDonald's All-American Game |url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/zion-williamson-injury-five-star-duke-commit-injures-hand-in-mcdonalds-all-american-game/ |publisher=[[CBS Sports]] |accessdate=January 21, 2019 |date=March 29, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122094803/https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/zion-williamson-injury-five-star-duke-commit-injures-hand-in-mcdonalds-all-american-game/ |archive-date=January 22, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The injury also forced him to miss the [[Jordan Brand Classic]] and [[Nike Hoop Summit]] in the following month.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Zagoria |first1=Adam |title=Zion Williamson Sidelined For Jordan Brand Classic & Nike Hoop Summit |url=https://www.flohoops.com/articles/6170725-zion-williamson-sidelined-for-jordan-brand-classic-nike-hoop-summit |publisher=FloHoops |accessdate=January 22, 2019 |date=April 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190123071746/https://www.flohoops.com/articles/6170725-zion-williamson-sidelined-for-jordan-brand-classic-nike-hoop-summit |archive-date=January 23, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> For his 2017\u201318 high school season, Williamson was named to the ''USA Today'' All-USA first team and MaxPreps All-American second team.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Divens |first1=Jordan |title=2017\u201318 MaxPreps High School Boys Basketball All-American Team |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/news/vpYHC6-v2kiq_nCltCL9_Q/2017-18-maxpreps-high-school-boys-basketball-all-american-team-.htm |publisher=[[MaxPreps]] |accessdate=January 22, 2019 |date=April 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190123071708/http://www.maxpreps.com/news/vpYHC6-v2kiq_nCltCL9_Q/2017-18-maxpreps-high-school-boys-basketball-all-american-team-.htm |archive-date=January 23, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Halley |first1=Jim |title=ALL-USA Boys Basketball First Team: Zion Williamson, Spartanburg Day |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2018/all-usa-boys-basketball-first-team-zion-williamson-spartanburg-day |newspaper=[[USA Today|USA Today High School Sports]] |accessdate=January 22, 2019 |date=April 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121064221/https://usatodayhss.com/2018/all-usa-boys-basketball-first-team-zion-williamson-spartanburg-day |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He additionally earned [[South Carolina Mr. Basketball]] recognition and was runner-up for [[Mr. Basketball USA]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Flores |first1=Ronnie |title=All-Time Mr. Basketball USA Honorees |url=http://www.grassrootshoops.net/2018/04/all-time-mr-basketball-usa-honorees/ |publisher=Grassroots Hoops |accessdate=January 22, 2019 |date=April 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190123071737/http://www.grassrootshoops.net/2018/04/all-time-mr-basketball-usa-honorees/ |archive-date=January 23, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wertz Jr. |first1=Langston |title=UNC, Duke recruits named Mr. Basketball in North, South Carolina |url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/high-school/article207586694.html |website=[[The Charlotte Observer]] |accessdate=January 22, 2019 |date=March 31, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181109234950/https://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/high-school/article207586694.html |archive-date=November 9, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Recruiting===\n[[Wofford Terriers men's basketball|Wofford]] offered Williamson his first college basketball scholarship when he was a freshman in high school.<ref name=\"wofford\">{{cite web|last1=Fowler|first1=Scott|title=Basketball star Zion Williamson: 'Wide open' on recruiting, including ... Wofford?|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/college/article133115939.html|website=[[The Charlotte Observer]]|accessdate=January 14, 2018|date=February 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180115184538/http://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/college/article133115939.html|archive-date=January 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In the summer of 2015, Williamson emerged with the South Carolina Hornets AAU team as one of the top players in his class.<ref>{{cite web |title=Name to Know: 6'5\u2033 2018 Zion Williamson of Spartanburg Country Day (SC) |url=http://www.phenomhoopreport.com/name-to-know-65-2018-zion-williamson-of-spartanburg-country-day-sc/ |publisher=Phenom Hoop Report |accessdate=January 21, 2019 |date=September 15, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122094731/http://www.phenomhoopreport.com/name-to-know-65-2018-zion-williamson-of-spartanburg-country-day-sc/ |archive-date=January 22, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> By the end of his sophomore season, he received offers from 16 [[NCAA Division I]] programs, including [[Clemson Tigers men's basketball|Clemson]], [[Florida Gators men's basketball|Florida]], and [[South Carolina Gamecocks men's basketball|South Carolina]], but was not planning on making a decision until his senior year.<ref name=melton/> In the summer of 2016, Williamson was drawing the most attention from Clemson, Florida, [[North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball|North Carolina]], and South Carolina.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Meyer |first1=Jerry |title=Top247 No. 1 Zion Williamson lists four recruiting him hardest |url=https://247sports.com/Bolt/Clemson-Florida-North-Carolina-and-South-Carolina-recruiting-Zion-Williamson-the-hardest-46904188/ |publisher=[[247Sports.com|247Sports]] |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |date=August 22, 2016}}</ref> On August 30, 2016, he received a scholarship offer from [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rowe |first1=Adam |title=Duke offers 247Sports' #1 player in 2018, SF Zion Williamson |url=https://247sports.com/college/duke/Bolt/duke-basketball-recruiting-zion-williamson-offer-47069123/ |publisher=[[247Sports.com|247Sports]] |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |date=August 30, 2016}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> Williamson was also offered a [[American football|football]] scholarship by Eric Mateos, [[tight end]]s coach for [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]], but did not show interest.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Borzello |first1=Jeff |title=Ex-LSU asst.: Zion Williamson 'probably the best damn tight end to ever live' |url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/25280950/duke-sensation-zion-williamson-had-football-scholarship-offer-lsu |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=November 15, 2018 |date=November 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115201742/http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/25280950/duke-sensation-zion-williamson-had-football-scholarship-offer-lsu |archive-date=November 15, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Entering his junior season, he was a consensus five-star recruit and was ranked the number one player in the 2018 class by recruiting service [[247Sports.com|247Sports]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Zion Williamson takes over top spot in 247Sports' 2018 basketball player rankings |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2016/zion-williamson-takes-over-top-spot-in-247sports-2018-basketball-player-rankings |newspaper=[[USA Today|USA Today High School Sports]] |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |date=August 5, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125020306/https://usatodayhss.com/2016/zion-williamson-takes-over-top-spot-in-247sports-2018-basketball-player-rankings |archive-date=January 25, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2016, [[ESPN]] recruiting director Paul Biancardi touted Williamson as \"probably the best player in terms of production\" in his class.<ref name=usatodayhss/> By 2018, most recruiting experts predicted that he would play for Clemson.<ref>{{cite web |last1=O'Donnell |first1=Ricky |title=Clemson has become the surprise favorite for 5-star basketball recruit Zion Williamson |url=https://www.sbnation.com/college-basketball/2018/1/5/16856056/zion-williamson-recruiting-predictions-clemson-tigers-basketball-kentucky-duke-kansas |publisher=[[SB Nation]] |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |date=January 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190124203434/https://www.sbnation.com/college-basketball/2018/1/5/16856056/zion-williamson-recruiting-predictions-clemson-tigers-basketball-kentucky-duke-kansas |archive-date=January 24, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn a live ESPN telecast on January 20, 2018, Williamson committed to Duke.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Borzello |first1=Jeff |title=Zion Williamson pledge gives Duke top three players in ESPN 100 |url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/22163323/espn-100-recruit-zion-williamson-commits-duke-blue-devils |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |date=January 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122132616/http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/22163323/espn-100-recruit-zion-williamson-commits-duke-blue-devils |archive-date=January 22, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"brotherhood\">{{cite web |last1=Pope IV |first1=Jonas |title=Zion Williamson: 'I will be joining the brotherhood of Duke University' |url=https://www.newsobserver.com/sports/college/acc/unc/article195807054.html |website=[[The News & Observer]] |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |date=January 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125020914/https://www.newsobserver.com/sports/college/acc/unc/article195807054.html |archive-date=January 25, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He explained the decision, \"Duke stood out because the brotherhood represents a family. ([[Mike Krzyzewski]]) is just the most legendary coach that ever coached college basketball. I feel like going to [[Duke University]], I can learn a lot from him.\"<ref name=brotherhood/> Duke, who had landed [[RJ Barrett]] and [[Cam Reddish]] in addition to Williamson, became the first team to land the top three recruits in a class since modern recruiting rankings began.<ref name=\"top3\">{{cite web |last1=Roberts |first1=Ben |title=Duke has the top three basketball recruits in the country. Has that ever happened? |url=https://www.kentucky.com/sports/college/kentucky-sports/uk-basketball-men/article195908284.html |website=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]] |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |date=January 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824065807/https://www.kentucky.com/sports/college/kentucky-sports/uk-basketball-men/article195908284.html |archive-date=August 24, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> His stepfather Lee Anderson remarked that Clemson lost a \"mile-and-a-half lead\" in recruiting Williamson.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Connolly |first1=Matt |title=How could Clemson lose 'a mile-and-a-half lead' for Zion Williamson? |url=https://www.thestate.com/sports/college/acc/clemson-university/article196041029.html |website=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]] |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |date=January 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125073345/https://www.thestate.com/sports/college/acc/clemson-university/article196041029.html |archive-date=January 25, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Despite having three of the country's top recruits on their roster, Duke was unable to win the 2019 NCAA Tournament when they lost to Michigan State by one point in the East Regional Final.\n\n{{College athlete recruit start|collapse=no|year=2018}}\n{{College athlete recruit entry\n| recruit = Zion Williamson\n| position = [[Power forward (basketball)|PF]]\n| hometown = [[Spartanburg, South Carolina|Spartanburg, SC]]\n| highschool = [[Spartanburg Day School]] (SC)\n| feet = 6\n| inches = 6\n| weight = 272\n| 40 =\n| commitdate = January 20, 2018\n| scout stars = \n| rivals stars = 5\n| 247 stars = 5\n| espn stars = 5\n| espn grade = 96\n}}\n{{College athlete recruit end\n| 40 =\n| year = 2018\n| rivals ref title = Duke 2018 Basketball Commitments\n| scout ref title = \n| espn ref title = 2018 Duke Blue Devils Recruiting Class\n| 247 school =\n| rivals school = duke\n| scout s = \n| espn schoolid = 150\n| scout overall = \n| rivals overall = 5\n| 247 overall = 7\n| espn overall = 2\n| accessdate = January 14, 2018\n| bball = yes\n}}\n\n==College career==\n[[File:Zion Williamson Duke (cropped).jpg|thumb|235px|Williamson with Duke in December 2018]]\nWilliamson played in a preseason game for Duke on August 15, 2018, in an 86\u201367 win over Canadian university [[Ryerson Rams|Ryerson]], recording a [[double (basketball)|double-double]] of 29 points and 13 rebounds and shooting 3-of-4 from three-point range.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Boone |first1=Kyle |title=Duke's Zion Williamson, R.J. Barrett lead Blue Devils to exhibition rout of Ryerson |url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/dukes-zion-williamson-r-j-barrett-lead-blue-devils-to-exhibition-rout-of-ryerson/ |publisher=[[CBS Sports]] |accessdate=August 19, 2018 |date=August 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820005843/https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/dukes-zion-williamson-r-j-barrett-lead-blue-devils-to-exhibition-rout-of-ryerson/ |archive-date=August 20, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> He was named to the preseason watch lists for the [[Karl Malone Award]], [[Naismith College Player of the Year|Naismith Trophy]], and [[John R. Wooden Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.woodenaward.com/john_r_wooden_award_presented_by_wendy_s_announces_2018_19_preseason_top_50_watch_list|title=John R. Wooden Award Presented By Wendy's Announces 2018\u201319 Preseason Top 50 Watch List|website=[[John R. Wooden Award]]|date=November 6, 2018|accessdate=November 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108025819/http://www.woodenaward.com/john_r_wooden_award_presented_by_wendy_s_announces_2018_19_preseason_top_50_watch_list|archive-date=November 8, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://naismithtrophy.com/citizen-naismith-trophy-mens-watch-list-released/|title=Citizen Naismith Trophy Men's Watch List Released|website=[[Naismith College Player of the Year]]|publisher=Atlanta Tipoff Club|date=November 5, 2018|accessdate=November 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106053317/http://naismithtrophy.com/citizen-naismith-trophy-mens-watch-list-released/|archive-date=November 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncaa.com/news/basketball-men/article/2018-10-18/college-basketball-awards-20-power-forwards-named-karl|title=College basketball awards: 20 power forwards named to Karl Malone Award preseason watch list|website=ncaa.com|publisher=NCAA|date=October 18, 2018|accessdate=October 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181022232829/https://www.ncaa.com/news/basketball-men/article/2018-10-18/college-basketball-awards-20-power-forwards-named-karl|archive-date=October 22, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On November 6, in his first regular season game with Duke, Williamson scored 28 points on 11-of-13 shooting in 23 minutes in a 118\u201384 win over [[Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball|Kentucky]] at the [[Champions Classic]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Doyel |first1=Gregg |title=Meet Duke phenom Zion Williamson, the most unique college basketball player I've ever seen |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/2018/11/07/zion-williamson-duke-blue-devils/1917786002/ |website=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=November 8, 2018 |date=November 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107152619/https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/2018/11/07/zion-williamson-duke-blue-devils/1917786002/ |archive-date=November 7, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> In the game, he and teammate RJ Barrett each broke the Duke freshman debut scoring record set by [[Marvin Bagley III]].<ref>{{cite web |title=No. 4 Duke Topples No. 2 Kentucky 118\u201384 |url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211779280 |publisher=Duke Athletics |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |date=November 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117070213/http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211779280 |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In his following game, a 94\u201372 victory over [[Army Black Knights men's basketball|Army]], Williamson tallied 27 points, 16 rebounds, and 6 blocks.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rollins |first1=Khadrice |title=Zion Williamson's Almost-Perfect First Half Propels Duke to 22-Point Win Over Army |url=https://www.si.com/college-basketball/2018/11/11/duke-army-highlights-zion-williamson-rj-barrett-cam-reddish-video |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |date=November 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117070042/https://www.si.com/college-basketball/2018/11/11/duke-army-highlights-zion-williamson-rj-barrett-cam-reddish-video |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He became the second player in school history to record at least 25 points, 15 rebounds, and 5 blocks in a game.<ref name=\"pow1\">{{cite web |title=ACC Announces Weekly Basketball Honors |url=http://theacc.com/news/2018/11/12/mens-basketball-acc-announces-weekly-basketball-honors.aspx |publisher=[[Atlantic Coast Conference]] |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |date=November 12, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190211094634/http://theacc.com/news/2018/11/12/mens-basketball-acc-announces-weekly-basketball-honors.aspx |archive-date=February 11, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson was subsequently named both player and freshman of the week in the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] (ACC).<ref name=pow1/>\n\nOn January 5, 2019, he had another strong performance versus Clemson, with 25 points, 10 rebounds, and a 360-degree dunk in 22 minutes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Williamson Leads No. 1 Duke Past Clemson 87\u201368 |url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211785688 |publisher=Duke Athletics |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |date=January 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117070338/http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211785688 |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Two days later, Williamson earned ACC Freshman of the Week honors for a second time.<ref>{{cite web |title=Virginia's Guy, Duke's Williamson recognized |url=http://theacc.com/news/2019/1/7/mens-basketball-acc-announces-basketball-players-of-the-week.aspx |publisher=[[Atlantic Coast Conference]] |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |date=January 7, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190110072015/http://theacc.com/news/2019/1/7/mens-basketball-acc-announces-basketball-players-of-the-week.aspx |archive-date=January 10, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On January 8, he posted 30 points, 10 rebounds, 5 assists, and 4 steals in an 87\u201365 win over [[Wake Forest Demon Deacons men's basketball|Wake Forest]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hale |first1=David M. |title=Duke's Zion Williamson posts all-around gem in rout of Wake Forest |url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/25717739/duke-blue-devils-zion-williamson-does-all-vs-wake-forest |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |date=January 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190112135843/http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/25717739/duke-blue-devils-zion-williamson-does-all-vs-wake-forest |archive-date=January 12, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On January 12, against [[Florida State Seminoles men's basketball|Florida State]], he was poked in the left eye by an opposing player towards the second half and missed the remainder of the game.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wiseman |first1=Steve |title=Duke star Zion Williamson poked in left eye, suffers double vision |url=https://www.newsobserver.com/sports/article224439050.html |website=[[The News & Observer]] |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |date=January 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117070351/https://www.newsobserver.com/sports/article224439050.html |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson returned in Duke's next game, a 95\u201391 [[Overtime (sports)|overtime]] loss to [[Syracuse Orange men's basketball|Syracuse]], and erupted for 35 points, 10 rebounds, and 4 blocks.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Goldberg |first1=Rob |title=Tyus Battle's 32 Lead Syracuse to Shocking Upset Win over Zion Williamson, Duke |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2815699-tyus-battles-32-lead-syracuse-to-shocking-upset-win-over-zion-williamson-duke |website=[[Bleacher Report]] |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |date=January 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115082719/https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2815699-tyus-battles-32-lead-syracuse-to-shocking-upset-win-over-zion-williamson-duke |archive-date=January 15, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He eclipsed the Duke freshman record for single-game points previously held by Marvin Bagley III and [[J.J. Redick]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Duke University Men's Basketball Postgame Notes January 14, 2019 \u2013 vs. Syracuse |url=http://www.goduke.com/pdf9/5481322.pdf |publisher=Duke Athletics |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |date=January 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117122253/http://www.goduke.com/pdf9/5481322.pdf |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On January 21, Williamson collected his third ACC Freshman of the Week accolades.<ref>{{cite web |title=Williamson Grabs Third ACC Freshman of the Week Honor |url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_LANG=C&ATCLID=211787280&DB_OEM_ID=4200 |publisher=Duke Athletics |access-date=January 24, 2019 |date=January 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190123202618/http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_LANG=C&ATCLID=211787280&DB_OEM_ID=4200 |archive-date=January 23, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> One week later, he scored 26 points and grabbed 9 rebounds in an 81\u201363 victory over [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish men's basketball|Notre Dame]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/college/ct-spt-duke-notre-dame-zion-williamson-20190128-story.html|title=Zion Williamson leaves an impression on Notre Dame|last=|first=|date=|work=Chicago Tribune|access-date=January 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129164456/https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/college/ct-spt-duke-notre-dame-zion-williamson-20190128-story.html|archive-date=January 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> By recording nine 25-point games in the season, Williamson set a new Duke freshman record.<ref>{{cite web |title=Duke University Men's Basketball Postgame Notes January 28, 2019 \u2013 vs. Notre Dame |url=http://www.goduke.com/pdf9/5481935.pdf?_ga=2.29292281.459220722.1548735165-881145153.1546751298 |publisher=Duke Athletics |access-date=March 9, 2019 |date=January 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190206134255/http://www.goduke.com/pdf9/5481935.pdf?_ga=2.29292281.459220722.1548735165-881145153.1546751298 |archive-date=February 6, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On February 2, he led all scorers with 29 points and 5 steals in a 91\u201361 win over [[St. John's Red Storm men's basketball|St. John's]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Williamson's 29 leads No. 2 Duke to 91-61 rout of St. John's |url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401082685 |website=[[ESPN]] |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=March 9, 2019 |date=February 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190304145945/http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401082685 |archive-date=March 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> After two days, Williamson was named ACC Freshman of the Week on his fourth occasion, while earning National Player of the Week distinction from the Naismith Trophy.<ref>{{cite web |title=Williamson Named National Player, ACC Freshman of the Week |url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211789182 |publisher=Duke Athletics |access-date=March 9, 2019 |date=February 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404171520/http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211789182 |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He had his third 30-point game of the season on February 16, scoring 32 points in a 94\u201378 victory over [[NC State Wolfpack men's basketball|NC State]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Barrett has triple-double, No. 2 Duke beats NC State, 94-78 |url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401082688 |website=[[ESPN]] |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=March 9, 2019 |date=February 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190314061122/http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401082688 |archive-date=March 14, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The performance helped him claim his second ACC Player of the Week and fifth ACC Freshman of the Week accolades.<ref>{{cite web |title=Duke's Williamson sweeps ACC weekly honors |url=http://theacc.com/news/2019/2/18/mens-basketball-dukes-williamson-sweeps-acc-weekly-honors.aspx |publisher=[[Atlantic Coast Conference]] |access-date=March 9, 2019 |date=February 18, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222051029/http://www.theacc.com/news/2019/2/18/mens-basketball-dukes-williamson-sweeps-acc-weekly-honors.aspx |archive-date=February 22, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> \n{{multiple image\n<!-- Essential parameters -->\n| align = left\n| direction = horizontal\n| width = 170\n| image1 = ZION WILLIAMSON (cropped) 2.jpg\n| width1 = \n| alt1 = \n| caption1 =\n| image3 = ZION WILLIAMSON 2 (cropped).jpg\n| width3 =\n| alt3 = \n| caption3 =\n| header = Williamson out with knee injury in February 2019\n| header_align = <!-- left/right/center -->\n| header_background = \n| footer = Williamson sits on the bench during a game versus [[Virginia Tech Hokies men's basketball|Virginia Tech]] with an injury suffered from a broken shoe. He walks on the court during a media timeout.\n| footer_align = <!-- left/right/center -->\n| footer_background = \n| background color = \n}}\nIn a February 20 game versus [[North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball|North Carolina]], Williamson suffered a Grade 1 knee [[sprain]] 36 seconds into the contest after his foot ripped through his [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] shoe, causing him to slip.<ref>{{cite news |date=February 21, 2019 |title=Zion Williamson felled by faulty Nike as North Carolina blast top-ranked Duke |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/feb/21/zion-shoe-duke-north-carolina-nike |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=February 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190221233601/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/feb/21/zion-shoe-duke-north-carolina-nike |archive-date=February 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"2021 Gleeson\">{{cite news |last=Gleeson |first=Scott |date=February 21, 2019 |title=Duke star Zion Williamson considered 'day-to-day' with a knee sprain |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/acc/2019/02/21/zion-williamson-duke-day-to-day-knee-sprain-injury/2936664002/ |work=USA Today |accessdate=February 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222055501/https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/acc/2019/02/21/zion-williamson-duke-day-to-day-knee-sprain-injury/2936664002/ |archive-date=February 22, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He did not return to the game, which Duke lost, 88\u201372.<ref>{{cite web |title=With Zion injured, No. 8 UNC routs No. 1 Duke 88-72 |url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401082689 |website=[[ESPN]] |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=March 9, 2019 |date=February 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190304044636/http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401082689 |archive-date=March 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Nike saw the value of its [[stock market|stock]] drop by $1.1 billion the following day as a result of the incident.<ref>{{cite news |last=Drury |first=Colin |date=February 22, 2019 |title=Nike stock market value plunges by $1.1bn after basketball star Zion Williamson's shoe breaks |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/nike-share-price-zion-williamson-shoe-duke-blue-devils-north-california-stock-a8791476.html |work=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=February 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222113408/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/nike-share-price-zion-williamson-shoe-duke-blue-devils-north-california-stock-a8791476.html |archive-date=February 22, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Alexander |first=Chip |date=February 21, 2019 |title=Zion Williamson's shoe blowout, knee injury leads to blowback for Nike |url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/article226570779.html |work=Charlotte Observer |access-date=February 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404155021/https://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/article226570779.html |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The day after the injury, Duke announced that Williamson was \"day-to-day\".<ref name=\"2021 Gleeson\" /> The incident led to growing calls for Williamson to stop playing basketball at the college level because he had already established himself as the top [[2019 NBA draft]] prospect.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jenkins |first1=Sally |title=Zion Williamson injury makes clear: The NCAA has turned education into a risk |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/colleges/zion-williamson-injury-makes-clear-the-ncaa-has-turned-education-into-a-risk/2019/02/21/6f14fd56-35f3-11e9-af5b-b51b7ff322e9_story.html |website=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=March 11, 2019 |date=February 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190311144943/https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/colleges/zion-williamson-injury-makes-clear-the-ncaa-has-turned-education-into-a-risk/2019/02/21/6f14fd56-35f3-11e9-af5b-b51b7ff322e9_story.html |archive-date=March 11, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wertz Jr. |first1=Langston |title=NBA players urge Zion Williamson to shut it down after bizarre injury during UNC game |url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/latest-news/article226561629.html |website=[[The Charlotte Observer]] |access-date=March 11, 2019 |date=February 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190303064836/https://www.charlotteobserver.com/latest-news/article226561629.html |archive-date=March 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, the injury resulted in more criticism of the NCAA for not paying student-athletes.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sullivan |first1=Tim |title=Zion Williamson's injury underscores the inequities of college sports |url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/2019/02/21/zion-williamson-injury-underscores-inequities-ncaa-sports/2937819002/ |website=[[The Courier-Journal]] |access-date=March 11, 2019 |date=February 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Gregory |first1=Sean |title=Zion Williamson's Exploding Shoe Is a Reminder That College Basketball Needs Serious Fixing |url=http://time.com/5534615/zion-williamson-shoe-college-basketball/ |website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |access-date=March 11, 2019 |date=February 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190305050022/http://time.com/5534615/zion-williamson-shoe-college-basketball/ |archive-date=March 5, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Skinner |first1=Nancy |title=How to pay NCAA athletes like Zion Williamson without costing colleges a dime |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2019/02/26/how-pay-ncaa-athletes-without-costing-colleges-dime/ |website=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=March 11, 2019 |date=February 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190305155957/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2019/02/26/how-pay-ncaa-athletes-without-costing-colleges-dime/ |archive-date=March 5, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He was held out from his team's final six games in the regular season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Zion Williamson Caps Stunning Return, Leading Duke to A.C.C. Title |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/17/sports/college-basketball-tournaments-zion-williamson.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=April 3, 2019 |date=March 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404144058/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/17/sports/college-basketball-tournaments-zion-williamson.html |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> When the regular season concluded, Williamson earned [[Atlantic Coast Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year|Player of the Year]] and [[Atlantic Coast Conference Men's Basketball Rookie of the Year|Rookie of the Year]] honors in the ACC, joining former Duke players [[Jahlil Okafor]] and Marvin Bagley III as the only recipients of both awards. Williamson was also named [[ACC Athlete of the Year]], becoming the 10th Duke player to win the Award.<ref>{{Cite news|url= http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=22737&SPID=1845&DB_LANG=C&DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211806496|title=Williamson Voted ACC Male Athlete of the Year|last=|first=|date=|work=www.goduke.com|access-date=July 25, 2019}}</ref> He additionally made the ACC All-Defensive and All-Freshman teams.<ref>{{cite web |title=ACC 2019 Men's Basketball All-Conference Team, Postseason Awards |url=https://accsports.com/acc-news/acc-2019-mens-basketball-all-conference-team-postseason-awards/ |publisher=[[Atlantic Coast Conference]] |access-date=March 11, 2019 |date=March 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330211136/https://accsports.com/acc-news/acc-2019-mens-basketball-all-conference-team-postseason-awards/ |archive-date=March 30, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Sporting News]]'' named Williamson as its [[Sporting News Men's College Basketball Player of the Year|Player of the Year]] and Freshman of the Year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=DeCourcy |first1=Mike |title=Duke's Zion Williamson is Sporting News Player, Freshman of the Year |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/us/ncaa-basketball/news/dukes-zion-williamson-is-sporting-news-player-freshman-of-the-year/rnnni0dhtiwzcfrcty42nm6 |website=[[Sporting News]] |access-date=March 15, 2019 |date=March 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190314144805/http://www.sportingnews.com/us/ncaa-basketball/news/dukes-zion-williamson-is-sporting-news-player-freshman-of-the-year/rnnni0dhtiwzcfrcty42nm6 |archive-date=March 14, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He returned from injury on March 14, posting 29 points, 14 rebounds, and 5 steals in an 84\u201372 win over Syracuse in the quarterfinals of the [[2019 ACC Men's Basketball Tournament|ACC Tournament]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tracy |first1=Marc |title=Zion Williamson Returns in Style, Leading Duke to Victory Over Syracuse |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/14/sports/duke-zion-williamson-returns.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=March 15, 2019 |date=March 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190315174326/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/14/sports/duke-zion-williamson-returns.html |archive-date=March 15, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He shot 13-of-13 from the field, marking the best shooting performance in school and tournament history, while tying the best in ACC history.<ref>{{cite web |title=Duke University Men's Basketball Postgame Notes March 14, 2019 \u2013 vs. Syracuse (ACC Tournament Quarterfinals) |url=http://www.goduke.com/pdf9/5485015.pdf?_ga=2.249588290.514877976.1552629767-814154638.1552629766 |publisher=Duke Athletics |access-date=March 15, 2019 |date=March 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190322011420/http://www.goduke.com/pdf9/5485015.pdf?_ga=2.249588290.514877976.1552629767-814154638.1552629766 |archive-date=March 22, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson also became the first Duke player to record at least 25 points, 10 rebounds, and 5 steals in a game since [[Christian Laettner]] in 1992.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Parrish |first1=Gary |title=Duke remains No. 5 in Top 25 And 1 after Zion Williamson's incredible return |url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/college-basketball-rankings-duke-remains-no-5-in-top-25-and-1-after-zion-williamsons-incredible-return/ |publisher=[[CBS Sports]] |access-date=March 15, 2019 |date=March 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404171457/https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/college-basketball-rankings-duke-remains-no-5-in-top-25-and-1-after-zion-williamsons-incredible-return/ |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The next day, he scored 31 points including the game-winner to help Duke defeat North Carolina, 74\u201373, in the ACC Tournament semifinals.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jones |first1=Jonathan |title=Zion Williamson Puts on a Show in Classic Duke-UNC Rivalry Game |url=https://www.si.com/college-basketball/2019/03/16/zion-williamson-puts-show-duke-defeats-unc-acc-tourney |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=April 3, 2019 |date=March 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404144101/https://www.si.com/college-basketball/2019/03/16/zion-williamson-puts-show-duke-defeats-unc-acc-tourney |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> After posting 21 points in a 73\u201363 victory over Florida State in the championship game, Williamson was named ACC Tournament MVP, becoming the sixth freshman to win the honor.<ref>{{cite web |title=Duke Beats FSU for Program's 21st ACC Title |url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211795899 |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=April 3, 2019 |date=March 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404155053/http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211795899 |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFor the [[2019 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|2019 NCAA Tournament]], official broadcast partner [[CBS]] specifically devoted a camera\u2014called the \"Zion Cam\"\u2014to record Williamson throughout the tournament.<ref name=\"zioncam\">{{cite web |last1=Lauletta |first1=Tyler |title=CBS hired a special cameraman to work the 'Zion Cam' and record every move the Duke star makes in his NCAA tournament run |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/zion-williamson-cbs-cam-march-madness-2019-3 |website=[[Business Insider]] |accessdate=April 3, 2019 |date=March 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404144059/https://www.businessinsider.com/zion-williamson-cbs-cam-march-madness-2019-3 |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In his NCAA Tournament debut on March 22, he scored 25 points in an 85\u201362 win over 16th-seeded [[North Dakota State Bison men's basketball|North Dakota State]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Top-Seeded Duke Beats NDSU, 85-62, in NCAA Opener |url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211796767 |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=April 3, 2019 |date=March 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401030801/http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211796767 |archive-date=April 1, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On March 24, Williamson erupted for 32 points, 11 rebounds, and 4 assists in a 77\u201376 second round victory over [[UCF Knights men's basketball|UCF]]. He was the first player in school history to record at least 25 points, 10 rebounds, and 4 assists in an NCAA Tournament game.<ref>{{cite web |title=Duke University Men's Basketball Postgame Notes March 24, 2019 \u2013 vs. UCF |url=http://www.goduke.com/pdf9/5485603.pdf |publisher=Duke Athletics |accessdate=April 3, 2019 |date=March 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404144057/http://www.goduke.com/pdf9/5485603.pdf |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson led all scorers on March 31, with 24 points and 14 rebounds in a season-ending 68\u201367 loss to [[Michigan State Spartans men's basketball|Michigan State]] in the Elite 8.<ref>{{cite web |title=Duke Falls to Michigan State, 68-67 |url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211797994 |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=April 3, 2019 |date=March 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401145312/http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211797994 |archive-date=April 1, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Through 33 appearances in his freshman season, he averaged 22.6 points, 8.9 rebounds, 2.1 steals, and 1.8 blocks per game.<ref name=\"stats\">{{cite web |title=Zion Williamson Stats |url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/player/stats/_/id/4395628/zion-williamson |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=April 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401220400/http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/player/stats/_/id/4395628/zion-williamson |archive-date=April 1, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He shot 68% from the field, which led the ACC, ranked second in the NCAA Division I, and was the highest ever field goal percentage by a freshman.<ref>{{cite web |title=Zion Williamson Named NABC Player, Freshman of the Year |url=https://dukereport.com/duke-basketball/zion-williamson-named-nabc-player-freshman-of-the-year-dis/ |publisher=Duke Report |accessdate=April 3, 2019 |date=April 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404144059/https://dukereport.com/duke-basketball/zion-williamson-named-nabc-player-freshman-of-the-year-dis/ |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"nola\">{{cite web |last1=Duncan |first1=Jeff |title=Zion Williamson could transform basketball in New Orleans and the Pelicans must do everything they can to get him |url=https://www.nola.com/pelicans/2019/04/zion-williamson-could-transform-basketball-in-new-orleans-and-the-pelicans-must-try-to-get-him.html |website=[[The Times-Picayune]] |accessdate=April 3, 2019 |date=April 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404144059/https://www.nola.com/pelicans/2019/04/zion-williamson-could-transform-basketball-in-new-orleans-and-the-pelicans-must-try-to-get-him.html |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, Williamson joined [[Kevin Durant]] and [[Anthony Davis]] as the only freshmen to collect 500 points, 50 steals, and 50 blocks in a season.<ref name=nola/>\n\nOn April 15, 2019, Williamson declared his eligibility for the 2019 NBA draft.<ref>{{cite web |title=Zion declares for draft after 'best year' of life |url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/26532333/zion-declares-draft-best-year-life |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=May 17, 2019 |date=April 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424015808/http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/26532333/zion-declares-draft-best-year-life |archive-date=April 24, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> After the [[New Orleans Pelicans]] won the 2019 [[NBA draft lottery]], Williamson's stepfather Lee Anderson said they were excited about him potentially playing in New Orleans and dismissed rumors that he would return to Duke for a second year, saying, \"As far as returning to Duke, that's not something we've even considered.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shapiro |first1=Michael |title=Zion Williamson's Stepfather Says Former Duke Star Won't Return to College After Pelicans Won Lottery |url=https://www.si.com/nba/2019/05/16/zion-williamson-pelicans-nba-draft-lottery-duke-freshman |website=SI.com |accessdate=May 17, 2019 |date=May 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190516153242/https://www.si.com/nba/2019/05/16/zion-williamson-pelicans-nba-draft-lottery-duke-freshman |archive-date=May 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nOn June 20, 2019, the [[New Orleans Pelicans]] drafted Williamson with the first pick in the [[2019 NBA draft]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/27018830|title=Pelicans pick Zion to open draft, Morant goes 2nd|date=June 20, 2019|website=ESPN.com|access-date=June 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621074618/https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/27018830|archive-date=June 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/basketball/48716152|title=NBA draft: Zion Williamson is selected first by the New Orleans Pelicans|date=June 21, 2019|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=June 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621113729/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/basketball/48716152|archive-date=June 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On July 1, 2019, Williamson officially signed with the Pelicans.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pelicans sign Zion Williamson |url=https://www.nba.com/pelicans/pelicans-sign-zion-williamson |website=NBA.com |accessdate=July 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701203732/https://www.nba.com/pelicans/pelicans-sign-zion-williamson |archive-date=July 1, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson tore his [[Tear of meniscus|meniscus]] on October 13, 2019, during the preseason of his rookie campaign.<ref>{{cite web |title=Where is Zion Williamson? |url=https://www.sbnation.com/nba/2019/12/25/21036567/zion-williamson-injury-new-orleans-pelicans-why-isnt-he-playing |website=sbnation.com |accessdate=December 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191226035102/https://www.sbnation.com/nba/2019/12/25/21036567/zion-williamson-injury-new-orleans-pelicans-why-isnt-he-playing |archive-date=December 26, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson made his professional debut three months later on January 22, 2020 in a 121\u2013117 loss to the [[San Antonio Spurs]]. He played 18 minutes and finished with 22 points and 7 rebounds, scoring 17 consecutive points in 3:08 minutes during the fourth quarter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28542223/pelicans-zion-williamson-erupts-17-4th-sits-final-minutes-debut|title=Pelicans' Zion Williamson erupts for 17 in 4th, sits out final minutes of debut|website=espn.com|publisher=ESPN|first=Andrew|last=Lopez|date=January 22, 2020|accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref> He would later become the first teenager in NBA history to score 20+ points in 10 consecutive games.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Young |first1=Ryan |title=Zion Williamson becomes first teenager in NBA history with 10 straight 20-point games |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/new-orleans-pelicans-zion-williamson-first-teenager-nba-history-10-straight-20-point-games-034707525.html |website=sports.yahoo.com |accessdate=April 18, 2020 |date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> On March 1, Williamson scored a career-high 35 points, along with 7 rebounds, in a 122\u2013114 loss to the [[Los Angeles Lakers]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Botkin |first1=Brad |title=Zion Williamson goes toe to toe with LeBron James, extends teenage record with a career-high 35 points |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/zion-williamson-goes-toe-to-toe-with-lebron-james-extends-teenage-record-with-a-career-high-35-points/ |website=cbssports.com |accessdate=April 18, 2020 |date=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Player profile==\n[[File:Zion Williamson - Keenan Hairston (cropped).jpg|thumb|Williamson goes in for a slam dunk against [[Hartford Hawks men's basketball|Hartford]], December 2018]]\nWilliamson is listed at {{Height|ft=6|in=6}} tall and weighs {{convert|285|lbs|kg|0}}.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |title=Zion Williamson |url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211767525 |publisher=[[Duke Blue Devils]] |accessdate=August 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822020553/http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211767525 |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Boone |first1=Kyle |title=Why 5-star Zion Williamson would fit better at Clemson than Kentucky, Kansas, or Duke |url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/why-5-star-zion-williamson-would-fit-better-at-clemson-than-kentucky-kansas-or-duke/ |publisher=[[CBS Sports]] |accessdate=August 20, 2018 |date=January 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822014952/https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/why-5-star-zion-williamson-would-fit-better-at-clemson-than-kentucky-kansas-or-duke/ |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Despite his heavy weight for a basketball player, he is known for his speed and [[Vertical jump|leaping]] ability.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Phillips |first1=Scott |title=Zion Williamson breaks Duke vertical leap record |url=https://collegebasketball.nbcsports.com/2018/07/07/zion-williamson-breaks-duke-vertical-leap-record/ |publisher=[[NBC Sports]] |accessdate=August 21, 2018 |date=July 7, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"willitwork\">{{cite web |last1=O'Donnell |first1=Ricky |title=We've never seen anyone like Zion Williamson ... but will his game work in the NBA? |url=https://www.sbnation.com/2017/10/19/16454852/zion-williamson-recruit-highlights-nba |publisher=[[SB Nation]] |accessdate=August 21, 2018 |date=October 19, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822014950/https://www.sbnation.com/2017/10/19/16454852/zion-williamson-recruit-highlights-nba |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> NBA player [[Kevin Durant]] described him as a \"once-in-a-generation type athlete\" while an anonymous [[college basketball]] coach labeled him a \"freak of nature\".<ref name=\"johnson\">{{cite web |last1=Johnson |first1=Chris |title=Zion Williamson: Basketball's next dunking prodigy |url=https://www.si.com/longform/2017/zion-williamson-basketball-dunks-high-school/index.html |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=August 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707010252/https://www.si.com/longform/2017/zion-williamson-basketball-dunks-high-school/index.html |archive-date=July 7, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"durant\">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Cam |title=Kevin Durant on Zion Williamson: 'He's a once-in-a-generation type athlete' |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2017/kevin-durant-on-zion-williamson-hes-a-once-in-a-generation-type-athlete |newspaper=[[USA Today|USA Today High School Sports]] |accessdate=August 20, 2018 |date=November 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822014842/https://usatodayhss.com/2017/kevin-durant-on-zion-williamson-hes-a-once-in-a-generation-type-athlete |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson plays the [[power forward (basketball)|power forward]] position but is also capable of being a [[Small ball (basketball)|small-ball]] [[center (basketball)|center]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Westerholm |first1=Tony |title=Zion Williamson to Duke: Three takeaways as hyper-athletic forward joins Blue Devils mens basketball |url=https://www.masslive.com/hoophallclassic/index.ssf/2018/01/zion_williamson_to_duke_four_t.html |website=[[The Republican (Springfield, Massachusetts)|The Republican]] |accessdate=August 20, 2018 |date=January 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822045938/https://www.masslive.com/hoophallclassic/index.ssf/2018/01/zion_williamson_to_duke_four_t.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> However, he is best played as a forward due to his size. He has been described as not fitting a specific [[basketball positions|basketball position]].<ref name=\"gauntlet\">{{cite web|last1=Bossi|first1=Eric|title=Adidas Gauntlet: Feeding frenzy for five-star Langford|url=https://basketballrecruiting.rivals.com/news/adidas-gauntlet-feeding-frenzy-for-five-star-langford|website=[[Rivals.com]]|accessdate=January 14, 2018|date=April 18, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180115184704/https://basketballrecruiting.rivals.com/news/adidas-gauntlet-feeding-frenzy-for-five-star-langford|archive-date=January 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> His physical attributes have drawn comparisons to former NBA stars [[Charles Barkley]], [[Anthony Mason (basketball)|Anthony Mason]], and [[Larry Johnson (basketball, born 1969)|Larry Johnson]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Astramskas |first1=David |title=The Insane Growth Of The Man-Child That Is Zion Williamson |url=http://ballislife.com/zion-williamson-size/ |website=ballislife.com |accessdate=April 18, 2020 |date=August 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Bossi |first1=Eric |last2=Evans |first2=Corey |title=Rival Views: The best Zion Williamson comparison |url=https://basketballrecruiting.rivals.com/news/rival-views-the-best-zion-williamson-comparison |publisher=[[Rivals.com|Rivals]] |accessdate=August 20, 2018 |date=January 18, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822045958/https://basketballrecruiting.rivals.com/news/rival-views-the-best-zion-williamson-comparison |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, according to different analysts, he resembles NBA players [[LeBron James]] and [[Julius Randle]].<ref name=gauntlet/> Lee Sartor, Williamson's high school coach, reported that basketball coach [[Roy Williams (coach)|Roy Williams]] told Williamson \"that he was probably one of the best high school players he's seen since Michael Jordan\".<ref name=\"nextlebron\">{{cite web|last1=Fowler|first1=Scott|title=Is SC dunking phenom Zion Williamson basketball's next LeBron James?|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/spt-columns-blogs/scott-fowler/article133103369.html|website=[[The Charlotte Observer]]|accessdate=January 14, 2018|date=February 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108014943/http://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/spt-columns-blogs/scott-fowler/article133103369.html|archive-date=January 8, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson, who is [[handedness|left-handed]], is almost [[ambidextrous]], being adept using either hand.<ref name=gauntlet/>\n\nWhile in high school, Williamson drew national attention for his [[slam dunk]]s.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wiseman |first1=Steve |title=Duke's Zion Williamson talks dunks, his fame and learning from Coach K |url=https://www.myajc.com/sports/duke-zion-williamson-talks-dunks-his-fame-and-learning-from-coach/t2VPgpHpdUwLFWGFvXfglJ/ |website=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]] |accessdate=August 20, 2018 |date=August 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822014738/https://www.myajc.com/sports/duke-zion-williamson-talks-dunks-his-fame-and-learning-from-coach/t2VPgpHpdUwLFWGFvXfglJ/ |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Charlotte Observer]]'' remarked that he \"could be the best high-school dunker in history\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fowler |first1=Scott |title=Is Zion Williamson the best prep dunker ever? Watch this video from ONE GAME and drool |url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/spt-columns-blogs/scott-fowler/article132589769.html |website=[[The Charlotte Observer]] |accessdate=August 21, 2018 |date=February 14, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822015001/https://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/spt-columns-blogs/scott-fowler/article132589769.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> NBA point guard [[John Wall (basketball)|John Wall]] has likened Williamson's in-game dunking ability to that of [[Vince Carter]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nelson |first1=Ryne |title=John Wall: Zion Williamson Is Top 2\u20133 'Most Athletic Player I've Ever Seen' |url=https://www.slamonline.com/nba/john-wall-zion-williamson-top-2-3-most-athletic-player-ever-seen/ |website=[[Slam (magazine)|Slam]] |accessdate=August 20, 2018 |date=August 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824080552/http://www.slamonline.com/nba/john-wall-zion-williamson-top-2-3-most-athletic-player-ever-seen/ |archive-date=August 24, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson's outside shooting has been considered a point of concern, and he has unorthodox shot mechanics.<ref name=legend/><ref name=washpost/><ref name=\"stepien\">{{cite web |last1=Gribanov |first1=Mike |title=Draft Profile: Zion Williamson |url=https://www.thestepien.com/zion-williamson/ |publisher=The Stepien |accessdate=August 21, 2018 |date=November 11, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822014757/https://www.thestepien.com/zion-williamson/ |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Recruiting service [[247Sports.com|247Sports]] has praised his [[dribbling|ball handling]] and passing skills for his size, commenting that they are \"overshadowed by [his] athletic plays\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Flaherty |first1=Kevin |title=YouTube star Zion Williamson creates challenge for evaluators |url=https://247sports.com/Article/Duke-basketball-recruit-Zion-Williamson-could-have-unique-fits-in-college-and-NBA-game-117476807/ |publisher=[[247Sports.com|247Sports]] |accessdate=August 21, 2018 |date=April 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822014813/https://247sports.com/Article/Duke-basketball-recruit-Zion-Williamson-could-have-unique-fits-in-college-and-NBA-game-117476807/ |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson has the ability to defend multiple positions well due to his speed and length, although his defensive effort has been questioned.<ref name=\"westerholm\">{{cite web |last1=Westerholm |first1=Tom |title=Zion Williamson Scouting: How does the freakishly athletic HS forward project to the NBA? |url=https://www.masslive.com/hoophallclassic/index.ssf/2018/01/scouting_zion_williamson_how_d.html |website=[[The Republican (Springfield, Massachusetts)|The Republican]] |accessdate=August 21, 2018 |date=January 14, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822014747/https://www.masslive.com/hoophallclassic/index.ssf/2018/01/scouting_zion_williamson_how_d.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> His explosive play makes him a reliable [[block (basketball)|shot-blocker]] and gives him prowess as a [[rebound (basketball)|rebounder]].<ref name=\"realgm\">{{cite web |last1=Uehara |first1=Rafael |title=Prospect Report: Zion Williamson Of Duke |url=https://basketball.realgm.com/analysis/250890/Prospect-Report-Zion-Williamson-Of-Duke |publisher=[[RealGM]] |accessdate=August 21, 2018 |date=August 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180802113204/https://basketball.realgm.com/analysis/250890/Prospect-Report-Zion-Williamson-Of-Duke |archive-date=August 2, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===College===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2018\u201319 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2018\u201319]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2018\u201319 Duke Blue Devils men's basketball team|Duke]]\n| 33 || 33 || 30.0 || .680 || .338 || .640 || 8.9 || 2.1 || 2.1 || 1.8 || 22.6\n{{s-end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nWilliamson was born in [[Salisbury, North Carolina]] to Lateef Williamson and Sharonda Sampson.<ref name=\"growthspurt\">{{cite web|last1=Wertz, Jr.|first1=Langston|title=One of nation's top basketball recruits resides in Spartanburg, says Coach K offered scholarship|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/high-school/article112797658.html|website=[[The Charlotte Observer]]|accessdate=April 7, 2017|date=November 5, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170405170554/http://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/high-school/article112797658.html|archive-date=April 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Lateef was a football [[Lineman (gridiron football)|defensive lineman]] at [[Mayo High School for Math, Science, and Technology|Mayo High School]] in [[Darlington, South Carolina]] who was a 1993 High School All-American and had committed to [[NC State Wolfpack football|NC State]] before transferring to [[Livingstone College]].<ref name=legend/><ref name=growthspurt/> Sampson was a [[Sprint (running)|sprinter]] at Livingstone and became a middle school health and physical education teacher.<ref name=growthspurt/> She named Williamson after the [[Bible|biblical]] location [[Mount Zion]] near [[Jerusalem]], taking her grandmother's advice to name him \"something extra special\".<ref name=\"finest\">{{cite web|last1=Bezjak|first1=Lou|title=Williamson drawing attention as one of 2018's finest|url=http://www.thestate.com/sports/high-school/prep-basketball/article105425861.html|website=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]]|accessdate=April 7, 2017|date=October 1, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408083909/http://www.thestate.com/sports/high-school/prep-basketball/article105425861.html|archive-date=April 8, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> When Williamson reached two years of age, following the death of his maternal grandmother, his family moved to [[Florence, South Carolina]].<ref name=legend/><ref name=growthspurt/> By the time he was five years old, his parents divorced, and his mother married Lee Anderson, a former [[Clemson Tigers men's basketball|Clemson]] basketball player.<ref name=\"usatodayhss\">{{cite news|last1=Jordan|first1=Jason|title=Chick-fil-A Classic: Zion Williamson is taking the country by storm|url=http://usatodayhss.com/2016/chick-fil-a-classic-zion-williamson-is-taking-the-country-by-storm-duke-kentucky-north-carolina-drake|newspaper=[[USA Today|USA Today High School Sports]]|accessdate=April 7, 2017|date=December 23, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170409021041/http://usatodayhss.com/2016/chick-fil-a-classic-zion-williamson-is-taking-the-country-by-storm-duke-kentucky-north-carolina-drake|archive-date=April 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"legend\">{{cite web|last1=Fowler|first1=Scott|title=The legend of basketball phenom Zion Williamson|url=http://www.kentucky.com/sports/college/kentucky-sports/uk-recruiting/article133179434.html|website=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]|accessdate=April 7, 2017|date=February 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408082436/http://www.kentucky.com/sports/college/kentucky-sports/uk-recruiting/article133179434.html|archive-date=April 8, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn July 23, 2019, Williamson signed a five-year, $75 million shoe deal with [[Air Jordan|Jordan brand]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Zagoria |first1=Adam |title=Zion Williamson Signs Multiyear Deal With Jordan Brand |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/adamzagoria/2019/07/23/zion-williamson-signs-multi-year-deal-with-jordan-brand/#3136ef9317e2 |website=Forbes |accessdate=April 18, 2020 |date=July 23, 2019}}</ref> Williamson's deal is the second-largest rookie shoe deal in history, trailing only LeBron James's $90 million rookie deal signed in 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.si.com/nba/2019/07/24/zion-williamson-jordan-brand-shoe-deal-75-million-five-years|title=Report: Zion's shoe deal worth $75 million over five years|last=Abdeldaiem|first=Alaa|website=Sports Illustrated|access-date=December 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209201923/https://www.si.com/nba/2019/07/24/zion-williamson-jordan-brand-shoe-deal-75-million-five-years|archive-date=December 9, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nOn March 13, 2020, Williamson pledged to pay for the salaries of all the employees of the [[Smoothie King Center]] for 30 days during the [[suspension of the 2019-20 NBA season]] because of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Giannis Antetokounmpo, Zion Williamson among stars aiding arena workers |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28898869/giannis-antetokounmpo-pledges-100k-help-fiserv-forum-staff |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{basketballstats|nba=zion_williamson|bbr=w/willizi01}}\n* [http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211767525 Duke Blue Devils bio]\n* [http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/26406892/the-education-zion-williamson The Education of Zion Williamson]\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{New Orleans Pelicans current roster}}\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{2019 NBA draft}}\n{{NBA NumberOne Draft Picks}}\n{{Naismith Player of the Year men}}\n{{Wooden Player of the Year men}}\n{{Oscar Robertson Trophy}}\n{{Associated Press College Basketball Player of the Year}}\n{{NABC Player of the Year}}\n{{Sporting News College Men's Basketball Player of the Year}}\n{{2019 NCAA Men's Basketball Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{Atlantic Coast Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year navbox}}\n{{ACC Athlete of the Year navbox}}\n{{USBWA National Freshman of the Year}}\n{{Karl Malone Award}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|Sports}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williamson, Zion}}\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American basketball players]]\n[[Category:All-American college men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Duke Blue Devils men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:McDonald's High School All-Americans]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Pelicans draft picks]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Pelicans players]]\n[[Category:People from Salisbury, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Power forwards (basketball)]]\n[[Category:Small forwards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Spartanburg, South Carolina]]\n", "name_user": "Bagumba", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zion_Williamson"}
{"title_page": "Zenati languages", "text_new": "{{Infobox language family\n| name = Zenati\n| region = [[North Africa]]\n| familycolor = Afro-Asiatic\n| fam2 = [[Berber languages|Berber]]\n| fam3 = [[Northern Berber languages|Northern Berber]]\n| child1 = [[Riff languages|Riff]]\n| child2 = [[Mzab\u2013Wargla languages|Mzab\u2013Wargla]]\n| child3 = [[East Zenati|Libyan and Tunisian Zenati]]\n| child4 = [[Shenwa language|Shenwa]]\n| child5 = [[Eastern Morocco Zenati|Eastern Moroccan Zenati]]\n| child6 = [[Iznasen Berber|Beni Iznassen]]\n| glotto = zena1250\n| glottorefname = Zenatic\n| ancestor = \n| glottoname = \n| notes = \n| child7 = [[Shawiya language|Shawiya]]\n}}\nThe '''Zenati languages''' are a branch of the [[Northern Berber languages|Northern Berber language family]] of [[North Africa]]. They were named after the medieval [[Zenata]] [[Berbers|Berber]] tribal confederation. They were first proposed in the works of French linguist [[Edmond Destaing]] (1915)<ref>[[Edmond Destaing]], \"[http://www.aravr.org/telechargements/ESSAI_DE_CLASSIFICATION_des_dialectes_berbere_au_Maroc.pdf Essai de classification des dialectes berb\u00e8res du Maroc] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110904063033/http://www.aravr.org/telechargements/ESSAI_DE_CLASSIFICATION_des_dialectes_berbere_au_Maroc.pdf |date=September 4, 2011 }}\", ''Etudes et Documents Berb\u00e8res'' 19-20, 2001-2002 (1915)</ref> (1920\u201323).<ref>Edmond Destaing, \"Note sur la conjugaison des verbes de forme C1eC2\", ''M\u00e9moires de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Linguistique de Paris'', 22 (1920/3), pp. 139-148</ref> Zenata dialects are distributed across the central [[Maghreb]], from northeastern [[Morocco]] to just west of [[Algiers]], and the northern [[Sahara]], from southwestern [[Algeria]] around [[Bechar]] to [[Zuwara]] in [[Libya]]. In much of this range, they are limited to discontinuous pockets in a predominantly [[Arabic]]-speaking landscape. The most widely spoken Zenati languages are [[Riffian language|Riffian]] in northeastern Morocco and [[Shawiya language|Shawiya]] in eastern Algeria, each of which have over 2 million speakers.\n\n==Languages==\n\n===Kossmann (2013)===\nAccording to [[Maarten Kossmann|Kossmann]] (2013: 21&ndash;24),<ref name=Kossmann2013>Maarten Kossmann (2013) [https://books.google.fr/books?id=Se-BAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA23#v=snippet&q=%22eastern%20Riffian%22&f=false The Arabic Influence on Northern Berber]</ref> Zenati is a rather arbitrary grouping, in which he includes the following varieties:\n* [[Riffian language|Riffian]] (Riffian Berber, or Rif-Berber, local name: ''Tmazi\u0263t'', north of [[Morocco]])\n*[[Eastern Morocco Zenati|Beni Iznassen]] (east of Morocco)\n* [[Eastern Middle Atlas Berber|Eastern Middle Atlas]]: [[Ait Seghrouchen Berber|Ait Seghrouchen]] and a group of dialects including [[Ait Warain Berber|Ait Warain (Ayt Warayn)]] (north-central Morocco)\n*[[Western Algerian Zenatic dialects|Western Algerian]], west of [[Algiers]] (a diffuse group):\n**[[Beni Snous dialect|Beni Snous]] (Tlemcen) dialect, in western Algeria near the border\n**Jebel Bissa (intelligible with Shenwa)\n**[[Shenwa language|Shenwa]] (Chenoua), between [[Tipasa]] and [[T\u00e9n\u00e8s]] in north-central Algeria west of [[Algiers]]\n**[[Beni Messaoud]] (Shenwa?)\n**[[Beni Menacer Berber|Beni Menacer]]\n**[[Metmata Berber (Algeria)|Metmata]] (of Algeria; distinguish [[Matmata Berber]] of Tunisia)\n**etc. (see article)\n* [[Shawiya language|Shawiya]] (Chaouia), around [[Batna City|Batna]] and [[Khenchela]], south of [[Constantine, Algeria|Constantine]] in northeastern Algeria\n*[[Mzab\u2013Wargla languages|Mzab\u2013Wargla]] (Northern Saharan oases):\n** [[South Oran Berber|South Oran and Figuig]], in the [[ksar|ksours]] along the Algerian\u2013Moroccan border and in [[Figuig]] in southeastern Morocco\n** [[Gurara language|Gourara Berber]] (Taznatit) ([[Gourara]], southwestern Algeria, around [[Timimoun]])\n** [[Tidikelt language|Tidikelt]] and [[Tuat language|Tuat]] ([[Touat]], Algeria)\n** [[Mozabite language|Mozabite]] aka ''Mzab, Tumzabt'' (northern Algerian Sahara, near [[Ghardaia]])\n** [[Wargla language|Wargla]] (Ouargli aka ''Tagergrent, Teggargarent''), northern Algerian Sahara, near [[Ouargla]]\n** [[Tugurt language|Oued Righ Berber]] (incl. Touggourt; [[Ethnologue]] name \"Temacine Tamazight\") in [[Oued Righ]], around [[Touggourt]] and [[Temacine]], Algeria\n* Southeastern Tunisian&ndash;Libyan: [[Djerbi language|Djerbi]] (island of [[Djerba]]), [[Matmata Berber]] ([[Matmata, Tunisia|Matmata]]), [[Sened language|Sened]] and [[Zuwara Berber]] ([[Zuwara]] in northwestern [[Libya]])\n\n===Blench & Dendo (2006)===\n[[Roger Blench|Blench]] & Dendo (ms, 2006) considers Zenati to consist of just three distinct languages, with the rest (in parentheses) dialects:<ref>[http://rogerblench.info/Language/Afroasiatic/General/AALIST.pdf AA list], Blench & Dendo, ms, 2006</ref>\n\n*[[Riff languages|Riff cluster]] (Shawiya, Tidikelt, Tuat, Tariifit/Riff, Ghmara, Tlemcen, Sheliff Basin)\n*[[Mzab\u2013Wargla languages|Mzab\u2013Wargla]] (Gurara, Mzab, Wargla, Ghardaia, Tugurt, Seghru\u0161en, Figuig, Senhaja, Iznacen)\n*[[East Zenati]] (Tmagurt, Sened, Jerba, Tamezret, Taujjut, Nefusi, Zrawa)\nShenwa and Zuwara are not addressed.\n\n==Features==\nAccording to Kossmann (1999:31-32, 86, 172),<ref name=Kossmann>Maarten Kossmann, ''Essai sur la phonologie du proto-berb\u00e8re'', R\u00fcdiger K\u00f6ppe:K\u00f6ln</ref> common innovations defining the Zenati languages include:\n* The vowel ''a-'' in nominal prefixes is dropped in a number of words when it precedes CV, where C is a single consonant and V is a full (non-[[schwa]]) vowel.  For example, ''afus'' \"hand\" is replaced with ''fus''.  (A similar development is found in some [[Eastern Berber languages]], but not Nafusi.)\n* Verbs whose original aorist forms end in ''-u'' while their perfect forms end in ''-a'' end up with ''-a'' in the aorist as well, leaving the aorist / perfect distinction unmarked for these verbs.  For example, *''ktu'' \"forget\", Siwi ''ttu'', becomes Ouargli ''tta''.  (This also affects [[Nafusi language|Nafusi]].)\n* Verbs consisting (in the aorist) of two consonants with no vowel other than schwa fall into two classes elsewhere in Berber:<ref>Maarten Kossmann, \"[https://openaccess.leidenuniv.nl/bitstream/1887/4157/1/1267577_042.pdf Note sur la conjugaison des verbes CC \u00e0 voyelle alternante en berb\u00e8re]\", Etudes et Documents Berb\u00e8res 12, 1994, pp. 17-33</ref><ref>Andr\u00e9 Basset, ''La langue berb\u00e8re. Morphologie. Le verbe.-\u00c9tude de th\u00e8mes''. Paris 1929, pp. 9, 58</ref> one where a variable final vowel appears in the perfect form, and one which continues to lack a final vowel in the perfect.  In Zenati, the latter class has been entirely merged into the former in the perfect, with the single exception of the negative perfect of *''\u0259\u0263 s'' \"want\".  For example, [[Kabyle language|Kabyle]] (non-Zenati) ''g\u0259r'' \"throw\", pf. ''-g\u0259r'' (int. ''-ggar''), corresponds to Ouargli (Zenati) ''g\u0259r'', pf. ''-gru''. (This change too also affects [[Nafusi language|Nafusi]]; Basset (1929:9) gives examples where it appears not to occur in Chenoua.)\n* [[Proto-Berber]] *''-\u0259\u03b2'' has become ''-i'' in Zenati.<ref>See also Maarten Kossmann, \"[https://www.openaccess.leidenuniv.nl/bitstream/1887/4153/1/1267577_036.pdf Les verbes \u00e0 i finale en z\u00e9n\u00e8te] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718173608/https://www.openaccess.leidenuniv.nl/bitstream/1887/4153/1/1267577_036.pdf |date=July 18, 2011 }}\", Etudes et Documents Berb\u00e8res 13, 1995, pp. 99-104.</ref>  For example, *''ar\u0259\u03b2'' \"write\" becomes ''ari''.  (This change also occurs in varieties including the [[Central Atlas Tamazight]] dialect of the [[Zayanes|Izayan]], Nafusi, and [[Siwi language|Siwi]].)\n* Proto-Berber palatalised ''k\u00b4'' and ''g\u00b4'', corresponding to ''k'' and ''g'' in non-Zenati varieties, become ''\u0161'' and ''\u017e'' in Zenati (although a fair number of irregular correspondences for this are found.)  For example, ''k\u00b4\u0103m'' \"you (f. sg.)\" becomes ''\u0161\u0259m''. (This change also occurs in Nafusi and Siwi.)\n\nIn addition to the correspondence of ''k'' and ''g'' to ''\u0161'' and ''\u017e'', Chaker (1972),<ref>[[Salem Chaker]], 1972, \"[http://www.persee.fr/web/revues/home/prescript/article/remmm_0035-1474_1972_num_11_1_1152 La langue berb\u00e8re au Sahara]\", ''Revue de l'Occident musulman et de la M\u00e9diterran\u00e9e'' 11:11, pp. 163-167</ref> while expressing uncertainty about the linguistic coherence of Zenati, notes as shared Zenati traits:\n* A proximal demonstrative suffix \"this\" ''-u'', rather than ''-a''\n* A final ''-u'' in the perfect of two-consonant verbs, rather than ''-a'' (e.g. ''y\u0259-nsu'' \"he slept\" rather than ''y\u0259-nsa'' elsewhere)\nThese characteristics identify a more restricted subset of Berber than those previously mentioned, mainly northern Saharan varieties; they exclude, for example, Chaoui<ref># Penchoen, Th.G., 1973, ''Etude syntaxique d'un parler berb\u00e8re (Ait Frah de l'Aur\u00e8s)'', Napoli, Istituto Universitario Orientale (= Studi magrebini V). p. 14</ref> and all but the easternmost [[Riffian language|Riff]] dialects.<ref>Lafkioui, Mena. 2007. ''Atlas linguistique des vari\u00e9t\u00e9s berb\u00e8res du Rif''. K\u00f6ln: R\u00fcdiger K\u00f6ppe. pp. 207, 178.</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{berber languages}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zenati Languages}}\n[[Category:Berber languages]]\n[[Category:Berbers in Algeria]]\n[[Category:Berbers in Morocco]]\n[[Category:Languages of Algeria]]\n[[Category:Languages of Morocco]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language family\n| name = Zenati\n| region = [[North Africa]]\n| familycolor = Afro-Asiatic\n| fam2 = [[Berber languages|Berber]]\n| fam3 = [[Northern Berber languages|Northern Berber]]\n| child1 = [[Riff languages|Riff]]\n| child2 = [[Mzab\u2013Wargla languages|Mzab\u2013Wargla]]\n| child3 = [[East Zenati|Libyan and Tunisian Zenati]]\n| child4 = [[Shenwa language|Shenwa]]\n| child5 = [[Eastern Morocco Zenati|Eastern Moroccan Zenati]]\n| child6 = [[Iznasen Berber|Iznasen]]\n| glotto = zena1250\n| glottorefname = Zenatic\n| ancestor = \n| glottoname = \n| notes = \n| child7 = [[Shawiya language|Shawiya]]\n}}\nThe '''Zenati languages''' are a branch of the [[Northern Berber languages|Northern Berber language family]] of [[North Africa]]. They were named after the medieval [[Zenata]] [[Berbers|Berber]] tribal confederation. They were first proposed in the works of French linguist [[Edmond Destaing]] (1915)<ref>[[Edmond Destaing]], \"[http://www.aravr.org/telechargements/ESSAI_DE_CLASSIFICATION_des_dialectes_berbere_au_Maroc.pdf Essai de classification des dialectes berb\u00e8res du Maroc] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110904063033/http://www.aravr.org/telechargements/ESSAI_DE_CLASSIFICATION_des_dialectes_berbere_au_Maroc.pdf |date=September 4, 2011 }}\", ''Etudes et Documents Berb\u00e8res'' 19-20, 2001-2002 (1915)</ref> (1920\u201323).<ref>Edmond Destaing, \"Note sur la conjugaison des verbes de forme C1eC2\", ''M\u00e9moires de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Linguistique de Paris'', 22 (1920/3), pp. 139-148</ref> Zenata dialects are distributed across the central [[Maghreb]], from northeastern [[Morocco]] to just west of [[Algiers]], and the northern [[Sahara]], from southwestern [[Algeria]] around [[Bechar]] to [[Zuwara]] in [[Libya]]. In much of this range, they are limited to discontinuous pockets in a predominantly [[Arabic]]-speaking landscape. The most widely spoken Zenati languages are [[Riffian language|Riffian]] in northeastern Morocco and [[Shawiya language|Shawiya]] in eastern Algeria, each of which have over 2 million speakers.\n\n==Languages==\n\n===Kossmann (2013)===\nAccording to [[Maarten Kossmann|Kossmann]] (2013: 21&ndash;24),<ref name=Kossmann2013>Maarten Kossmann (2013) [https://books.google.fr/books?id=Se-BAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA23#v=snippet&q=%22eastern%20Riffian%22&f=false The Arabic Influence on Northern Berber]</ref> Zenati is a rather arbitrary grouping, in which he includes the following varieties:\n* [[Riffian language|Riffian]] (Riffian Berber, or Rif-Berber, local name: ''Tmazi\u0263t'', north of [[Morocco]]); Includes [[Arzew Berber|Arzew]] dialect, in [[Arzew]] in western Algeria\n*[[Eastern Morocco Zenati|Iznasen]] (north east of Morocco)\n* [[Eastern Middle Atlas Berber|Eastern Middle Atlas]]: [[Ait Seghrouchen Berber|Ait Seghrouchen]] and a group of dialects including [[Ait Warain Berber|Ait Warain (Ayt Warayn)]] (north-central Morocco)\n*[[Western Algerian Zenatic dialects|Western Algerian]], west of [[Algiers]] (a diffuse group):\n**[[Beni Snous dialect|Beni Snous]] (Tlemcen) dialect, in western Algeria near the border\n**Jebel Bissa (intelligible with Shenwa)\n**[[Shenwa language|Shenwa]] (Chenoua), between [[Tipasa]] and [[T\u00e9n\u00e8s]] in north-central Algeria west of [[Algiers]]\n**[[Beni Messaoud]] (Shenwa?)\n**[[Beni Menacer Berber|Beni Menacer]]\n**[[Metmata Berber (Algeria)|Metmata]] (of Algeria; distinguish [[Matmata Berber]] of Tunisia)\n**etc. (see article)\n* [[Shawiya language|Shawiya]] (Chaouia), around [[Batna City|Batna]] and [[Khenchela]], south of [[Constantine, Algeria|Constantine]] in northeastern Algeria\n*[[Mzab\u2013Wargla languages|Mzab\u2013Wargla]] (Northern Saharan oases):\n** [[South Oran Berber|South Oran and Figuig]], in the [[ksar|ksours]] along the Algerian\u2013Moroccan border and in [[Figuig]] in southeastern Morocco\n** [[Gurara language|Gourara Berber]] (Taznatit) ([[Gourara]], southwestern Algeria, around [[Timimoun]])\n** [[Tidikelt language|Tidikelt]] and [[Tuat language|Tuat]] ([[Touat]], Algeria)\n** [[Mozabite language|Mozabite]] aka ''Mzab, Tumzabt'' (northern Algerian Sahara, near [[Ghardaia]])\n** [[Wargla language|Wargla]] (Ouargli aka ''Tagergrent, Teggargarent''), northern Algerian Sahara, near [[Ouargla]]\n** [[Tugurt language|Oued Righ Berber]] (incl. Touggourt; [[Ethnologue]] name \"Temacine Tamazight\") in [[Oued Righ]], around [[Touggourt]] and [[Temacine]], Algeria\n* Southeastern Tunisian&ndash;Libyan: [[Djerbi language|Djerbi]] (island of [[Djerba]]), [[Matmata Berber]] ([[Matmata, Tunisia|Matmata]]), [[Sened language|Sened]] and [[Zuwara Berber]] ([[Zuwara]] in northwestern [[Libya]])\n\n===Blench & Dendo (2006)===\n[[Roger Blench|Blench]] & Dendo (ms, 2006) considers Zenati to consist of just three distinct languages, with the rest (in parentheses) dialects:<ref>[http://rogerblench.info/Language/Afroasiatic/General/AALIST.pdf AA list], Blench & Dendo, ms, 2006</ref>\n\n*[[Riff languages|Riff cluster]] (Shawiya, Tidikelt, Tuat, Tariifit/Riff, Ghmara, Tlemcen, Sheliff Basin)\n*[[Mzab\u2013Wargla languages|Mzab\u2013Wargla]] (Gurara, Mzab, Wargla, Ghardaia, Tugurt, Seghru\u0161en, Figuig, Senhaja, Iznacen)\n*[[East Zenati]] (Tmagurt, Sened, Jerba, Tamezret, Taujjut, Nefusi, Zrawa)\nShenwa and Zuwara are not addressed.\n\n==Features==\nAccording to Kossmann (1999:31-32, 86, 172),<ref name=Kossmann>Maarten Kossmann, ''Essai sur la phonologie du proto-berb\u00e8re'', R\u00fcdiger K\u00f6ppe:K\u00f6ln</ref> common innovations defining the Zenati languages include:\n* The vowel ''a-'' in nominal prefixes is dropped in a number of words when it precedes CV, where C is a single consonant and V is a full (non-[[schwa]]) vowel.  For example, ''afus'' \"hand\" is replaced with ''fus''.  (A similar development is found in some [[Eastern Berber languages]], but not Nafusi.)\n* Verbs whose original aorist forms end in ''-u'' while their perfect forms end in ''-a'' end up with ''-a'' in the aorist as well, leaving the aorist / perfect distinction unmarked for these verbs.  For example, *''ktu'' \"forget\", Siwi ''ttu'', becomes Ouargli ''tta''.  (This also affects [[Nafusi language|Nafusi]].)\n* Verbs consisting (in the aorist) of two consonants with no vowel other than schwa fall into two classes elsewhere in Berber:<ref>Maarten Kossmann, \"[https://openaccess.leidenuniv.nl/bitstream/1887/4157/1/1267577_042.pdf Note sur la conjugaison des verbes CC \u00e0 voyelle alternante en berb\u00e8re]\", Etudes et Documents Berb\u00e8res 12, 1994, pp. 17-33</ref><ref>Andr\u00e9 Basset, ''La langue berb\u00e8re. Morphologie. Le verbe.-\u00c9tude de th\u00e8mes''. Paris 1929, pp. 9, 58</ref> one where a variable final vowel appears in the perfect form, and one which continues to lack a final vowel in the perfect.  In Zenati, the latter class has been entirely merged into the former in the perfect, with the single exception of the negative perfect of *''\u0259\u0263 s'' \"want\".  For example, [[Kabyle language|Kabyle]] (non-Zenati) ''g\u0259r'' \"throw\", pf. ''-g\u0259r'' (int. ''-ggar''), corresponds to Ouargli (Zenati) ''g\u0259r'', pf. ''-gru''. (This change too also affects [[Nafusi language|Nafusi]]; Basset (1929:9) gives examples where it appears not to occur in Chenoua.)\n* [[Proto-Berber]] *''-\u0259\u03b2'' has become ''-i'' in Zenati.<ref>See also Maarten Kossmann, \"[https://www.openaccess.leidenuniv.nl/bitstream/1887/4153/1/1267577_036.pdf Les verbes \u00e0 i finale en z\u00e9n\u00e8te] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718173608/https://www.openaccess.leidenuniv.nl/bitstream/1887/4153/1/1267577_036.pdf |date=July 18, 2011 }}\", Etudes et Documents Berb\u00e8res 13, 1995, pp. 99-104.</ref>  For example, *''ar\u0259\u03b2'' \"write\" becomes ''ari''.  (This change also occurs in varieties including the [[Central Atlas Tamazight]] dialect of the [[Zayanes|Izayan]], Nafusi, and [[Siwi language|Siwi]].)\n* Proto-Berber palatalised ''k\u00b4'' and ''g\u00b4'', corresponding to ''k'' and ''g'' in non-Zenati varieties, become ''\u0161'' and ''\u017e'' in Zenati (although a fair number of irregular correspondences for this are found.)  For example, ''k\u00b4\u0103m'' \"you (f. sg.)\" becomes ''\u0161\u0259m''. (This change also occurs in Nafusi and Siwi.)\n\nIn addition to the correspondence of ''k'' and ''g'' to ''\u0161'' and ''\u017e'', Chaker (1972),<ref>[[Salem Chaker]], 1972, \"[http://www.persee.fr/web/revues/home/prescript/article/remmm_0035-1474_1972_num_11_1_1152 La langue berb\u00e8re au Sahara]\", ''Revue de l'Occident musulman et de la M\u00e9diterran\u00e9e'' 11:11, pp. 163-167</ref> while expressing uncertainty about the linguistic coherence of Zenati, notes as shared Zenati traits:\n* A proximal demonstrative suffix \"this\" ''-u'', rather than ''-a''\n* A final ''-u'' in the perfect of two-consonant verbs, rather than ''-a'' (e.g. ''y\u0259-nsu'' \"he slept\" rather than ''y\u0259-nsa'' elsewhere)\nThese characteristics identify a more restricted subset of Berber than those previously mentioned, mainly northern Saharan varieties; they exclude, for example, Chaoui<ref># Penchoen, Th.G., 1973, ''Etude syntaxique d'un parler berb\u00e8re (Ait Frah de l'Aur\u00e8s)'', Napoli, Istituto Universitario Orientale (= Studi magrebini V). p. 14</ref> and all but the easternmost [[Riffian language|Riff]] dialects.<ref>Lafkioui, Mena. 2007. ''Atlas linguistique des vari\u00e9t\u00e9s berb\u00e8res du Rif''. K\u00f6ln: R\u00fcdiger K\u00f6ppe. pp. 207, 178.</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{berber languages}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zenati Languages}}\n[[Category:Berber languages]]\n[[Category:Berbers in Algeria]]\n[[Category:Berbers in Morocco]]\n[[Category:Languages of Algeria]]\n[[Category:Languages of Morocco]]\n", "name_user": "93.22.149.230", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zenati_languages"}
{"title_page": "Let the Right One In (film)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox movie\n| name           = Let the Right One In (movie)\n| image          = Let the Right One In (Swedish).jpg\n| image_size     = 215px\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Tomas Alfredson]]\n| producers      = {{Plainlist|\n* Carl Molinder\n* John Nordling\n}}\n| screenplay     = [[John Ajvide Lindqvist]]\n| based on       = {{based on|''[[Let the Right One In (novel)|Let the Right One In]]''|John Ajvide Lindqvist}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[K\u00e5re Hedebrant]]\n* [[Lina Leandersson]]\n* [[Per Ragnar]]\n* [[Ika Nord]]\n* [[Peter Carlberg]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Johan S\u00f6derqvist]]\n| cinematography = [[Hoyte van Hoytema]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* Tomas Alfredson\n* Daniel Jons\u00e4ter\n}}\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* EFTI\n* Filmpool Nord\n* [[Sveriges Television]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Sandrew Metronome]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|2008|01|26|[[Gothenburg Film Festival|Gothenburg]]|2008|10|24|Sweden}}\n| runtime        = 114 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 114:26--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://bbfc.co.uk/releases/lat-den-ratte-komma-let-right-one-film | title=Lat den ratte komma in \u2013 Let the Right One In (15) | publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=16 January 2009 | accessdate=13 December 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220220217/http://bbfc.co.uk/releases/lat-den-ratte-komma-let-right-one-film | archive-date=20 December 2016 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| country        = Sweden\n| language       = Swedish\n| budget         = {{Plainlist|\n* 29 million [[Swedish krona|kr]]\n* ([[United States dollar|$]]4.5 million)\n}}\n| gross          = $11.2 million<ref name=\"boxofficemojo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=lettherightonein.htm|title=Let the Right One In (2008)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|date=30 April 2009|accessdate=30 April 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090426020433/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=lettherightonein.htm|archive-date=26 April 2009|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n}}\n{{for|the English-language remake|Let Me In (film)}}\n'''''Let the Right One In''''' ({{lang-sv|L\u00e5t den r\u00e4tte komma in}}) is a 2008 Swedish [[Romance film|romantic]] [[horror film]] directed by [[Tomas Alfredson]], based on the 2004 [[Let the Right One In (novel)|novel of the same title]] by [[John Ajvide Lindqvist]], who also wrote the screenplay. The film tells the story of a bullied 12-year-old boy who develops a friendship with a [[vampire]] child in [[Blackeberg]], a suburb of [[Stockholm]], in the early 1980s. Alfredson, unconcerned with the [[Horror film|horror]] and [[Vampire films|vampire conventions]], decided to tone down many elements of the novel and focus primarily on the relationship between the two main characters and explore the darker side of humanity. Selecting the lead actors involved a year-long process with open castings held all over Sweden. In the end, the 11-year-olds [[K\u00e5re Hedebrant]] and [[Lina Leandersson]] were chosen for the leading roles. They were subsequently commended by both Alfredson and film reviewers for their performances.\n\nThe film received critical acclaim and won several awards, including the \"Founders Award for Best Narrative Feature\" at the 2008 [[Tribeca Film Festival]] and the [[European Fantastic Film Festivals Federation]]'s 2008 M\u00e9li\u00e8s d'Or (Golden [[Georges M\u00e9li\u00e8s|M\u00e9li\u00e8s]]) for the \"Best European Fantastic Feature Film\", as well as four [[Guldbagge Award]]s from the [[Swedish Film Institute]] and the [[Saturn Award for Best International Film]].\n\n==Plot==\n<!--Eli's gender is intentionally ambiguous. See the talk page before attempting to correct this.-->\nOskar, a meek 12-year-old boy, resides with his mother Yvonne in the western Stockholm suburb of Blackeberg in 1981. His classmates regularly [[Bullying|bully]] him, and he spends his evenings imagining revenge, collecting clippings from newspapers and magazines about grisly murders. One night he meets Eli, who appears to be a pale girl of his age. Eli has recently moved into the next-door apartment with an older man, H\u00e5kan. Eli initially informs Oskar that they cannot be friends. Over time, however, they begin to form a close relationship, with Oskar lending his [[Rubik's Cube]] to Eli, and the two exchanging [[Morse code]] messages through their adjoining wall. H\u00e5kan requests that Eli stop seeing Oskar. After questioning Oskar about a cut on his cheek, Eli learns that the boy is being bullied by schoolmates and encourages him to stand up for himself. This inspires Oskar to enroll for weight-training classes after school.\n\nEarlier, H\u00e5kan stops and kills a passerby on a busy footpath near a main road to harvest fresh blood for Eli, but he fails to return with any when he is interrupted by an approaching dog walker. Eli is prompted to waylay and kill a local man, Jocke, making his way home from a bar after having said goodnight to his best friend, Lacke. A local cat-loving recluse, G\u00f6sta, witnesses the attack from his flat. He does not believe what he has seen and decides not to report the incident. H\u00e5kan hides Jocke's body in an ice-hole in the local lake. H\u00e5kan later makes another well-prepared but incompetently executed effort to obtain blood for Eli by trapping a teenage boy in a changing room after school. The boy's friends are waiting for him to emerge, and go to see what is holding him up. Before he is discovered, H\u00e5kan pours concentrated [[hydrochloric acid]] onto his own face, disfiguring it to prevent the authorities from identifying him. Eli learns that H\u00e5kan has been taken to the hospital and scales the building to access his restricted room. H\u00e5kan opens the window for Eli and offers his neck for feeding; drained of blood, H\u00e5kan falls out of the window onto the snow and dies. Now alone, Eli goes to Oskar's apartment and spends the night with him, during which time they agree to \"go steady\". While Eli states, \"I'm not a girl\", Oskar (ambiguously) either ignores this or accepts the unclear nature of the relationship.\n\nDuring an ice skating [[field trip]] at the lake, some of Oskar's fellow students discover Jocke's body. At the same time, Oskar finally stands up to his tormentors and strikes the leader of the bullies, Conny, on the side of the head with a pole, splitting his ear. Some time later, Oskar shows Eli a private place he knows. Unaware that Eli is a vampire, Oskar suggests that they form a [[Blood brother|blood bond]], and cuts his hand, asking Eli to do the same. Eli, thirsting for blood but not wanting to harm Oskar, laps up his spilled blood before running away. Lacke's girlfriend, Virginia, is subsequently attacked by Eli. Lacke turns up in time to interrupt the attack. Virginia survives, but soon discovers that she has become painfully sensitive to sunlight. Seeking Lacke, Virginia visits G\u00f6sta, only to be fiercely attacked by G\u00f6sta's cats. In the hospital, Virginia, who has realized what she has become, asks an orderly to open the blinds in her room. When the sunlight streams in, she bursts into flames.\n\nRealizing the situation, Oskar confronts Eli, who admits to being a vampire. Oskar is initially upset by Eli's need to kill people for survival. However, Eli insists that their bloodthirsty natures are alike, in that Oskar wants to kill and Eli needs to kill, and encourages Oskar to \"be me, for a little while.\"\n\nLacke, who has lost both his best friend and girlfriend to the attacks, tracks Eli down to the closed-off apartment. Breaking in, he discovers Eli asleep in the bathtub. He prepares to kill Eli, but Oskar, who was hiding inside the apartment, interferes; Eli immediately wakes up, jumps on Lacke and kills him, feeding on his blood. Eli thanks Oskar and kisses him in gratitude. However, an upstairs neighbor is angrily knocking on the ceiling due to the disturbance the fight has caused. Eli realizes that it is no longer safe to stay and leaves the same night.\n\nThe next morning, Oskar receives a phone call from Conny's friend, Martin, who lures Oskar out to resume the after-school fitness program at the local swimming pool. The bullies, led by Conny and his [[wikt:sadism|sadistic]] older brother Jimmy, start a fire to draw Mr \u00c1vila, the teacher in charge, outside, and enter the pool area, ordering the other children to clear out. This leaves Oskar trapped alone in the pool. Jimmy forces Oskar under the water, threatening to stab his eye out if he does not hold his breath for three minutes. While Oskar is being held underwater, Eli arrives and rescues him by killing and dismembering the bullies, except for the most reluctant of their number, Andreas, who is left sobbing on a bench.\n\nLater, Oskar is traveling on a train with Eli in a box beside him, safe from sunlight. From inside, Eli taps the word \"kiss\" to Oskar in Morse code, to which he taps back \"''puss''\" (small kiss in Swedish).\n\n==Cast==\n{{Main|List of Let the Right One In characters}}\n{{castlist|\n* [[K\u00e5re Hedebrant]] as [[List of characters from Let the Right One In and Let Me In#Oskar or Owen|Oskar]]\n* [[Lina Leandersson]] as [[List of characters from Let the Right One In and Let Me In#Eli or Abby|Eli]]\n** [[Elif Ceylan]] as Eli (Voice)\n** Susanne Ruben as Aged Eli\n* [[Per Ragnar]] as [[List of characters from Let the Right One In and Let Me In#H\u00e5kan or \"The Father\"|H\u00e5kan]]\n* [[Henrik Dahl (actor)|Henrik Dahl]] as Erik\n* Karin Bergquist as Yvonne\n* [[Peter Carlberg]] as [[List of characters from Let the Right One In and Let Me In#Lacke|Lacke]]\n* [[Ika Nord]] as [[List of characters from Let the Right One In and Let Me In#Virginia|Virginia]]\n* [[Mikael Rahm]] as Jocke\n* Karl Robert Lindgren as G\u00f6sta\n* Anders T. Peedu as Morgan\n* [[Pale Olofsson]] as Larry\n* Cayetano Ruiz as Magister \u00c1vila\n* Patrik Rydmark as Conny\n* Johan S\u00f6mnes as Andreas\n* Mikael Erhardsson as Martin\n* Rasmus Luthander as Jimmy\n* S\u00f6ren K\u00e4llstigen as Erik's friend\n* Bernt \u00d6stman as Virginia's nurse\n* Kajsa Linderholm as Oskar's teacher\n* [[Frank Welker]] as Cats (Uncredited)\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[File:Blackeberg Subway.jpg|thumb|right|The characteristic subway station of [[Blackeberg]], which features in the film]]\nThe film project started in late 2004 when John Nordling, a producer at the production company EFTI, contacted [[John Ajvide Lindqvist|Ajvide Lindqvist]]'s publisher [[Ordfront]] to acquire the rights for a film adaptation of his novel, ''[[Let the Right One In (novel)|Let the Right One In]]'': \"At Ordfront they just laughed when I called, I was like the 48th they put on the list. But I called John Ajvide Lindqvist and it turned out we had the same idea of what kind of film we should make. It wasn't about money, but about the right constellation\".<ref name=\"flerbocker\">{{cite web|last=Ivarsson|first=Torbj\u00f6rn|date=8 July 2007|url=http://www.dn.se/kultur-noje/allt-fler-bocker-blir-film/|title=Allt fler b\u00f6cker blir film|language=Swedish|work=[[Dagens Nyheter]]|accessdate=2009-03-06|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170910221001/http://www.dn.se/kultur-noje/allt-fler-bocker-blir-film/|archive-date=10 September 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A friend introduced Tomas Alfredson to the novel.<ref name=\"k\u00e4rv\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bt.se/noje/tomas-alfredson-om-nya-filmen-br-skildringen-ar-oerhort-karv(958320).gm |title=Tomas Alfredson om nya filmen: \"Skildringen \u00e4r oerh\u00f6rt k\u00e4rv\" |last=Melin |first=Inger |date=7 November 2008|work=[[Bor\u00e5s Tidning]]|language=Swedish |accessdate=2009-07-16 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927183609/http://www.bt.se/noje/tomas-alfredson-om-nya-filmen-br-skildringen-ar-oerhort-karv%28958320%29.gm |archivedate=27 September 2011 }}</ref> While he normally does not like to receive books, because \"it's a private thing to choose what to read\", he decided after a few weeks to read it.<ref name=\"shock\">{{cite web | url = http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=8113#| title = 'Shock Till You Drop' Exclusive: Tomas Alfredson ''Lets the Right One In''|last=Douglas|first=Edward | date =19 October 2008|work=[[ComingSoon.net|ComingSoon]]|accessdate = 2009-07-16|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081021002518/http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=8113|archivedate=21 October 2008}}</ref> The depiction of bullying in the novel affected Alfredson deeply. \"It's very hard and very down-to-earth, unsentimental (...) I had some period when I grew up when I had hard times in school (...) So it really shook me\", he told the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.<ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite news| url = http://articles.latimes.com/2008/oct/19/entertainment/ca-indieeye19| title = Taking a deep look at horror| last = King| first = Susan| date = 19 October 2008| newspaper = [[Los Angeles Times]]| accessdate = 2009-03-14| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121005090844/http://articles.latimes.com/2008/oct/19/entertainment/ca-indieeye19| archive-date = 5 October 2012| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref> Ajvide Lindqvist already knew Alfredson's previous work,<ref name=\"shock\"/> and he and Alfredson discovered that they \"understood each other very well\".<ref name=\"k\u00e4rv\"/>\n\nIn addition to EFTI, co-producers included [[Sveriges Television]] and the regional production-centre Filmpool Nord. The production involved a total budget of around 29 million [[Swedish krona|SEK]], including support from the [[Swedish Film Institute]] and Nordisk Film- & TV Fond and WAG.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfi.se/sv/svensk-film/Filmdatabasen/?itemid=63205&type=MOVIE&iv=Company|archive-url=https://archive.today/20110614075626/http://www.sfi.se/sv/svensk-film/Filmdatabasen/?itemid=63205&type=MOVIE&iv=Company|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 June 2011|title=L\u00e5t den r\u00e4tte komma in \u2013 Bolag |publisher=[[Swedish Film Institute]] |language=Swedish|accessdate=14 June 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"IPRED\">{{cite web| url = http://www.svd.se/nyheter/inrikes/artikel_2101895.svd| title = Utan Ipred slutar vi g\u00f6ra film| last = Olsson| first = Tobias| date = 26 November 2008| work = [[Svenska Dagbladet]]| language = Swedish| accessdate = 2009-03-08| url-access = subscription| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090214112241/http://www.svd.se/nyheter/inrikes/artikel_2101895.svd| archive-date = 14 February 2009| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Screenplay===\nLindqvist had insisted on writing the screenplay himself. Alfredson, who had no familiarity with the vampire and horror genres,<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.smh.com.au/news/entertainment/film/film-reviews/let-the-right-one-in/2009/03/18/1237054900543.html| title = Let The Right One In| last = Cockrell| first = Eddie| date = 18 March 2009| work = [[Sydney Morning Herald]]| accessdate = 2009-05-09| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090421074001/http://www.smh.com.au/news/entertainment/film/film-reviews/let-the-right-one-in/2009/03/18/1237054900543.html| archive-date = 21 April 2009| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref> initially expressed skepticism at having the original author do the adaptation, but found the end result very satisfying.<ref name=\"shock\"/> Many of the minor characters and events from the book were removed, and focus directed primarily on the love story between the two leads.<ref name=\"JAL\">{{cite web|work=[[Ain't It Cool News]]|url=http://www.aintitcool.com/node/38839|title=The Northlander Sits Down With The Writer Of 'Let the Right One In'!|date=23 October 2008|accessdate=23 October 2008|author=Moriarty|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206050126/http://www.aintitcool.com/node/38839|archive-date=6 December 2008|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"huffington\">{{cite web| url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/karin-badt/emlet-the-right-one-inem_b_147966.html| title = Let the Right One In: New Vampire Film with a 'Beat'| last = Badt| first = Karin| date = 3 December 2008| work = [[HuffPost]]| accessdate = 2009-03-07| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090303103036/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/karin-badt/emlet-the-right-one-inem_b_147966.html| archive-date = 3 March 2009| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"tomas_sfi\">{{cite web|url=http://sfi.se/PageFiles/8169/L%C3%85TDENR%C3%84TTE_INTERVJU.pdf |title=Tomas&nbsp;\u2014 Den r\u00e4tte |last=Lagerstr\u00f6m |first=Louise |year=2008 |publisher=Swedish Film Institute |page=5 |language=Swedish |accessdate=2009-04-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110827022413/http://sfi.se/PageFiles/8169/L%C3%85TDENR%C3%84TTE_INTERVJU.pdf |archivedate=27 August 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In particular, many aspects of the character H\u00e5kan, including him being a [[paedophile]], were toned down, and his relationship with Eli was mostly left open to interpretation. Alfredson felt that the film could not deal with such a serious theme as pedophilia in a satisfying manner, and that this element would detract from the story of the children and their relationship.<ref name=\"tomas_sfi\" /> Still, the film provided a few hints, of which Alfredson mentions one in the director's comments (H\u00e5kan likes children, for the wrong reasons).\n\nA key passage in the novel details what happens when a vampire enters a room uninvited, an action that traditional [[Vampire|vampire lore]] usually prohibits.<ref name=\"bradshaw\">{{cite web| url = https://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/apr/10/let-the-right-one-in-vampires-film-review| title = Film Review: Let the Right One In| last = Bradshaw| first = Peter| date = 10 April 2009| work = [[The Guardian]]| accessdate = 2009-05-09| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20161231031530/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/apr/10/let-the-right-one-in-vampires-film-review| archive-date = 31 December 2016| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref> Alfredson originally wanted to omit this from the film, but Ajvide Lindqvist was adamant that it had to be included.<ref name=\"tomas_sfi\" /> Alfredson was initially nervous about the scene. He realized in post-production that the sound effects and music made it \"American, in a bad way\", and had to be removed for the scene to work.<ref name=\"DVD\">{{cite AV media notes|title=L\u00e5t den r\u00e4tte komma in|type=DVD commentary|others=K\u00e5re Hedebrant (Actor, Host) {{!}} Lina Leandersson (Actor, Host) {{!}}  Tomas Alfredson (Director, Host)|year=2009|publisher= Sandrew Metronome|language=Swedish}}</ref> The end result, which shows Eli slowly beginning to bleed from her eyes, ears, and pores, received positive notices from many critics.<ref name=\"skymovies\">{{cite web| url = http://movies.sky.com/review/let-the-right-one-in| title = Let The Right One In| last = Daniel| first = Rob| work = [[Sky Movies]]| year = 2008| accessdate = 2009-05-09| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090802015953/http://movies.sky.com/review/let-the-right-one-in| archive-date = 2 August 2009| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.reverseshot.com/article/let_right_one| title = The Pale Light of Morning| last = Yue| first = Genevieve| work = Reverse Shot| accessdate = 2009-05-09| date = 23 October 2008| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090426214628/http://www.reverseshot.com/article/let_right_one| archive-date = 26 April 2009| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.forteantimes.com/reviews/films/1628/let_the_right_one_in.html |title=Let The Right One In |last=Ogilvie |first=Jen |date=March 2009 |magazine=[[Fortean Times]] |accessdate=2009-05-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090522002421/http://www.forteantimes.com/reviews/films/1628/let_the_right_one_in.html |archivedate=22 May 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Peter Bradshaw]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' described it as a \"[[haemophilia]] of rejection\".<ref name=\"bradshaw\" />\n\nThe novel presents Eli as an [[Androgyny|androgynous]] boy, [[Castration|castrated]] centuries before by a sadistic vampire nobleman. The film handles the issue of Eli's gender more ambiguously: a brief scene in which Eli changes into a dress offers a glimpse of a suggestive scar but no explicit elaboration.<ref name=\"tomas_sfi\" /> When Oskar asks Eli to become his girlfriend, Eli tries to tell Oskar \"I'm not a girl\". An actress plays Eli's character, but her voice was considered to be too high pitched, so it was dubbed by voice actress [[Elif Ceylan]]. According to an interview with the director, as the film was originally conceived, flashbacks explained this aspect in more detail, but these scenes were eventually cut.<ref name=\"TA\">{{cite web|work=Ain't It Cool News|url=http://www.aintitcool.com/node/38870|title=Moriarty Sits Down With Tomas Alfredson, Director Of 'Let the Right One In'!|date=26 October 2008|accessdate=26 October 2008|author=Moriarty|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206101623/http://www.aintitcool.com/node/38870|archive-date=6 December 2008|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the end, Ajvide Lindqvist was satisfied with the adaptation. When Alfredson showed him eight minutes of footage for the first time, he \"started to cry because it was so damn beautiful\".<ref name=\"jal_chat\">{{cite news| url = http://www.aftonbladet.se/kultur/article3401613.ab| title = D\u00e4r vill jag vara. Bland tentaklerna.| last = Lindqvist| first = John Ajvide| date = 26 September 2008| work = [[Aftonbladet]]| language = Swedish| accessdate = 2009-07-16| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081103052852/http://www.aftonbladet.se/kultur/article3401613.ab| archive-date = 3 November 2008| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref> He subsequently described the film as a \"masterpiece\".<ref name=\"jal_chat\" /> \"It doesn't really matter that [Alfredson] didn't want to do it the way I wanted it in every respect. He could obviously never do that. The film is his creative process\", he said.<ref name=\"tomas_sfi\" />\n\n===Casting and filming===\nCasting of the lead actors took almost a year,<ref name=\"explodera\">{{cite web|last=Andersson|first=Jan-Olov|date=21 December 2008|url=http://www.aftonbladet.se/nojesbladet/article4044828.ab|title=Jag var n\u00e4ra att explodera|language=Swedish|work=[[Aftonbladet]]|accessdate=21 December 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081222104017/http://www.aftonbladet.se/nojesbladet/article4044828.ab|archive-date=22 December 2008|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"twitch_nifff\">{{cite web| url = http://twitchfilm.net/site/view/nifff-2008-let-the-right-one-in-interview/| title = NIFFF 2008 \u2013 'Let the Right One In' Interview| author = Blake| work = [[Screen Anarchy|Twitch]]| date = 24 July 2008| accessdate = 2009-03-06| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081019195004/http://twitchfilm.net/site/view/nifff-2008-let-the-right-one-in-interview/| archive-date = 19 October 2008| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref> with open castings held all over [[Sweden]]. [[K\u00e5re Hedebrant]], selected to audition for the role as Oskar after an initial screening at his school, eventually landed the role.<ref name=\"lwl\">{{cite web | url = http://www.littlewhitelies.co.uk/interviews/lina-leandersson-and-kare-%20hedebrant/| title = Lina Leandersson and Kare Hedebrant|last=Bochenski|first=Matt | date = 9 April 2009| work =[[Little White Lies (magazine)|Little White Lies]] | accessdate = 2009-04-10|archivedate=14 January 2013|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130114031318/http://www.littlewhitelies.co.uk/features/interviews/lina-leandersson-and-kare-hedebrant-4260}}</ref> [[Lina Leandersson]] responded to an online advertisement seeking a 12-year-old boy or girl \"good at running\".<ref name=\"dd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dalademokraten.se/Templates/pages/news.aspx?id=78208&epslanguage=sv |title=V\u00e4rldens hetaste vampyr |last=Lundholm |first=Johanna |date=11 July 2009|work=[[Dala-Demokraten]]|language=Swedish |accessdate=2009-07-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719092829/http://www.dalademokraten.se/Templates/pages/news.aspx?id=78208&epslanguage=sv |archivedate=19 July 2011 }}</ref> After three more auditions, she was selected to play Eli.<ref name=\"lwl\"/>\n\nAlfredson has described the casting process as the most difficult part of making the film.<ref name=\"explodera\" /> He had particular concerns about the interaction between the two leads,<ref name=\"latimes\" /> and the fact that those who had read the book would have a preconceived notion of how the characters were supposed to look.<ref name=\"alltomfilm\">{{cite web | url = http://www.alltomfilm.se/ArticlePages/200810/24/20081024135429_DVD137/20081024135429_DVD137.dbp.asp| title = Intervju med regiss\u00f6ren Thomas Alfredsson|last=Bjurvald|first=Anton | date = 24 October 2008| publisher =Allt om film|language=Swedish | accessdate = 2009-03-14 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> He wanted the actors to look innocent, and be able to interact in front of the camera. They were supposed to be \"mirror images of each other. She is everything he isn't. Dark, strong, brave, and a girl. (...) Like two sides of the same coin.\"<ref name=\"tomas_sfi\" /> On another occasion, Alfredson stated that \"[c]asting is 70 percent of the job; it's not about picking the right people to make the roles. It is about creating chords, how a B and A minor interact together, and are played together.\"<ref name=\"huffington\" /> In the end, Alfredson expressed satisfaction with the result, and has frequently lauded Hedebrant and Leandersson for being \"extremely intelligent\",<ref name=\"twitch_nifff\" /> \"incredibly wise\",<ref name=\"alltomfilm\" /> and \"unprecedentedly fantastic.\"<ref name=\"twitch_nifff\" />\n\n[[File:Lack of ceiling cropped.jpg|thumb|left|The absence of ceilings made various overhead lighting techniques possible.]]\nAlthough the film takes place in [[Blackeberg]], a suburb of [[Stockholm]], principal photography took place in [[Lule\u00e5]] (in the north of Sweden) to ensure enough snow and cold weather. The area where the filming took place dated from around the same time as Blackeberg, and has similar architecture.<ref name=\"JAL\" /> However, Alfredson shot a few scenes in the Blackeberg area. In particular, the scene where Eli leaps down on Virginia from a tree, was shot in the town square of Blackeberg.<ref name=\"DVD\" /> Another scene, where Eli attacks Jocke in an underpass, was shot in the nearby suburb of [[R\u00e5cksta]].<ref name=\"JAL\" /> The original Blackeberg underpass that Lindqvist had envisioned was deemed too high to fit in the picture.<ref name=\"DVD\" /> Some of the outdoor close-up scenes were made in a super cold studio.<ref name=\"filmthreat\">{{cite web| url = http://www.filmthreat.com/interviews/1215/| title = Frost Bite: Director Tomas Alfredson on \"Let the Right One In\"| date = 2008-10-22| publisher = [[Film Threat]]| access-date = 7 November 2014| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141107161755/http://www.filmthreat.com/interviews/1215/| archive-date = 7 November 2014| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref> The [[jungle gym]] where much of the interaction between Oskar and Eli takes place was constructed specifically for the film.<ref name=\"TA\" /> Its design was intended to suit the [[CinemaScope]] format<ref name=\"TA\" /> better than a regular jungle gym, which would typically have to be cropped height-wise.<ref name=\"DVD\" />\n\nMost of the filming used a single, fixed, [[Arriflex 535|Arri 535B]] camera, with almost no [[Handheld camera|handheld]] usage, and few cuts. Tracking shots relied on a track-mounted [[Camera dolly|dolly]], rather than [[Steadicam]], to create calm, predictable camera movement.<ref name=\"asc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ascmag.com/ac_magazine/December2008/LettheRightOneIn/page1.php|title=An Unusual Romance|last=Hemphill|first=Jim|work=[[American Cinematographer]]|publisher=[[American Society of Cinematographers]]|accessdate=2010-09-24|date=December 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716073937/http://www.ascmag.com/ac_magazine/December2008/LettheRightOneIn/page1.php|archive-date=16 July 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The crew paid special attention to lighting. Cinematographer [[Hoyte van Hoytema]] and director Alfredson invented a technique they called \"spray light\". In an interview, van Hoytema describes it as follows: \"If you could capture dull electrical light in a can and spray it like hairspray across Eli\u2019s apartment, it would have the same result as what we created\". For the emotional scenes between Oskar and Eli, van Hoytema consistently [[Soft light|diffused]] the lighting.<ref name=\"asc\" />\n\n===Post-production===\nThe film contains around fifty shots with [[computer-generated imagery]]. Alfredson wanted to make them very subtle and almost unnoticeable.<ref name=\"TA\" /> The sequence where multiple cats attack Virginia, one of the most complicated scenes to film, required several weeks of drafting and planning. The crew used a combination of real cats, stuffed cats and computer-generated imagery.<ref name=\"DVD\"/>\n\nThe film features analogue sound-effects exclusively throughout.<ref name=\"twitch_nifff\"/> The lead sound-designer Per Sundstr\u00f6m explained: \"The key to good sound effects is working with natural and real sounds.(...) These analogue sounds can be digitally reworked as much as necessary, but the origin has to be natural\".<ref name=\"alfredsonMF\"/> Sundstr\u00f6m designed the [[soundscape]] to come as close to the actors as possible, with audible heartbeats, breathing, and swallowing. Late in production it was also decided to overdub actress [[Lina Leandersson]]'s voice with a less feminine one, to underline the backstory.<ref name=\"alfredsonIFC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ifc.com/film/film-news/2008/10/tomas-alfredson-on-let-the-rig.php |title=Interview: Tomas Alfredson on 'Let the Right One In'|last=Hillis |first=Aaron |publisher=[[Independent Film Channel]] |date=29 October 2008|accessdate=2008-12-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081228220312/http://www.ifc.com/film/film-news/2008/10/tomas-alfredson-on-let-the-rig.php |archivedate=28 December 2008 }}</ref> \"She's 200 years old, not twelve. We needed that incongruity. Besides, it makes her menacing\", Sundstr\u00f6m said.<ref name=\"alfredsonMF\" /> Both men and women up to the age of forty auditioned for the role. After a vote, the film team ended up selecting Elif Ceylan, who provides all of Eli's spoken dialogue.<ref name=\"fn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.filmnyheterna.se/Arkiverade-nyheter/Nyheter/2009/Guldbaggar-for-otackt-ljud-i-Lat-den-ratte-komma-in/ |title=Guldbaggar f\u00f6r ot\u00e4ckt ljud i 'L\u00e5t den r\u00e4tte komma in' |last1=Roger |first1=Susanne |last2=Zill\u00e9n|first2=Fredrik  |date=12 January 2009|work=FilmNyheterna |language=Swedish |accessdate=2009-08-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100708193402/http://www.filmnyheterna.se/Arkiverade-nyheter/Nyheter/2009/Guldbaggar-for-otackt-ljud-i-Lat-den-ratte-komma-in |archivedate=8 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Footage of Ceylan eating melon or sausage was combined with various animal noises to emulate the sound of Eli biting into her victims and drinking their blood.<ref name=\"twitch_nifff\"/><ref name=\"alfredsonMF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.magasinetfilter.se/magasin/filter-4-08/4-08-film.aspx |title=L\u00e5t det r\u00e4tta komma ut|date=17 September 2008|publisher=Magasinet Filter |language=Swedish |accessdate=2008-12-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090215011654/http://magasinetfilter.se/magasin/filter-4-08/4-08-film.aspx |archivedate=15 February 2009 }}</ref> The sound crew won a [[Guldbagge Award]] for Best Achievement from the [[Swedish Film Institute]], for the \"nightmarishly great sound\" in the film.<ref name=\"sfi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sfi.se/en-gb/Press/Press-archive/2008-Guldbagge-Award-Winners/ |title=2008 Guldbagge Award Winners |date=1 December 2009 |publisher=Swedish Film Institute |accessdate=2009-03-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090502013311/http://www.sfi.se/en-gb/Press/Press-archive/2008-Guldbagge-Award-Winners/ |archivedate=2 May 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Soundtrack===\nSwedish composer [[Johan S\u00f6derqvist]] wrote the [[Film score|score]]. Alfredson instructed him to write something that sounded hopeful and romantic, in contrast to the events that take place in the film.<ref name=\"tomas_sfi\" /> S\u00f6derqvist has described the outcome as consisting of both darkness and light, and emphasized melody and harmony as the most important qualities of the music.<ref name=\"msm\"/> The Slovak National Symphony Orchestra performed the score; two years earlier they had performed the score for the first Swedish vampire movie, ''[[Frostbiten]]''.<ref name=\"aicnmusic\">{{cite web| url = http://www.aintitcool.com/node/39662| title = ScoreKeeper's Top 10 Best Scores Of 2008 List!!| date = 5 January 2009| work = Ain't it Cool News| accessdate = 2009-02-28| author = Merrick| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090123142132/https://www.aintitcool.com/node/39662| archive-date = 23 January 2009| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref> On 11 November 2008, [[MovieScore Media]] released the film [[soundtrack]] in a limited edition of 500 copies.<ref name=\"msm\">{{cite web | url = http://moviescoremedia.com/let-the-right-one-in-johan-soderqvist-2/ | title = Let the Right One In (Johan S\u00f6derqvist) | publisher = [[MovieScore Media]] | accessdate = 2009-02-28 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130508143741/http://moviescoremedia.com/let-the-right-one-in-johan-soderqvist-2/ | archive-date = 8 May 2013 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> It contains 21 of S\u00f6derqvist's original scores from the film.<ref name=\"msm\"/> It placed fourth on [[Ain't It Cool News]]' Top 10 Best Scores Of 2008 List, being described as \"scrupulously weaving together strains of bone-chillingly cold horror with the encompassing warmth of newly acquired love\".<ref name=\"aicnmusic\"/> [[If (magazine)|''If'' magazine]] described the score as \"the most beautifully emotional score yet to grace the undead. It\u2019s a feeling of tender melancholy that delivers its scares in a subtle, chamber orchestra way\".<ref name=\"ifmag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ifmagazine.com/feature.asp?article=3112 |title=What iF Picks: 'Let the Right One In' Is One of The Top Soundtracks To Own For November, 2008 |last=Schweiger |first=Daniel |date=20 November 2008|work=[[If (magazine)|If]]|accessdate=2009-02-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308073716/http://www.ifmagazine.com/feature.asp?article=3112 |archivedate=8 March 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe song \"Kvar i min bil\", written and performed by [[Per Gessle]], resonates repeatedly through the film. Originally an [[outtake]] from Gessle's solo album ''[[En h\u00e4ndig man]]'', the song was specially provided for the film, to resemble the sound of popular 1980s pop group [[Gyllene Tider]].<ref name=\"ajvidebok\">{{cite web|url=http://stockholm.city.se/noje/2008/10/23/_Vi_var_flera_som_ville_filma_Ajvides_bok_/ |title=Vi var flera som ville filma Ajvides bok |last=Tiselius |first=Henric |date=23 October 2008|work=[[Stockholm City (newspaper)|Stockholm City]]|language=Swedish |accessdate=2009-03-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090331150945/http://stockholm.city.se/noje/2008/10/23/_Vi_var_flera_som_ville_filma_Ajvides_bok_/ |archivedate=31 March 2009 }}</ref> Gessle has described the song as a \"bluesy tune with a nice guitar hook\".<ref name=\"blt\">{{cite news|url=http://blt.se/noje_o_kultur/hemlighetsfull-gessle-har-jobbat-i-det-tysta(896595).gm |title=Hemlighetsfull Gessle har jobbat i det tysta |last=Hylse |first=Christian |date=7 October 2008|work=Blekinge L\u00e4ns Tidning|language=Swedish |accessdate=2009-02-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20150227232838/http://web.archive.org/web/20090307150325/http://blt.se/noje_o_kultur/hemlighetsfull-gessle-har-jobbat-i-det-tysta%28896595%29.gm |archivedate=27 February 2015 }}</ref> Other songs in the film include \"F\u00f6rsonade\" from 1968, written and performed by future [[ABBA]] member [[Agnetha F\u00e4ltskog]],<ref name=\"DVD\"/> \"Flash in the Night\" from 1981, written by Tim Norell and Bj\u00f6rn H\u00e5kansson and performed by [[Secret Service (band)|Secret Service]],<ref name=\"DVD\" /> and \"Dags \u00e5 v\u00e4lja sida\" by [[Peps Persson|Peps Blodsband]].\n\n==Release==\n''Let the Right One In'' premiered at the [[Gothenburg Film Festival]] in [[Sweden]] on January 26, 2008<ref name=\"gbgiff\">{{cite web|url=https://festival.giff.se/events/let-the-right-one-in|title=L\u00e5t den r\u00e4tte komma in|publisher=[[G\u00f6teborg International Film Festival]]|accessdate=2011-03-05|year=2008|first=Marit|last=Kapla|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170915161400/https://festival.giff.se/events/let-the-right-one-in|archive-date=15 September 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> where Alfredson won the Festival's Nordic Film Prize.<ref name=\"GoteborgAward\">{{cite web|url=http://www.filmfestival.org/filmfestival/info/en/press/nyheter?itemId=163444 |title=Award ceremony at G\u00f6teborg International Film Festival's closing party |publisher=G\u00f6teborg International Film Festival|accessdate=2011-03-05 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090309064204/http://www.filmfestival.org/filmfestival/info/en/press/nyheter?itemId=163444 |archivedate=9 March 2009 }}</ref> It subsequently played at several other film festivals, including the [[Tribeca Film Festival]] in [[New York City]] (24 April 2008), where it won the Founders Award for Best Narrative Feature;<ref name=\"TribecaAward\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tribecafilm.com/home/18455719.html |title=Award Winners 2008 |publisher=[[Tribeca Film Festival]]|accessdate=2009-03-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303043905/http://www.tribecafilm.com/home/18455719.html |archivedate= 3 March 2009 }}</ref> the [[Edinburgh Film Festival]] (25 June 2008), where it won the Rotten Tomatoes Critical Consensus Award;<ref name=\"edfilmfest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.edfilmfest.org.uk/films/let-the-right-one-in/|title=Let the Right One In (L\u00e5t den R\u00e4tte Komma In)|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080830003322/http://www.edfilmfest.org.uk/films/let-the-right-one-in/|publisher=[[Edinburgh Film Festival]] |archivedate=30 August 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"RT\" /> and the [[Neuch\u00e2tel International Fantastic Film Festival]] in [[Switzerland]] (3 July 2008), where it won the M\u00e9li\u00e8s d'Argent (Silver M\u00e9li\u00e8s).<ref name=\"SilverMelies\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nifff.ch/site/en/the-festival/archives/2008|title=Neuch\u00e2tel International Fantastic Film Festival 2008|publisher=[[Neuch\u00e2tel International Fantastic Film Festival]]|accessdate=2011-03-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170915161753/http://www.nifff.ch/site/en/the-festival/archives/2008|archive-date=15 September 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\nThe Swedish premiere was originally planned for 18 April 2008, but following the positive response from the festival screenings, the producers decided to postpone the release until autumn, to allow for a longer theatrical run.<ref name=\"h\u00f6sten\">{{cite web| url = http://www.bio.nu/2008/lat-den-ratte-komma-in-till-hosten| title = L\u00e5t den r\u00e4tte komma in till h\u00f6sten| date = 21 February 2008| publisher = Bio.nu| language = Swedish| accessdate = 2009-07-27| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081023165528/http://www.bio.nu/2008/lat-den-ratte-komma-in-till-hosten/| archive-date = 23 October 2008| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref> At one time there was a plan to release the film for a special series of screenings in Lule\u00e5, beginning 24 September and lasting seven days. This was canceled when the Swedish Film Institute announced that ''[[Everlasting Moments]]'' had been selected over ''Let the Right One In'' as Sweden's submission for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]].<ref name=\"nsd_release\">{{cite web| url = http://www.nsd.se/noje/artikel.aspx?ArticleId=3997300| title = F\u00f6rhandsvisning inst\u00e4lld| language = Swedish| last = Holmberg| first = Anna| date = 23 September 2008| work = [[Norrl\u00e4ndska Socialdemokraten]]| accessdate = 2009-09-16| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080926115645/http://www.nsd.se/noje/artikel.aspx?ArticleId=3997300| archive-date = 26 September 2008| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref> The distributors released it on 24 October 2008 in Sweden, Norway, and as a limited release in the United States.<ref name=\"cineuropa\">{{cite web| url = http://cineuropa.org/newsdetail.aspx?lang=en&documentID=87398| title = ''Right One'' let into in Swedish, Norwegian and US cinemas| last = Pham| first = Annika| date = 24 October 2008| publisher = Cineuropa| accessdate = 2009-07-27| archive-url = https://archive.today/20130415001307/http://cineuropa.org/newsdetail.aspx?lang=en&documentID=87398| archive-date = 15 April 2013| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref> In Australia, the film was released on 19 March 2009.<ref name=\"filmink\">{{cite web|url=http://www.filmink.com.au/review/let-the-right-one-in-film/ |title=Let The Right One In (Film) |last=Kornel |first=Dov |date=17 April 2009|work=[[Filmink]]|accessdate=2009-04-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090319011410/http://www.filmink.com.au/review/let-the-right-one-in-film/ |archivedate=19 March 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The film was released in cinemas in the United Kingdom on 10 April 2009.<ref name=\"momentum\">{{cite web|url=http://lettherightonein.co.uk/ |title='Let The Right One In' Official Film Site |year=2009 |publisher=[[Momentum Pictures]] |accessdate=2009-04-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423205534/http://lettherightonein.co.uk/ |archivedate=23 April 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe film was released in North America on [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] in March 2009 by [[Magnolia Pictures|Magnet Films]], and in the United Kingdom in August by [[Momentum Pictures]]. The American discs feature both the original Swedish dialogue and an English [[Dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbed]] version, while the European versions feature only the Swedish, and an audio-descriptive track in English. ''Icons of Fright'' reported that the American release had been criticized for using new, oversimplified English subtitles instead of the original theatrical subtitles.<ref name=\"Fright on subtitles\">{{cite web|author=RobG|url=http://iconsoffright.com/news/2009/03/let_the_wrong_subtitles_in_to.html|title=Fright: Let The Wrong Subtitles In To 'Let the Right On In'?!|publisher=Iconsoffright.com|date=30 March 2009|accessdate=2011-03-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326042426/http://iconsoffright.com/news/2009/03/let_the_wrong_subtitles_in_to.html|archive-date=26 March 2009|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Following customer complaints, Magnet stated that they would release an updated version with the original theatrical subtitles, but will not exchange current discs.<ref name=\"Consumerist Article\">{{cite web|last=Walters |first=Chris |url=http://consumerist.com/5183800/us-distributor-of-let-the-right-one-in-says-theyll-fix-subtitles-but-no-exchanges |title=US Distributor Of 'Let The Right One In' Says They'll Fix Subtitles, But No Exchanges |work=[[Consumerist]] |date=25 March 2009|accessdate=2011-03-05|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090328103736/http://consumerist.com/5183800/us-distributor-of-let-the-right-one-in-says-theyll-fix-subtitles-but-no-exchanges|archivedate=28 March 2009}}</ref> Director Alfredson also expressed his dissatisfaction with the DVD subtitles, calling it a \"turkey translation\". \"If you look on the 'net, people are furious about how bad it is done\", he added.<ref name=\"sinnessjukt\">{{cite web| url = http://www.aftonbladet.se/nojesbladet/film/article4851576.ab| title = Det \u00e4r helt sinnessjukt| last = Triches| first = Robert| date = 8 April 2009| work = Aftonbladet| language = Swedish| accessdate = 2009-05-15| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090411024752/http://www.aftonbladet.se/nojesbladet/film/article4851576.ab| archive-date = 11 April 2009| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref> The UK release retains the theatrical subtitles.\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical reception===\n''Let the Right One In'' received widespread critical acclaim. The film has a 98% \"Certified fresh\" rating at [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 183 reviews, with an average rating of 8.28 out of 10. The critical consensus reads, \"''Let the Right One In'' reinvigorates the seemingly tired vampire genre by effectively mixing scares with intelligent storytelling\".<ref name=\"rotten\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/lat_den_ratte_komma_in|title=Let the Right One In (2008)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=6 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830134746/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/lat_den_ratte_komma_in|archive-date=30 August 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Additionally, [[Metacritic]] has reported an average score of 82 out of 100 based on 30 reviews which indicates \"universal acclaim\".<ref name=\"Meta\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/let-the-right-one-in|title='Let the Right One In' reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=2 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516232623/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/let-the-right-one-in|archive-date=16 May 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Roger Ebert cropped.jpg|thumb|[[Roger Ebert]] called the film \"The best modern vampire movie\".<ref name=\"ebert2\"/>]]\nSwedish critics generally expressed positive reactions to the film. In 26 reviews listed at the Swedish-language review site Kritiker.se it achieved an average rating of 4.1 out of 5.<ref name=\"kritiker\">{{cite web|url=http://kritiker.se/film/lat-den-ratte-komma-in/|title=L\u00e5t Den R\u00e4tte Komma In (2008)|accessdate=10 March 2009|website=Kritiker.se|language=Swedish|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160512183455/http://kritiker.se/film/lat-den-ratte-komma-in/|archive-date=12 May 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''[[Svenska Dagbladet]]'' gave the film a rating of 5 out of 6 and hailed Alfredson for his ability to \"tell [stories] through pictures instead of words about a society where hearts are turned to icicles and everyone is left on their own, but also about love warm and red like blood on white melting snow\".<ref name=\"svdb\">{{cite web|language=Swedish|work=[[Svenska Dagbladet]]|date=23 October 2008|url=http://www.svd.se/kulturnoje/film/artikel_1931441.svd|url-access=subscription|title=L\u00e5t den r\u00e4tte komma in - Bitvis h\u00e5rresande ot\u00e4ckt|quote=Men framf\u00f6rallt kan Tomas Alfredson konsten att ber\u00e4tta i bilder ist\u00e4llet f\u00f6r i ord om ett samh\u00e4lle d\u00e4r hj\u00e4rtan f\u00f6rvandlats till istappar och var och en f\u00e5r klara sig b\u00e4st den kan, men ocks\u00e5 om k\u00e4rlek som uppbrott och befrielse, k\u00e4rlek varm och r\u00f6d som blod p\u00e5 vit sm\u00e4ltande sn\u00f6|accessdate=4 April 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090302172012/http://www.svd.se/kulturnoje/film/artikel_1931441.svd|archive-date=2 March 2009|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> G\u00f6ran Everdahl for [[Sveriges Television|SVT]]'s ''Gomorron Sverige'' gave the film 4 out of 5 and described the film as \"[[kitchen sink realism|kitchen sink]] fantasy\" that \"gives the vampire story back something it has been missing for a long time: the ability to really frighten us\".<ref name=\"gomorron\">{{cite web|language=Swedish|work=Gomorron Sverige|date=23 October 2008|quote=F\u00f6rr pratade man om diskb\u00e4nksrealism&nbsp;\u2014 detta \u00e4r diskb\u00e4nksfantasy, sagans monster f\u00f6rflyttade till betongstaden. Vilket m\u00e4rkligt nog \u00e5terger vampyrstoryn n\u00e5got den saknat l\u00e4nge: kraft att verkligen skr\u00e4mma oss.|title=L\u00e5t Den R\u00e4tte Komma In}}</ref> ''[[Expressen]]'' and ''[[G\u00f6teborgs-Posten]]'' were less impressed and gave the film 3 out of 5. ''Expressen'' criticized it for being unappealing to those uninitiated in vampire films while ''G\u00f6teborgs-Posten'' believed the supporting characters had lost the emotional depth that made the novel so successful.<ref name=\"expressen\">{{cite web|work=[[Expressen]]|date=21 October 2008|url=http://www.expressen.se/noje/recensioner/film/1.1341593/blodigt-for-redan-bitna |title=Blodigt f\u00f6r redan bitna|first=Bernt|last=Eklund |accessdate=4 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081025091651/http://www.expressen.se/noje/recensioner/film/1.1341593/blodigt-for-redan-bitna |archivedate=25 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=[[G\u00f6teborgs-Posten]]|date=23 October 2009|url=http://www.gp.se/gp/jsp/Crosslink.jsp?d=257&a=453541|title=L\u00e5t Den R\u00e4tte Komma In|accessdate=4 April 2009}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nReviewers have commented on the beautiful cinematography and its quiet, restrained approach to the sometimes bloody and violent subject matter.<ref name=\"edfilm_terror\">{{cite web|url=http://www.edfilmfest.org.uk/news/view/2040/terror-incognita|title=Terror Incognita|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081020194926/http://www.edfilmfest.org.uk/news/view/2040/terror-incognita |archivedate=20 October 2008|date=29 May 2008|accessdate=29 May 2008|publisher=Edinburgh Film Festival}}</ref> KJ Doughton of [[Film Threat]] thought the visuals in the ending were fresh and inventive and would be talked about for years to come.<ref name=\"RotSIFF\">{{cite web|url=http://filmthreat.com/uncategorized/revenge-of-the-siff-2008-seattle-international-film-festival-second-week-wrap-up/|title=Revenge of the SIFF: 2008 Seattle International Film Festival Second Week Wrap-Up|work=[[Film Threat]]|date=10 June 2008|accessdate=2011-03-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170916010616/http://filmthreat.com/uncategorized/revenge-of-the-siff-2008-seattle-international-film-festival-second-week-wrap-up/|archive-date=16 September 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] gave the film 3.5 out of 4 stars, calling it a vampire movie that takes vampires seriously, drawing comparisons to ''[[Nosferatu]]'' and to ''[[Nosferatu the Vampyre]]''. He described it as a story of \"two lonely and desperate kids capable of performing dark deeds without apparent emotion\", and praised the actors for \"powerful\" performances in \"draining\" roles.<ref name=\"ebert\">{{cite news| url = http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20081111/REVIEWS/811129995| title = Let the Right One In| last = Ebert| first = Roger| date = 11 December 2008| newspaper = [[Chicago Sun-Times]]| accessdate = 2009-04-27| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120930223414/http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20081111%2FREVIEWS%2F811129995| archive-date = 30 September 2012| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref> Ebert later called the film \"The best modern vampire movie\".<ref name=\"ebert2\">{{cite news| url = http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20090812/REVIEWS/908129983| title = Thirst| last = Ebert| first = Roger| date = 13 August 2009| newspaper = [[Chicago Sun-Times]]| accessdate = 2009-12-29| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121002081904/http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20090812%2FREVIEWS%2F908129983| archive-date = 2 October 2012| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref> One negative review came from [[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', who gave the movie a \"C\", characterizing it as a \"Swedish head-scratcher\", with \"a few creepy images but very little holding them together\".<ref name=\"gleiberman\">{{cite web| url = http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20235010,00.html| title = Movie Review :: Let the Right One In| last = Gleiberman| first = Owen| date = 22 October 2008| work = [[Entertainment Weekly]]| accessdate = 2009-04-27| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090425155439/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20235010,00.html| archive-date = 25 April 2009| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Bloody Disgusting]] ranked the film first in their list of the 'Top 20 Horror Films of the Decade', with the article saying \"It\u2019s rare enough for a horror film to be good; even rarer are those that function as genuine works of art. ''Let the Right One In'' is one of those films \u2013 an austerely beautiful creation that reveals itself slowly, like the best works of art do.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/18447|title=00's Retrospect: Bloody Disgusting's Top 20 Films of the Decade...Part 4|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|accessdate=2010-01-03|date=18 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091221190351/http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/18447|archive-date=21 December 2009|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film was ranked #15 in ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'''s 2010 list of \"The 100 Best Films Of World Cinema\". In their rationale, the authors noted that, \"in these days where every second movie seems to feature vampires, it takes a very special twist on the legend to surprise us \u2013 but this one knocked us out and then bit us in the jugular\", and found that the \"strange central friendship\" between the two lead characters was what made the film \"so frightening, and so magnetic\".<ref>{{cite web| title = The 100 Best Films Of World Cinema| url = http://www.empireonline.com/features/100-greatest-world-cinema-films/default.asp?film=15| work = [[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]| date = 11 June 2010| accessdate = 13 April 2014| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140712012124/http://www.empireonline.com/features/100-greatest-world-cinema-films/default.asp?film=15| archive-date = 12 July 2014| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref> In the early 2010s, ''[[Time Out London|Time Out]]'' conducted a poll with several authors, directors, actors and critics who have worked within the horror genre to vote for their top horror films; ''Let the Right One In'' placed at number 28 on their top 100 list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/london/film/best-horror-films|work=[[Time Out London|Time Out]]|accessdate=13 April 2014|title=The 100 best horror films|first1=Tom|last1=Huddleston|first2=Cath|last2=Clarke|first3=Dave|last3=Calhoun|first4=Nigel|last4=Floyd|date=19 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120015803/http://www.timeout.com/london/film/best-horror-films|archive-date=20 January 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film was later voted the 94th greatest film since 2000 in an international critics' poll conducted by [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20160819-the-21st-centurys-100-greatest-films |title=BBC's 100 Greatest Films of the 21st Century |publisher=BBC |date=23 August 2016 |accessdate=26 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131124228/http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20160819-the-21st-centurys-100-greatest-films |archive-date=31 January 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n[[File:Tomas Alfredson at the London Premiere of Tinker Tailor Soldier Spy.png|thumb|left|Alfredson received many awards and nominations for his work on the film.]]\n\nAlfredson won the [[Gothenburg Film Festival]]'s Nordic Film Prize as director of ''Let the Right One In'' on the grounds that he \"succeeds to transform a vampire movie to a truly original, touching, amusing and heart-warming story about friendship and marginalisation\".<ref name=\"GoteborgAward\" /> ''Let the Right One In'' was nominated in five categories for the [[Swedish Film Institute]]'s 2008 [[Guldbagge Award]], eventually winning for best directing, screenplay and cinematography as well as a Best Achievement-award to production designer Eva Nor\u00e9n.<ref name=\"sfi_gb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sfi.se/en-gb/Press/Press-archive/2008-Guldbagge-Award-Winners/|title=2008 Guldbagge Award Winners|publisher=Swedish Film Institute|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090502013311/http://www.sfi.se/en-gb/Press/Press-archive/2008-Guldbagge-Award-Winners/ |archivedate=2 May 2009|date=12 January 2009|accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref> In awarding the film the \"Founders Award for Best Narrative Feature\", the top award at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]], the jury described the film as a \"mesmerizing exploration of loneliness and alienation through masterful reexamination of the vampire myth\".<ref name=\"TribecaAward\" /> The film also won the M\u00e9li\u00e8s d'Argent (Silver M\u00e9li\u00e8s) at the Swiss [[Neuch\u00e2tel International Fantastic Film Festival]]<ref name=\"SilverMelies\" /> (NIFFF) and went on to win the M\u00e9li\u00e8s d'Or (Golden M\u00e9li\u00e8s) for the \"Best European Fantastic Feature Film\", awarded by the [[European Fantastic Film Festivals Federation]] of which NIFFF is a part.<ref name=\"GoldenMelies\">{{cite web|url=http://www.melies.org/filer/Press_meliesdOr_eng.pdf |title=Press Release M\u00e9li\u00e8s d'Or 2008 |last=Hallman |first=Christian |date=2008-10-09 |publisher=[[Neuch\u00e2tel International Fantastic Film Festival|Swiss Neuch\u00e2tel International Fantastic Film Festival]]|accessdate=2009-03-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720081636/http://www.melies.org/filer/Press_meliesdOr_eng.pdf |archivedate=20 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Other awards include the first [[Rotten Tomatoes]] Critical Consensus Award at the Edinburgh Film Festival.<ref name=\"RT\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/lat_den_ratte_komma_in/news/1737665/rotten_tomatoes_critical_consensus_award_2008_presented |title=Rotten Tomatoes: Rotten Tomatoes Critical Consensus Award 2008 Presented |website= Rotten Tomatoes |date=27 June 2008|accessdate=2011-03-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090514085012/http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/lat_den_ratte_komma_in/news/1737665/rotten_tomatoes_critical_consensus_award_2008_presented |archivedate=14 May 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nDespite being an internationally successful film, ''Let the Right One In'' was not submitted by Sweden for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]. The details surrounding the film's eligibility for the award resulted in some confusion.<ref name=\"sfi_oscar\">{{cite web|url=http://www.filmnyheterna.se/en/Arkiverade-nyheter/Nyheter/2009/Darforvar-Lat-den-ratte-inte-valbar/ |title=D\u00e4rf\u00f6r var \"L\u00e5t den r\u00e4tte\" inte valbar |language=Swedish |last=Zill\u00e9n |first=Fredrik |date=16 September 2009|work=Filmnyheterna |publisher=Swedish Film Institute|accessdate=2010-06-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008225403/http://www.filmnyheterna.se/en/Arkiverade-nyheter/Nyheter/2009/Darforvar-Lat-den-ratte-inte-valbar/ |archivedate=8 October 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Being released on 24 October 2008, the film would normally be eligible for submission for the [[82nd Academy Awards]]. However, the producers decided to release it on 24 September as a seven-day limited run only in [[Lule\u00e5]]. This would be exactly enough to meet the criteria for the [[81st Academy Awards]] instead.<ref name=\"sfi_oscar\"/> When the Swedish Film Institute on 16 September announced that [[Jan Troell]]'s ''[[Everlasting Moments]]'' had been selected instead of ''Let the Right One In'', the Lule\u00e5 screenings were cancelled. Despite the fact that the film was released within the eligibility period for the 82nd Academy Awards, it wasn't among the films considered because the Swedish Film Institute doesn't allow a film to be considered twice.<ref name=\"sfi_oscar\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Date of ceremony\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Recipient(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[Imagine Film Festival|Amsterdam Fantastic Film Festival]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 16 \u2013 25 April 2009\n| Silver Scream Award\n| rowspan=\"2\" |  {{sort|Alfredson|[[Tomas Alfredson]]}}\n| {{won}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|<ref name=\"imagine\">{{cite web|url=http://imaginefilmfestival.com/about-imagine/awards|title=Imagine Film Festival: Jury's and Awards|publisher=[[Imagine Film Festival]]|accessdate=5 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160504100756/http://imaginefilmfestival.com/about-imagine/awards|archive-date=4 May 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| Black Tulip Award\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|[[Austin Fantastic Fest]]\n| 2009\n| Best Horror Feature\n!\n| {{won}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref name=\"austinff\">{{cite web| url =https://www.austinchronicle.com/daily/screens/2008-09-23/fantastic-fest-award-winners-announced/| title =Fantastic Fest Award Winners Announced| last =Jones| first =Kimberley| date =23 September 2008| work =[[Austin Chronicle]]| accessdate =2009-04-27| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20171118175406/https://www.austinchronicle.com/daily/screens/2008-09-23/fantastic-fest-award-winners-announced/| archive-date =18 November 2017| url-status =live| df =dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|[[Austin Film Critics Association]]\n| [[Austin Film Critics Association Awards 2008|16 December 2008]]\n| Best Foreign Language Film\n!\n| {{won}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref name=\"afca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.austinfilmcritics.org/2008.html |title=2008 Awards |publisher=[[Austin Film Critics Association]] |accessdate=2009-04-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090418040453/http://austinfilmcritics.org/2008.html |archivedate=18 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|[[Australian Film Critics Association]]\n| 2009\n| Best Foreign Language Film\n!\n| {{won}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fcca.com.au/award-archive/|title=Awards Archive|publisher=[[Australian Film Critics Association]]|accessdate=2009-04-27|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140125092626/http://fcca.com.au/award-archive/|archive-date=25 January 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Boston Society of Film Critics Awards]]\n| [[29th Boston Society of Film Critics Awards|14 December 2008]]\n| [[Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Foreign Language Film]]\n!\n| {{won}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref name=\"bsfc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thebsfc.org/CurrWin.html |title=Boston Society of Film Critics Awards 2008 Winners |publisher=[[Boston Society of Film Critics]] |accessdate=2009-04-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090216214508/http://thebsfc.org/CurrWin.html |archivedate=