onships |newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]] |accessdate=11 November 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112030431/http://www.hindustantimes.com/sports-news/OtherSports/Babita-clinches-bronze-in-World-Championships/Article1-937328.aspx |archivedate=12 November 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Babita Phogat entered politics by joining the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/babita-phogat-mahavir-phogat-join-bjp/articleshow/70640714.cms|title=Babita Phogat and Mahavir Phogat join BJP}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life and family ==\n{{see|Phogat sisters}}\nBabita is the younger sister of [[Geeta Phogat]], who won India's first gold medal in women's wrestling at the [[India at the Commonwealth Games|Commonwealth Games]]. Babita is the daughter of wrestler and [[Dronacharya Award]] recipient [[Mahavir Singh Phogat]]. She has a cousin [[Vinesh Phogat]] who also won gold, in the 48&nbsp;kg category, at the [[2014 Commonwealth Games|Commonwealth Games]] in [[Glasgow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/lifestyle/report-meet-the-medal-winning-phogat-sisters-2009485|title=Meet the medal winning Phogat sisters}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/wrestling-coach-mahavir-phogat-overlooked-for-dronacharya-award/15523177|title=Wrestling coach Mahavir Phogat overlooked for Dronacharya Award}}</ref><ref name=JATni1>[https://www.femina.in/achievers/the-success-of-the-phogat-sisters-geeta-babita-and-vinesh-all-wrestling-champs-is-a-story-worth-emulating-7019.html The Powerhouse Phogat Siblings and their Cousin - Deeta, Babita and Vinesh], Femina.</ref> \n\nBabita, along with her sister and cousin, have contributed to a change in mindset and attitude towards girls and women in their village in Haryana.<ref>{{Cite web|title = \u2018Phogat sisters\u2019 build their legacy in wrestling|url = http://www.sunday-guardian.com/sports/phogat-sisters-build-their-legacy-in-wrestling|website = www.sunday-guardian.com|accessdate = 2015-11-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Meet the medal winning Phogat sisters  {{!}} Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis|url = http://www.dnaindia.com/lifestyle/report-meet-the-medal-winning-phogat-sisters-2009485|website = dna|accessdate = 2015-11-02}}</ref>\n\nHer youngest sister, [[Ritu Phogat]], too is an international level wrestler and has won a gold medal at the 2016 [[Commonwealth Wrestling Championship]]. Her younger sister, [[Sangita Phogat]] is also a wrestler.\n\nIn June 2019, she announced her engagement to fellow wrestler Vivek Suhag.  <ref>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/off-the-field/babita-phogat-all-set-to-get-married/articleshow/69662051.cms?from=mdr</ref>\n\nBabita Phogat joined the BJP on Monday 12 August 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/babita-phogat-mahavir-phogat-join-bjp/articleshow/70640714.cms|title=Babita Phogat and Mahavir Phogat join BJP}}</ref>\n\n== Television ==\nBabita participated in [[Nach Baliye|Nach Baliye 2019]] with her fiancee/boyfriend [[Nach Baliye|Vivek Suhag]]. They later got married in November 2019.\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== 2009 Commonwealth Wrestling Championship ===\nIn the tournament in Jalandhar, Punjab, Babita won the gold medal in the women's freestyle 51&nbsp;kg category.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|title = Home|url = http://commonwealthwrestling.sharepoint.com/Pages/default.aspx|website = commonwealthwrestling.sharepoint.com|accessdate = 2015-11-02|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130419030013/http://commonwealthwrestling.sharepoint.com/Pages/default.aspx|archive-date = 19 April 2013|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n=== 2010 Commonwealth Games ===\nAt the [[2010 Commonwealth Games]], Babita won the silver medal in the women's freestyle 51&nbsp;kg category after being defeated by Ifeoma Christi Nwoye of [[Nigeria at the 2010 Commonwealth Games|Nigeria]] in the gold medal match with the score of 0\u20132, 4\u20135.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.webindia123.com/news/articles/India/20101009/1605354.html |author=Chetan Sharma |title=CWG wrestling: Anita, Alka win gold, Babita bags silver |publisher=Web India |place=[[New Delhi]] |date=8 October 2010 |accessdate=20 November 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141120051345/http://news.webindia123.com/news/articles/India/20101009/1605354.html |archivedate=20 November 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== 2011 Commonwealth Wrestling Championship ===\nIn the tournament held in Melbourne, Australia, Babita won the gold medal in the women's freestyle 48&nbsp;kg category.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n=== 2012 World Wrestling Championships ===\nIn the Round of 16 of the [[2012 World Wrestling Championships]], Babita faced Hsin-Ju Chiu of [[Chinese Taipei|Taipei]] whom she beat 5:0. Her quarter-finals opponent was [[Risako Kawai]] of Japan whom she beat 5:0 to qualify for the semi-finals. She lost 1:3 to Jessica Anne Marie MacDonald of [[Canada]] in the semi-finals. She was then able to contest for the bronze medal which she won in the women's freestyle 51&nbsp;kg category by beating [[Zamira Rakhmanova]] of [[Russia]] 5:0.<ref>{{Cite web|title = International Wrestling Database|url = https://www.iat.uni-leipzig.de/datenbanken/dbfoeldeak/daten.php?spid=5B20BF0196054A34B13C651708FB10F2&kaempfe=1&wkid=5C1651E110F442DFA77C02306036C83C&gkl=2&spid=5B20BF0196054A34B13C651708FB10F2|website = www.iat.uni-leipzig.de|accessdate = 2015-11-02|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20161226145633/https://www.iat.uni-leipzig.de/datenbanken/dbfoeldeak/daten.php?spid=5B20BF0196054A34B13C651708FB10F2&kaempfe=1&wkid=5C1651E110F442DFA77C02306036C83C&gkl=2&spid=5B20BF0196054A34B13C651708FB10F2|archive-date = 26 December 2016|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013 Asian Wrestling Championships ===\nAt the [[2013 Asian Wrestling Championships]] tournament in New Delhi, India, Babita won the bronze medal in the women's freestyle 55&nbsp;kg category along with [[Han Kum-ok]] of [[North Korea]].\n\n=== 2014 Commonwealth Games ===\nIn the women's freestyle 55&nbsp;kg category at the [[2014 Commonwealth Games]], Babita's first opponent in the quarter-finals was Kathryn Marsh of [[Scotland at the 2014 Commonwealth Games|Scotland]] whom she beat 9\u20132, 4\u20130 (classification points 4:1). Her opponent in the semi-finals was [[Louisa Porogovska]] of [[England at the 2014 Commonwealth Games|England]] whom she beat 2\u20130 (classification points 5:0) \u2013 victory by [[Pin (amateur wrestling)|fall]] (wrestling terminology). In the gold medal bout, she was up against [[Brittanee Laverdure]] of [[Canada at the 2014 Commonwealth Games|Canada]] whom she beat 5\u20130, 4\u20132 (classification points 3:1) to win the gold medal.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Glasgow 2014 \u2013 Babita Kumari Profile|url = http://g2014results.thecgf.com/athlete/cycling_road/1021846/babita_kumari.html|website = g2014results.thecgf.com|accessdate = 2015-11-02}}</ref>\n\n=== 2014 Asian Games ===\nBabita was not able to repeat her Commonwealth Games feat at the [[2014 Asian Games]] in [[Incheon]], South Korea. In the Round of 16 of the women's freestyle 55&nbsp;kg category, she faced Srey Mao Dorn of [[Mongolia at the 2014 Asian Games|Mongolia]] whom she beat 5:0. In the quarter-finals, she faced Aiym Abdildina of [[Kazakhstan at the 2014 Asian Games|Kazakhstan]] whom she beat 3:1. She lost 0:4 to Olympic champion [[Saori Yoshida]] of [[Japan at the 2014 Asian Games|Japan]] in the semi-finals. She was able to contest for the bronze medal but lost 1:3 to her opponent Xuechun Zhong of [[China at the 2014 Asian Games|China]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Athletes_Profile {{!}} Biographies {{!}} Sports|url = http://www.incheon2014ag.org/Sports/Biographies/Athletes_Profile/?ParticCode=5108759&lang=en|website = www.incheon2014ag.org|accessdate = 2015-11-02}}{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n=== 2015 Asian Wrestling Championships ===\nBabita defeated Abdy Kadyrova Elsa of [[Kyrgyzstan]] 10\u20130 in the quarterfinal of the [[2015 Asian Wrestling Championships]], after getting the better of Zukhra Mustanova of [[Uzbekistan]] by the same margin in the qualification round. Babita failed to enter the final as she lost her semifinal bout to Pak Yong-Mi of [[North Korea]], losing in the last five seconds.\n\nWith a chance for a podium finish, Babita lost to Zhuldyz Eshimova-Turtbayeva of [[Kazakhstan]] 3\u20136 in the bronze medal play-off.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Sakshi Malik, Lalita Win Bronze in Asian Wrestling Championship|url = http://sports.ndtv.com/wrestling/news/241842-sakshi-malik-lalita-win-bronze-in-asian-wrestling-championship|website = NDTVSports.com|accessdate = 2015-11-02|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150923230601/http://sports.ndtv.com/wrestling/news/241842-sakshi-malik-lalita-win-bronze-in-asian-wrestling-championship|archive-date = 23 September 2015|url-status = dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Indian Wrestlers Fail to Make a Mark in World Wrestling Championships|url = http://sports.ndtv.com/wrestling/news/248351-indian-wrestlers-fail-to-make-a-mark-in-world-wrestling-championships|website = NDTVSports.com|accessdate = 2015-11-02|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304084110/http://sports.ndtv.com/wrestling/news/248351-indian-wrestlers-fail-to-make-a-mark-in-world-wrestling-championships|archive-date = 4 March 2016|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016 Rio Olympics ===\nBabita became the third and final entry from India in the women's wrestling for the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]]. She represented India along with her cousin [[Vinesh Phogat]]. She qualified for the Rio Games after her opponent failed a doping test in the qualifying tournament and the quota was given to India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/other-sports/ravinder-khatri-babita-kumari-bag-rio-berths-take-indian-wrestlers-count-to-8/story-y4q94uRS42lUrgajLQ051N.html|title=Khatri, Babita bag Rio berths, take Indian wrestlers\u2019 count to 8|date=11 May 2016|publisher=|accessdate=18 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nBabita lost in the first round 1\u20135.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.firstpost.com/sports/babita-kumari-loses-her-wrestling-bout-bows-out-of-rio-olympics-2016-2964006.html|title=Babita Kumari loses her wrestling bout, bows out of Rio Olympics 2016 \u2013 Firstpost|date=2016-08-18|newspaper=Firstpost|language=en-US|access-date=2016-10-21}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018 Gold Coast Commonwealth Games ===\nBabita Kumari Phogat won the Silver medal in women\u2019s 53kg freestyle wrestling at [[2018 Commonwealth Games]] in [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]]. \n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/commonwealth-games/cwg-2018-live-india-wrestling-live-streaming-5133842/|title=CWG 2018, Wrestling highlights: Sushil Kumar, Rahul Aware win gold medal; Babita Kumari wins silver; Kiran wins bronze|date=12 April 2018|publisher=|accessdate=12 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Popular culture==\nThe film ''[[Dangal (film)|Dangal]]'' loosely based on the story of her and her sister which released on 23 December 2016. Babita was portrayed by [[Sanya Malhotra]] and her younger self by Suhani Bhatnagar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/aamir-khan-to-play-mahavir-phogat-in-dangal-meets-his-wrestler-daughters-geeta-and-babita/|title=Aamir Khan to play Mahavir Phogat in Dangal, meets his wrestler daughters Geeta and Babita}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/this-is-how-aamir-is-preparing-for-his-role-in-dangal/article1-1374639.aspx|title=This is how Aamir is preparing for his role in Dangal}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodmantra.com/news/ranbir-kapoor-karan-johar-visit-aamir-khan-post-his-injury/19925/|title=Ranbir Kapoor, Karan Johar visit Aamir Khan post his injury|publisher=Bollywood Mantra|accessdate=25 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nShe joined the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] in August 2019.<ref>https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/babita-phogat-father-mahavir-join-bjp-today-1579927-2019-08-12</ref> She lost to BJP rebel Sombir in October 2019 in Haryana assembly elections from [[Dadri (Vidhan Sabha constituency)]]. <ref>https://punemirror.indiatimes.com/news/india/haryana-assembly-elections-wrestler-babita-phogat-loses-to-bjp-rebel-sombir-sangwan-in-dadri/articleshow/71741970.cms</ref>\n\n== Other titles ==\n* Dave Schultz Memorial Tournament, 2010 \u2013 Sixth place<ref>{{Cite web|title = International Wrestling Database|url = https://www.iat.uni-leipzig.de/datenbanken/dbfoeldeak/daten.php?wkid=4D4D5650AA2C40E582969A8CE29E8D8F&gkl=3|website = www.iat.uni-leipzig.de|accessdate = 2015-11-02}}</ref>\n* Dave Schultz Memorial Tournament, 2012 \u2013 Bronze<ref>{{Cite web|title = International Wrestling Database|url = https://www.iat.uni-leipzig.de/datenbanken/dbfoeldeak/daten.php?wkid=AB9A3B6CDA6649B584CC26682127DC26&gkl=2|website = www.iat.uni-leipzig.de|accessdate = 2015-11-02}}</ref>\n* Dave Schultz Memorial Tournament, 2014 \u2013 Silver<ref>{{Cite web|title = International Wrestling Database|url = https://www.iat.uni-leipzig.de/datenbanken/dbfoeldeak/daten.php?wkid=33FFD2A122E54748B488A4F70AB7ADEF&gkl=3|website = www.iat.uni-leipzig.de|accessdate = 2015-11-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://unitedworldwrestling.org/DATABASE Babita Kumari \u2013 FILA database]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kumari, Babita}}\n[[Category:Indian female sport wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Sportswomen from Haryana]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Wrestlers at the 2010 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games silver medallists for India]]\n[[Category:Wrestlers at the 2014 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games gold medallists for India]]\n[[Category:Wrestlers at the 2014 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:World Wrestling Championships 